<HEADLINE> Greece Calls for Peaceful Solution to Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Greece Tuesday called for a
peaceful solution to the current ethnic conflict in Yugoslavia's
autonomous province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Dimitris Reppas told a press conference
that Athens was concerned over the Kosovo crisis and hoped to end
it through dialogue with respect to the rights of ethnic Albanians
and the unity and sovereignty of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
He said Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis had discussed the
issue with his Albanian counterpart Fatos Nano by telephone, and
Foreign Undersecretary Yiannos Kranidiotis had also met with the
Yugoslav embassy's charge d'affairs in Athens.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman described Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos's coming visit to Belgrade, scheduled on Friday, as "a
good opportunity" for further consultations.
</P>
<P>
Tension in Kosovo heightened on March 1 after an escalation of
a larger armed conflict between Serbian police and local ethnic
Albanians, during which four policemen and 16 Albanians were
killed with another two policemen injured.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo has a 90 percent ethnic Albanian majority which has been
seeking independence from Yugoslavia since 1981.
</P>
<P>
Greece has said that it opposed Kosovo's independence from
Yugoslavia and respected the borders of Yugoslavia, coupled with
prospects for wide-ranging autonomy for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In January, Greece offered to host a meeting between Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic, Albanian Prime Minister Nano and the
leader of the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, Ibrahim Rugova, to help
resolve the Kosovo problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
