<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Chief: Israel Attempts to Evade UN Resolutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary General
Esmat Abdel-Meguid said Tuesday that Israel's proposal to withdraw
from south Lebanon is intended to bypass U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"The Likud move is an attempt to evade legitimate (U.N.)
resolutions and draw attention away from its continued violation
of U.N. Security Council resolutions on the Middle East in general
and the Palestinian cause in particular," the AL chief told the
Egypt's Middle East News Agency (MENA).
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid pointed out that the Israeli suggestion to pull
out of south Lebanon if security is guaranteed by the Lebanese
government, "completely runs contrary" to the Security Council
Resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
"The resolution clearly stipulates full Israeli withdrawal from
south Lebanon and western Bekaa and Lebanon's complete sovereignty
over its lands," he added, quoted by MENA.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, adopted in 1978 after Israel first invaded
Lebanon, calls on it to "immediately cease military action against
the integral territory of Lebanon and to withdraw its forces
without delay from all Lebanese territory."
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said on Sunday that
Israeli troops were prepared to withdraw from south Lebanon on
condition that Beirut cooperates on security arrangements in the
area.
</P>
<P>
He said Israel did not want a "unilateral withdrawal which
would increase Hezbollah attacks in northern Israel."
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer "security zone" in south
Lebanon in 1985 to protect its northern residents from cross
border guerrilla attacks. The Lebanese resistance movement has
been fighting to end Israeli occupation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
