<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's New Cabinet Criticized by Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 3 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's opposition Grand
National Party (GNP) said the cabinet members appointed Tuesday by
President Kim Dae-jung are unqualified for their posts.
</P>
<P>
Most members of the new cabinet are old faces short of
administrative experience and professional expertise needed for
their jobs, said the GNP, which occupies 161 seats at the
299-member National Assembly, or parliament.
</P>
<P>
President Kim assigned 12 of the 17 cabinet posts to members of
his National Congress for New Politics (NCNP) and its coalition
partner, the United Liberal Democrats (ULD).
</P>
<P>
The appointment of the 12 politicians shows that President Kim
did not take the candidates' professional expertise into
consideration and failed to recruit new figures, spokesman Maeng
Hyung-kyu for the GNP said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The appointments had been delayed by legal disputes over the
nomination of Kim Jong-pil as prime minister. Kim Jong-pil was
finally named as acting prime minister in the new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the ruling camp defended President Kim, saying
that he appointed the politicians so that they can support his
reform programs when the nation has been sustaining a deepening
financial crisis and political instability.
</P>
<P>
"The president also considered the fact that the National
Assembly is controlled by the opposition," Kim's spokesman Park
Jie-won said. And Kim made the choice so that his minority ruling
coalition parties can maintain a wider political base.
</P>
<P>
He said the president tried to ensure a balance in the regional
background of the candidates by appointing five each from the
southwestern Cholla and southeastern Kyongsang areas.
</P>
<P>
Kim Dae-jung is the first president from South Korea's
southwestern part, whose people say they have been discriminated
against by a succession of governments headed by people from the
southeast.
</P>
<P>
Of the 17 cabinet ministers appointed, six are in their 60s, 10
in 50s, and one in 40s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
