<HEADLINE> Greece Urges EU to Pressure Turkey Ahead of Cyprus' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Greece Tuesday urged the European
Union (EU) to exert more pressure upon neighboring Turkey and
northern Cyprus ahead of the beginning of Cyprus' accession talks
with the EU.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made by Greek government spokesman Dimitris
Reppas while commenting on the recent statements by Turkish Deputy
Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit and Turkish Cypriots leader Rauf
Denktash calling for recognition of the northern Cyprus, which
unilaterally declared independent in 1983, but it has been
recognized by no countries except Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the two men for repeating their desires and
subverting the framework set for the resolution of the Cyprus
problem by the international community.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops occupied
the northern third of the island in the wake of an abortive coup
supported by Athens.
</P>
<P>
The EU decided last year to include Cyprus to the list of
countries waiting to join the group, and the accession
negotiations will begin this year, but his did lead to the
opposition by northern Cyprus and its supporter Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Greece has expressed its opposition to the equal participation
of Turkish Cypriots in Cyprus' accession talks with the EU, saying
that it wants them to be involved in the negotiations with two
conditions, namely this would not lead to the recognition of
northern Cyprus and not create obstacles to the island's accession
to the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
