<HEADLINE> France Welcomes UN Resolution, Sends Envoy to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- France Tuesday welcomed the newly
adopted United Nations Security Council resolution on Iraq, and
sent a presidential envoy to Baghdad in a further step to push
Iraq fully implement its agreement with U.N. Secretary-General.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret said
that the U.N. Resolution 1154 is "very balanced" and France is
"entirely satisfied" with it.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman said that the resolution "excludes any idea of
automatic strike" against Iraq if it fails to implement its
agreement with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
"Our position is clear: It is for the Security Council to
evaluate the behavior of a country, in this case Iraq, to make if
need be the statement of possible violations and fix in
consequence the decisions," she said.
</P>
<P>
The secretary general of the French Foreign Ministry Bertrand
Dufourcq, who is carrying a letter from President Jacques Chirac
to Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, is expected to arrive in
Baghdad Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
"In the wake of the Security Council vote, the envoy of
President Chirac will stress the importance France pays to the
complete and rapid application of the agreement reached on
February 23... which is adopted by the Resolution 1154," said the
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Chirac said that Iraq has the right to return to
the international community on the condition that it plays the
game according to the rule.
</P>
<P>
"The envoy will also raise the perspective of the lifting of
sanctions as soon as Baghdad has fulfilled its obligation in terms
of elimination of weapons of mass destruction," she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
