<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Employees Continue Strike Across Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Major Kenyan banks remained
closed Tuesday, the fourth day of the strike of bank employees
who demand an immediate scrapping of the newly-introduced
low-interest benefit tax.
</P>
<P>
The Standard Bank Ltd, Barclays Bank, Commercial Bank of Kenya,
Development Bank of Kenya, Delphis Bank, Blashara Bank, and Post
Bank were all closed with a notice saying they could not operate
due to the strike by a number of their employees.
</P>
<P>
More than two hundred people formed long queues under the hot
sun outside the National Bank of Kenya, which still opened but
"extremely goes slow" because of lack of enough staff, an
eyewitness told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
It was said about 50 affiliate members of the Kenya Union of
Commercial Food and Allied Workers took part in the strike
Tuesday, putting more pressures on the government as customers
were suffering.
</P>
<P>
The Central Organization of Trade Unions (COTU) and the Kenya
National Chamber of Commerce and Industry have asked the
government to quickly resolve the dispute, warning the strike
could bring the economy to a "grinding halt."
</P>
<P>
The strikers were demanding the government to quickly rescind
the new 22 percent interest rate imposed on employees' loans and
allowances, saying the tax contradicted the government's policy
of asking bankers to lower their interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Most branches of the 53-member Kenya Bankers Association have
took part in the strike since last Friday across the east African
country.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of All Banks Shopstewards Committee (ABSC) Jacob
Opiyo, at the beginning of the strike, vowed that
employees of all banks would continue with the strike until the
Ministry of Finance scrapped the new tax rates.
</P>
<P>
However, the Kenya Revenue Authority (KRA) Friday accused the
ABSC of misleading its members, saying that under the Income Tax
Act, the general policy in Kenya has always been that all
remuneration provided to employees are taxable.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Friday, the KRA said that the 22 percent
rate is far below what the Kenyan public is paying for commercial
loans where the interest ranges between 30 and 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
The tussle between the government and bank employees on the
issue of taxation has been going on for the last seven years.
</P>
<P>
The new rate of tax ranging from 15 percent to 22 percent is
based on the average 91-day treasury bill rate for the relevant
quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
