<HEADLINE> Nepali PM Aircraft Makes Emergency Landing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A Nepali aircraft carrying Prime
Minister Surya Bahadur Thapa Tuesday made a safe emergency landing
at the capital's international airport, the official RSS news
agency said.
</P>
<P>
The plane took off at 10:30 a.m. for Biratnagar, about 250
kilometers southeast of Kathmandu. Thapa was flying there to
inaugurate a seminar, the RSS said.
</P>
<P>
But the plane could not land in Biratnagar because its nose
wheel developed a technical snag. As the airport there has no
emergency landing facilities, the plane flew back to Kathmandu.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft landed at the Tribhuvan International Airport,
suffering some damage, the RSS said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister and 48 other passengers were evacuated
without injuries, it added.
</P>
<P>
It said a nine-member committee is investigating the accident.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft belongs to a private airline in Nepal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
