<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Welcomes Security Council Resolution on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The British government expressed
endorsement here Tuesday to the U.N. Security Council Resolution
on Iraq and warned that severe consequences will follow if Baghdad
fails to comply with the resolution.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said in a statement issued
Tuesday afternoon that Britain "Welcomes Security Council
Resolution 1154 adopted overnight in New York. It is a clear
endorsement by the United Nations of the agreement made by
Secretary General (Kofi Annan) during his recent visit to Iraq".
</P>
<P>
"The Resolution is an expression of the Security Council's
determination to ensure full Iraqi compliance with all the U.N.
Resolutions in place to deal with Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Cook, whose country is the staunchest American ally in the
latest U.N.-Iraq crisis, warned: "Should Saddam break his
agreement with the United Nations, the Resolution makes clear that
severest consequences will follow."
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a BBC Radio interview, Cook said: "The ball is now
in Saddam Hussein's court. If he wants to return normality to the
lives of people in Iraq all he has to do is to comply with the
undertakings he has given."
</P>
<P>
"But if he breaks them, then there will be entirely different
consequences," Cook added. But he declined to spell out what
action might be contemplated should Iraq again flaunt the United
Nation's wishes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a spokesman for Prime Minister Tony Blair told
reporters that British troops in the Gulf Region will remain in
combat position until it was clear that Iraq would accept the
latest U.N. Resolution on Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
