<HEADLINE> Crop Yields Drop Sharply in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Major crops from the January
harvest in Somalia have been drastically reduced by heavy rains
and floods caused by the El Nino weather phenomenon, said
a World Food Program (WFP) harvest assessment report.
</P>
<P>
Maize production has fallen to an alarming 11 percent of last
year's so-called Deyr harvest, while the overall sorghum crop
dropped by half, said the report issued here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"A normal level of production is 20 times greater than the
current harvest. War, drought and now floods have made this level
of production impossible," Burk Oberle, WFP Country Director for
Somalia, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Although farmers cultivated more land last year, the harvest
was almost destroyed by torrential rains and widespread flooding
of the rivers," Oberle noted.
</P>
<P>
"People in the Lower Juba and Shabelle areas are still
suffering intensely, and will need our help until at least June
when the next harvest starts to come in," he continued.
</P>
<P>
The WFP is currently operating one C-130 Hercules, one Buffalo
aircraft, one helicopter and two boats for the Somalia operation.
Since the end of November last year, it has delivered 7,200 tons
of food to the Somali flood victims.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. agency also made appeals last month for 12.8 million
U.S. Dollars for the emergency flood operation in southern
Somalia. Now the shortfall totals four million Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
