<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Situation in Zimbabwe Remains Calm Despite Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Situation in Zimbabwe is calm
despite the country's trade union Tuesday started its two-day
national mass stay-away from work, the Zimbabwean News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Most of the urban centers in the country were closed Tuesday
as workers heeded a call from the Zimbabwe Congress of Trade
Unions (ZCTU) to stay at home for two days in protest against
rising prices of basic commodities and unpopular government taxes
and levies.
</P>
<P>
The central business district in the capital Harare came to a
standstill. Most banks and schools were closed with heavy
presence of riot police at main roads leading in and out of the
city center.
</P>
<P>
In Bulawayo, the country's second largest city, virtually all
private businesses stopped Tuesday morning as workers
overwhelmingly heeded the call by the ZCTU for a national strike.
</P>
<P>
But there is no sign of the promised heavy police and army
presence around businesses and the situation might remain the
same because there were no indication of a possible outbreak of
violence, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
In the central city of Gweru, business also came to a halt in
the city center and at the industrial sites as most shops
remained closed.
</P>
<P>
The police are on full alert and are patrolling the streets in
both the low and high density suburbs to ensure that no violence
takes place during the strike.
</P>
<P>
Most of the workers in the eastern border city of Mutare
responded to the trade union's call for the strike, resulting in
a partial closure of industry and commerce. Police and soldiers
were deployed in the city to ensure the protection of property
and human life.
</P>
<P>
The ZCTU declared February 27 as a deadline for the government
to scrap the 2.5 percent sales tax, five percent development levy
and 15 percent tax on pensions.
</P>
<P>
In January, thousands of residents in the capital city Harare
and towns staged the demonstrations in protest against rising
prices. Some of them looted, destroyed properties, causing
million of Dollars losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
