<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandans Threatened by Malaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- An Ugandan medical officer said
malaria cases in Uganda increased this year compared to last
year's 28,700, according to a local press report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Geofrey Kabagambe, Director of Medical Services of Kabarole
District, disclosed that 36,629 cases of severe malaria were
registered in the district between November 1997 and January 31
this year. About 102 of these died and 60 percent of the dead are
children below five, he added.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the problem to the increase in mosquitos
following the flooding caused by the El-Nino weather phenomenon.
He also blamed the local people for failing to take preventive
measures.
</P>
<P>
For controlling the killer disease, the Ugandan Health
Ministry has recently embarked on a massive campaign which has
been widely publicized in the press and health units.
</P>
<P>
This campaign is aimed to provide the public with correct
treatment of malaria, because self medication for the disease is
high with as many as 80 percent of the Ugandans practicing it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0018 </DOCNO>
