<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium to Provide $1.6 Million for S. African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Belgium's Flanders Province
will provide 1.6 million U.S. Dollars for South Africa's
educational, cultural and technological development over the next
two years.
</P>
<P>
The projects will also cover the areas of arts, science and
sport, according to delegations from South Africa and Flanders,
which were meeting in Pretoria this week to work out a program
under a cooperative agreement signed in October, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Gert Grobler, South African Foreign Department's Chief
Director for Europe, said the two sides had a very constructive
and fruitful round of discussions, South African Press
Association reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Director-General of the Flanders Department of Cooperation,
Administration and Foreign Policy, Diane Verstraeten, said that
the projects included an exchange program for students studying
science and technology.
</P>
<P>
The money would also be used to train South African
non-governmental organizations which provide aids to the youth,
and sport and recreation organizations, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-five percent of the projects were expected to be
realized within two years with the funding of the Belgian
province, and the rest would be catered for by the South African
government, Verstraeten said.
</P>
<P>
Besides the cooperation fund, Flanders will give another 25
million Rand (5.07 million Dollars) in grant to South Africa this
year.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch-speaking province donated 70 million Rand (14.2
million Dollars) for South African development projects from 1995
to 1997, with 30 million Rand (6.1 million Dollars) last year
alone.
</P>
<P>
Belgium ranked among South Africa's top 10 trading and
investment partners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
