<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Firms Which Closed to Be Punished: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government Tuesday
said it would punish those companies and financial institutions
that closed their business on the first day of a nationwide
stayaway.
</P>
<P>
Industry and Commerce Minister Nathan Shamuyarira told a news
conference here that the two-day work boycott called by the
Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions (ZCTU) was illegal and business
people who closed their premises denying employees to chance the
work would be censured.
</P>
<P>
"The government is going to punish those companies which
closed their premises today and, therefore, denied workers who
wanted to work the opportunity to do so," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He, however, did not say what punishment would be taken or
what legislation the government would invoke to deal with those
businesses that defied the call by the government to ignore the
work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
Most commercial banks, building societies, financial
institutions, post offices, light and heavy industries, retail
shops and chain stores in Harare and other towns closed their
doors as thousands of workers responded to the ZCTU call.
</P>
<P>
The minister said parastatal bodies such as post offices that
closed on Tuesday would face disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
He said that because of the work boycott, the government would
now not negotiate with ZCTU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
