<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Process Underway in War-torn Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Somali faction leaders Tuesday
announced here that they have overcome what they called the snags
that hindered their efforts in pursuing the Cairo peace agreement
and the establishment of an inclusive administration for
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
However, the faction leaders did not specify the obstacles
they met.
</P>
<P>
In a press briefing at Hotel Sahafi in the capital Tuesday,
Ali Mahdi Mohamed, a major faction leader, expressed his sorrow
over the delay for a quick understanding among the concerned
faction leaders.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he added that during this period the faction
leaders have been busy holding consultative meetings for
shortening the gap between them.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi Mohamed has declared that the Mogadishu politicians
will from Tuesday work so closely together and that the Nation
Coordination Committee (the Cairo signatories) can start
fulfilling their duties.
</P>
<P>
Husseion Mohamed Aidid also said at the meeting that they have
now unified their ideas in restoring peace and the Somali dignity
in general.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed the administration for the capital will be
completed in eight days time, adding that the pacification of the
capital will be given priority so as to open the main facilities
of the air and sea ports which have been closed since 1995.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting Tuesday, the faction leaders have also for
the first time said they will unite the programs broadcast on the
factional radioes that operated in the capital during the civil
war.
</P>
<P>
Since their arrival in Mogadishu after signing the historic
Cairo peace deal late December last year, the faction leaders
have managed to abolish the green lines that divided Mogadishu
for the past seven years.
</P>
<P>
They have also facilitated the return of life around the
deserted former front lines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
