<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR Tries to Ease Refuge Crisis in Great Lakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) Sadako Ogata said Tuesday the agency is seeking
159 million U.S. Dollars to help hundreds of thousands of
refugees in five Great Lakes countries.
</P>
<P>
The funding will finance UNHCR's ongoing programs both to
repatriate and reintegrate about 400,000 refugees living in
Rwanda, Burundi, Tanzania, Uganda and the Democratic Republic of
Congo, she said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The money will also be used in projects to rehabilitate health
centers, schools, water projects, forestry and crop and livestock
production.
</P>
<P>
In the last two years, more than 1.3 million Rwandan and
175,000 Burundi refugees already returned home. Now Tanzania is
the largest host country with 260,000 Burundi and 70,000
Congolese exiles.
</P>
<P>
During her recent trip to the region, Ogata promised continued
help for refugees from Congo-Brazzaville who fled to neighboring
Kinshasa during a five-month civil war last year.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR funding requirements are part of a consolidated U.N.
inter-agency appeal for 550 million U.S. Dollars announced Friday
by the Office of the Co-ordinator for Humanitarian Affairs in New
York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
