<HEADLINE> Rwandan Government Announces Important Lay-offs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government has
announced that it will proceed to important lay-offs of public
sector's employees, the Rwanda News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The lay-offs are scheduled to begin on April 1, Rwandan Prime
Minister Pierre Celestin Rwigema told reporters on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"This decision is aimed at developing the economy and to
increase salaries of government workers," said
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The workers who will be affected by this measure include those
without qualification, the aged who must retire and those the
prime minister labeled as "indisciplined at work."
</P>
<P>
Soon after the 1994 genocide, the Rwandan government was
advised by the World Bank not to recruit more than 50 percent of
the pre-genocide employees.
</P>
<P>
However, the government failed to abide by this advice and
hired 57 percent.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan Minister of Labor Joseph Nsengimana proposed to
the workers who will lose their jobs to look for other
professions and to form associations that the government could
support. 
</P>
</TEXT>
