<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Goldenberg Corruption Case Goes to Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Notorious Goldenberg corruption
case, connected with high-level Kenyan governmental officials and
a thorny issue for foreign donors, returned to court Tuesday when
defense lawyers demanded a fast trial against years of delays.
</P>
<P>
"My client was first accused in 1994 and we have waited till
today to learn what the prosecution wants to hurl at us," said
Aurelio Rebelo, defense counsel for chief defendant Kamlesh
Pattni of Golderberg International Ltd, according to Kenya News
Agency's reports.
</P>
<P>
However, Director of Public Prosecution Benaro Chunga said
Tuesday that delays are normal in such cases as defense lawyers
tried hard to get the termination of charges through preliminary
applications both before the trial court and the high court which
took a lot of time to finalize.
</P>
<P>
Pattni, former Treasury Permanent Secretary Wilfred Koinange
and two former senior officers at the Central Bank were accused
of the theft of 5.8 billion Shillings (about 97 million U.S.
Dollars) from the Kenyan government in the guise of gold and
diamond exports in 1993.
</P>
<P>
However, the four accused Tuesday pleaded not guilty at
Nairobi Magistrates' Court to a total of 15 counts including
theft, fraud and forgery at the beginning of the trial,
the reports said.
</P>
<P>
After the prosecution's opening statement, Chief Magistrate
Uniter Kidullah adjourned the case until Wednesday
when the prosecution is due to call its first witness.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) cited corruption and the
failure to bring the Goldenberg scandal to court as one reason
for suspending a 205-million-Dollar aid package to the east
African country in mid last year.
</P>
<P>
The Goldenberg International Ltd used a 1974 law designed to
promote exports to make allegedly fraudulent applications for
compensation payments from the government-run Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed with George Saitoti, then
vice-president and now serving as Minister for Planning and
National Development, the company was given a monopoly of gold
and diamond exports and a 35 percent bonus meant to compensate
exporters in advance of payment by export customers.
</P>
<P>
Therefore Golderberg was paid 185 million Shillings by the
government even though the country has no diamonds and produces
little gold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
