<HEADLINE> British Company Produces Human Protein in Transgenic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 3 (Xinhua)-- The British company that helped to
create Dolly, the world's first cloned sheep, announced Tuesday
that it has produced the human blood clotting agent Factor IX from
the milk of transgenic sheep.
</P>
<P>
PPL Therapeutics said in a statement that the success "will be
particularly important in the light of current concerns over the
safety of products derived from human plasma."
</P>
<P>
Factor IX, which is essential in the blood clotting process,
can be used to treat haemophiliacs, who often have deficiencies in
the protein.
</P>
<P>
The commercial production of Factor IX from the milk of
transgenic sheep, which is genetically engineered to carry the
human gene, will provide a cheap and safe source of the protein.
</P>
<P>
PPL, one of world's leading companies in the production of
human proteins in the milk of transgenic animals, has also used
genetically engineered sheep to produce AAT, a human protein used
to treat cystic fibrosis patients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
