<HEADLINE> Uzbekistan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan Join to Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The foreign ministers of
Uzbekistan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan held a meeting in Dushanbe
on Tuesday to discuss combating Islamic extremism and arms and
drugs smuggling in the region.
</P>
<P>
After the trilateral talks Uzbek Foreign Minister Abdulaziz
Kamilov told the press conference that the three countries "cannot
help being concerned over the instances of Islamic extremism
throughout the region and in Uzbekistan in particular."
</P>
<P>
The three countries intend to cooperate in locating sources of
this threat and to coordinate efforts for combating it at both
international and regional levels, according to Kamilov.
</P>
<P>
The Uzbek foreign minister criticized "certain countries" for
backing extremist activists in Central Asia, but not named these
countries.
</P>
<P>
The ministers favored Tajikistan's upcoming admission to the
single economic space of the Central Asian Union, comprising
Kyrgyzstan, Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
Kyrgyz Foreign Minister Muratbek Imanaliyev noted it is
"neither a political nor a military alliance, but an exclusively
economic union, open for membership of all CIS states, including
Russia." Russia currently acts as an observer state of the union,
he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
