<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Faces Shortage of Doctors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 3 (Xinhua) -- With only 400 native doctors for
over 15 million population, Mozambique is now facing a major
shortage in doctors.
</P>
<P>
Ellias Walle, chairman of the Mozambique Association for
Family Development, disclosed Tuesday that due to poor medical
facility, the mortality rate for Mozambican children is very
high, at 15 percent for babies under one year, and 29.5 percent
for children under five, the Mozambique News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
According to Walle, the average life expectancy for
Mozambicans is 46.8 years, with 47 for man, and 50 for woman.
</P>
<P>
In Mozambique, an average family has six children. In order to
reduce child mortality rate, the government has implemented the
policy of family planning to prevent women from giving birth
yearly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
