<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Appoints Chief of UNTSO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on Wednesday appointed Major-General Timothy Ford of
Australia as Chief of Staff of the United Nations Truce
Supervision Organization (UNTSO).
</P>
<P>
Major-General Ford will take over the command from
Major-General Rufus Modupe Kupolati of Nigeria, who will end his
tour of duty on March 31.
</P>
<P>
He was born in 1945. He was commissioned as an officer in 1966
and has held his present rank since 1996. He has held a variety of
appointments including Director Artillery, Director Plans-Army,
Director General Force Development (Land) and Chief of Staff at
Land Headquarters. His present appointment is Commander,
headquarters 1st Division.
</P>
<P>
Major-General Ford has a Bachelor's degree in electrical
engineering. He has attended a number of courses both in Australia
and oversees. The latter include Gunnery Course (the UK), Army War
College (the USA) and Commander and Staff College (India). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief on Council's Approval of UN-Iraq Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- It has been a tough period
for all and he is very pleased by the unanimous approval by the
United Nations Security Council of the deal he negotiated with the
Government of Iraq, UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan said on
Wednesday in a statement issued by his spokesman's office.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is a chance for Iraq to comply with the Security
resolutions and give free unrestricted access to the United
Nations Special Commission ((UNSCOM)). The United Nations has
taken certain obligations in the way it deals with Iraq and Iraq
has undertaken to fulfill its obligations," Annan said in the
statement.
</P>
<P>
"I hope this is a new chapter. I trust that if both sides were
to honor their engagements that we have entered into, we will be
moving into a period when Iraq will complete its obligation and
the Council can being thinking of lifting the sanctions and Iraq
will be admitted back into the world of Nations," the UN chief
said.
</P>
<P>
On February 13, Annan negotiated the Memorandum of
Understanding with Iraq's President Saddam Hussein, which ended
the latest crisis over UN weapons inspection in Iraq and avoided a
possible American military strike against Iraq. The UN chief
received a hero's welcome in the Headquarters of the United
Nations when he came back to his office form Baghdad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
