<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> C'wealth Meets on Nigeria Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Commonwealth Ministerial Action
Group (CMAG) began its meeting on Nigeria's transition to civil
rule program Monday in London, with Britain proposing another
CMAG visit to Nigeria to assess the situation.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting are Stan Mduenge, the CMAG chairman and
Zimbabawean Foreign Minister, British Foreign Office Minister
Tony Lloyd, Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworth and the
foreign ministers of Babados, Botswana, Ghana, Malaysia and New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Axworth reportedly said that the entire transition program was
tailored toward self-succession, without necessarily
accommodating the views of the opposition or providing a
conductive atmosphere for them to participate.
</P>
<P>
He noted that with just a few months to the August 1
presidential election, credible candidates are yet to indicate
any interest to contest.
</P>
<P>
The CMAG was put in place shortly after Nigeria was suspended
from the Commonwealth in November 1995, following its execution
of nine minority activists for murder.
</P>
<P>
The CMAG visited Nigeria in November 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
