<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Denies Clashes With Cameroun in Bakassi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria denied media reports
Tuesday that its troops clashed with Camerounian soldiers on the
disputed Bakassi Peninusla at the weekend, saying that it is a
propaganda by the Camerounians.
</P>
<P>
Briefing defense correspondents in Lagos, Acting Defense
Spokesman Colonel Godwin Ugob said the Nigerian troops on the
peninsula have been calm and that there was no exchange of fire.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian newspapers Tuesday carried a report by the British
Broadcasting Corporation that Nigerian troops took a surprise
attack on the peninsula at the weekend, killing at least seven
Camerounian soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the report is false and unfounded and that
it is a propaganda employed by the Camerounians when the issue is
approaching resolution.
</P>
<P>
Report of the clash came just as the International Court of
Justice at the Hague resumed hearing on the Bakassi dispute
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria and Cameroun both claim sovereignty over the Bakassi
Peninsula in the Guinea Gulf, which is of the size of about 1,000
square kilometers and is believed to be rich in oil resources.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have had several clashes over the peninsula
since 1994. Cameroun filed the case to the international court in
1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
