<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Said to Block Israeli Troop Pullback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior Israeli army
intelligence officer claimed on Tuesday that Hezbollah has warned
the Lebanese government against reaching any security arrangements
with Israel for its withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said the officer, who was not identified, made
the statement in a briefing to Knesset's (parliament) Foreign
Affairs and Defense Committee.
</P>
<P>
The officer said the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God,
contends that the Lebanese army is to defend Lebanon, not Israel,
in an effort to prevent the Lebanese government from meeting
Israeli demand.
</P>
<P>
Israel said that it will pull back from south Lebanon if the
Lebanese government promises to curb cross-border attacks on
Israel by guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish states carved out a "security zone" in south Lebanon
in 1985 manned with 1,500 soldiers and 2,000 South Lebanon Army
militiamen, for what it called protecting its northern areas from
attacks by resistance forces, which have been fighting to end
Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli officer said Hezbollah has been stepping up its
actions recently against the background of an up-heating debate in
Israel over troop withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli presence in south Lebanon has been costly, with
hundred of its troops having been killed. Last month, another nine
soldiers lost their lives in clashes with resistance forces,
putting more pressure on the government for a unilateral pullback.
</P>
<P>
So far, Lebanon has reacted with a resounding no to Israel's
offer, the Israeli officer said, terming this as the result of
Syrian attitude.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government maintains that Israel's proposal on
troop pullback is nothing new and that Lebanon will accept nothing
less than an unconditional withdrawal by Israel, as stipulated in
U.N. Security Council Resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
The officer said that Syria, a main power in the Israeli-Arab
peace process whose 40,000 troops are now stationed in Lebanon,
does not allow Lebanon to conceive peace unilaterally with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Syria is holding the situations in south Lebanon as a leverage
for getting back its territory the Golan Heights, which was
captured in 1967 by Israel, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
