<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan State Minister Censured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's parliament Tuesday
passed a censure motion against Jum Muhwezi, State Minister for
Education.
</P>
<P>
In a parliament session chaired by Speaker James Wapakhabulo,
the parliamentarians voted 148 for and 91 against the motion in a
secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
The motion was raised on the ground of corruption, violation
of code of Uganda People's Defense Forces (UPDF) and blackmailing
parliamentarians.
</P>
<P>
Muhwezi was an officer of UPDF, Uganda's armed forces, before
shifting to the post of state minister.
</P>
<P>
Some parliamentarians accused Muhwezi for engagement in
business with foreigners, which is in violation of the code of
UPDF.
</P>
<P>
Muhwezi is the first high ranking official and parliamentarian
censured by parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan authorities have repeatedly reaffirmed its
decision to fight corruption. Early this year, Ugandan President
Yoweri Museveni asked all officials to declare publicly their
estates, the estates of their spouse and children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
