<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN to Send Oil Experts for Assessing Iraq's Capacity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations is
arranging to sent a group of oil experts to Iraq to assess its
capacity to export oil, UN Spokesman Fred Eckhard announced on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Despite the approval by the Security Council of the United
Nations of 5.2 billion U.S. dollars for an expanded oil-for-food
program, Iraq has indicated that it has the capability to export
only up to 4 billion dollars worth of oil in every six months.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has kept complaining that what limits its oil export
capacity are the old oil pipelines and lacking of spare parts of
oil equipment, which it says are caused by the UN economic
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the experts are expected to arrive in
Baghdad sometime next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
