<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief on Council Resolution on U.N.-Iraq Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan stressed Tuesday that the resolution and discussions
of the United Nations Security Council is very clear that "we
should give this resolution a chance."
</P>
<P>
Asked by reporters if there is any ambiguity in the council's
resolution as to the use of force and if there is room for the
United States to act unilaterally to launch any strike against
Iraq without coming to the Security Council, the secretary-general
said, "We should give this agreement a chance to work and there
are expectations on all sides that the engagements and the
understanding will be honored."
</P>
<P>
Answering the question about the "severest consequences" in the
council's resolution, Annan said, "I think the implication there
is that any policy of patience and diplomatic approaches do have a
limit. If one breaks it time and time again, there may be a price
to pay, and I hope this will not be necessary."
</P>
<P>
"I think that in 1991 Iraq had not had this experience. Today
there is history. The Iraqi leadership and the Iraqi people
remember what happened in 1991 and subsequent bombardments. And I
think they knew what would have happened if they had not complied
this time. There can be no vision without a sense of history. And
I think that history has played an important role here," Annan
added.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council Monday unanimously adopted
a resolution, endorsing the Memorandum of Understanding reached by
the U.N. chief and the Iraqi government on February 23, which
ended the latest standoff between the United Nations and Iraq over
U.N. weapons inspection in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
