<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. CBO Projects 8 Billion U.S. Dollars Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The Congressional Budget Office
(CBO) of the United States projects an 8 billion U.S. dollar
surplus for this year, the first time the U.S. government would
record no a deficit since 1969, according to an AP report here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The CBO, Congressional nonpartisan, official budget analyst is
expected to release the information later in the day. It will be
the first official projection of budget surplus for this fiscal
year which runs through September 30.
</P>
<P>
CBO was also forecasting surpluses of 9 billion dollars for
1999, 1 billion dollars for 2000, 13 billion dollars for 2001, 67
billion dollars for 2002 and 53 billion dollars for 2003.
</P>
<P>
The projections come as some lawmakers from both parties and
the administration are debating on whether to use surpluses to pay
for tax cuts or spending boosts this year or enhancing Social
Security. The projection could dampen those people's expectations
since the surpluses for the next two years would be such a small
fraction of an annual budget exceeding 1.7 trillion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the White House said it expected a 10 billion
dollar deficit this year but a 9.5 billion dollar surplus for
1999. The next updated White House projection is not due until the
Summer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's 15,000 Striking Bank Employees Fired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 3 (Xinhua) -- As the strike by Kenya's bank
employees entered the fourth day Tuesday, major Kenyan banks
fired over 15,000 strikers who had been demanding to immediately
scrap the new tax on their soft loans and allowances.
</P>
<P>
Each bank employee received a letter of dismissal that listed
contractual obligations for the decision, the Kenya Television
Network (KTN) reported Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
In response, the Central Organization of Trade Unions (COTU),
organizer of the strike, said it is discussing whether to call a
general strike in support of bank workers.
</P>
<P>
The bank workers from at least 53 banks across this eastern
African country launched the strike Friday, vowing they will not
return to work until the government calls off the decision on the
new tax hike.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday night, Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae met
representatives of the Kenya Bankers Association on the crisis,
urging them to prepare a memorandum for presentation to
parliament.
</P>
<P>
It was said that about 50 affiliate members of the Kenya Union
of Commercial Food and Allied Workers took part in the strike
Tuesday, putting more pressures on the government as customers
complained.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, both the COTU and the Kenya National Chamber of
Commerce and Industry have asked the government to quickly
resolve the dispute, warning the strike could bring the economy
to a "grinding halt."
</P>
<P>
The strikers were requesting the government to quickly rescind
the new 22 percent interest rate imposed on employees' loans and
allowances, saying the tax contradicted with the government's
policy which asks bankers to lower their interest rates.
</P>
<P>
However, the Kenya Revenue Authority (KRA) argues that under
the Income Tax Act, the general policy in Kenya has always been
that all remuneration provided to employees are taxable.
</P>
<P>
The new rate of tax ranging from 15 percent to 22 percent is
based on the average 91-day treasury bill rate for the relevant
quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.: Severest Consequences Mean Military Strike on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States said Tuesday
that "the severest consequences" in a U.N. Security Council
resolution meant Iraq would face military strikes if it failed to
live up to an agreement on weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
"The United States clearly has stated, and the president has so
stated, that any reneging on the commitments Iraq has acknowledged
will lead to severest consequences, which very clearly means
military action," White House Press Secretary Mike McCurry told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said President Bill Clinton was expected to comment
later Tuesday on the Security Council resolution passed Monday
night containing the warning to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"I expect the president will... talk about the importance of
the Security Council resolution, talk about the imperative of
compliance by Iraq and talk about the consequences that can arise
if there is failure to comply," he said.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin also said "the severest
consequences" in the Security Council resolution was "the clearest
possible threat to use force that the Security Council has taken
since this crisis began last year."
</P>
<P>
"The world is now supporting a strong, clear threat that
military force will ensue if Iraq violates this agreement, and
that's why we think this resolution was so important," Rubin told
reporters at a regular briefing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
