<HEADLINE> European Shares End Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe ended
mixed Tuesday, with London and Paris retreating from their recent
record-breaking rally while Frankfurt extending Monday's gains and
ending at new record high.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 index of leading British shares fell from
record levels and closed modestly lower for the first time in five
sessions, dragged down by a flat Wall Street and concerns over the
country's interest rate ahead of the Bank of England's monetary
policy meeting on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 index hovered around the 5,800 level and closed at
5807.7, down 12.9 points, or 0.22 percent.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that investors turned their attention to smaller
stocks in the continuing hunt for value.
</P>
<P>
Energy Group was once again in the spotlight as bid battle
between U.S. group Texas Utilities and PacifiCorp intensified,
boosting its shares by 32 pence to 838 pence.
</P>
<P>
in Frankfurt, Germany's DAX-30 index closed at 4757.14, up
20.40 points, or 0.43 percent, a new record closing high,
supported by the dollar and gains in heavily weighed car stocks.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that these shares were in focus as a result of the
Geneva motor show.
</P>
<P>
The Paris CAC-40 index closed at 3,414.87, down 31.83 points or
0.92 percent as investors halted a run of four consecutive highs
to consolidate their positions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
