<HEADLINE> Updated: French President's Special Envoy Arrives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 3 (Xinhua) -- French president's special envoy
Bertrand Dufourcq arrived here Tuesday evening to stress the
importance France attaches to the complete and rapid compliance by
Iraq with the U.N.-Iraq accord.
</P>
<P>
Dufourcq, secretary general of French foreign ministry, told
reporters upon arrival at Saddam internation Airport that he
would deliver a letter from President Jacques Chirac to Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Chirac said in his letter to Saddam that
Iraq has the right to return to the international community on
condition that it plays the game according to the rule.
</P>
<P>
Dufourcq, on his second visit to Baghdad within a month, said
he would tell the Iraqi officials the importance to completely
implement the agreement signed by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan and Iraq on February 23.
</P>
<P>
He will raise the perspective of the lifting of sanctions as
soon as Iraq has fulfilled its obligation in terms of elimination
of weapons of mass destruction, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council adopted a resolution on Monday which
approves the agreement and warns of the "severest consequences"
if Iraq violates the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Dufourcq visited Baghdad as French president's special envoy
early last month to help find a diplomatic solution to the
then standoff between Iraq and the United States over U.N.
weapons inspection.
</P>
<P>
France played an important role in blocking a U.S.-led air
strike on Iraq and helping reach the U.N.-Iraq accord on resuming
inspections for weapons of mass destruction in Iraq. 
</P>
