<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Says Ties With Egypt Key to Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The normalization of relations
with Egypt is key to stability in Sudan, a Sudanese official said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Aziz Shaddu, a member of the Sudanese National Assembly
(parliament), was quoted by local media as saying Egypt's role in
peace negotiations between the Khartoum government and the
Sudanese People's Liberation Army (SPLA) led by John Garang, would
contribute to a rapprochement between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Sudan calls for the participation of Egypt and Saudi Arabia in
the IGADD, the Inter-Governmental Authority for Drought and
Development which is mediating between Sudanese government and the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
The IGADD is composed of Kenya, Uganda, Ethiopia, Eritrea and
Sudan. Sudan hopes Egyptian and Saudi participation would ease the
mediation process since Khartoum is at odds with Uganda, Ethiopia
and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA is a main rebel faction in southern Sudan which took
up arms in 1983 to press for greater autonomy for the southern
third of the Africa's largest country.
</P>
<P>
The two sides sat at the negotiating table late last October in
the Kenya capital city Nairobi under IGADD sponsorship. But the
talks failed to reach conclusive results. Another round is
scheduled for April.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Egypt and Sudan have been strained since
Sudan's President Omar al-Bashir took power in 1989 in a military
coup and installed an Islamic regime.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral ties reached their lowest point in 1995 when
Cairo accused Khartoum of involvement in an assassination attempt
on Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia.
Sudan denied the charge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
