<HEADLINE> Cohen Orders Troops in Gulf to Get Anthrax Vaccine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen
announced Tuesday that the U.S. military will begin vaccinating
36,000 American troops in the Gulf this month against the deadly
anthrax biological agent as a "prudent action."
</P>
<P>
He said he had decided to begin the mass innoculations at the
request of Marine Corps Gen. Anthony Zinni, commander of U.S.
forces in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The decision to vaccinate all the 1.4 million military men and
women in uniform was made in December, but the program wasn't
expected to go into practice until this coming summer.
</P>
<P>
But the program was accelerated, and will begin this month with
the forces now in the Gulf region due to the ongoing crisis with
Iraq, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
"After a careful review, I have concluded that vaccination
against anthrax is a safe, prudent force protection measure,"
Cohen said in a statement issued at the Pentagon. 
</P>
