<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: Chinese Economy to Surpass Eight Percent Growth in 1998 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Xinhua Writer Wang Weiping
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China's 1998 economic growth rate
is expected to surpass eight percent, with inflation remaining at
around three percent.
</P>
<P>
Liu Hong, director-general of the State Statistical Bureau,
said that this year's goals for economic growth will "be
completely achieved." The country's economy will continue to
develop along the track of "high growth and low inflation".
</P>
<P>
Continuing stable political and social environments will be
beneficial to economic expansion. The central government has
announced an overall objective of "seeking development through
stability", a move which fully indicates greater flexibility in
terms of policies, the currency, finances and investments,
according to Liu.
</P>
<P>
Strong material conditions which will further promote economic
growth include consecutive bumper harvests over the past three
years and the alleviation of "bottlenecks" related to energy, raw
materials, and transportation. Foreign currency reserves are also
on the rise.
</P>
<P>
The fact that pressures from commodity price hikes are
obviously easing offers an ideal macroeconomic environment for
deepening reforms, expanding the opening drive and promoting
economic development, said Liu.
</P>
<P>
Bao Kexin, director of the Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation Department under the State Planning Commission noted
that the financial crisis in Southeast Asia and the Republic of
Korea will have only a "limited" negative influence on the
Chinese economy."
</P>
<P>
While exports to the region will definitely be challenged,
great potential remains for the domestic market, especially the
rural market.
</P>
<P>
Bao also noted that massive personal savings deposits held by
Chinese citizens offer excellent conditions for supporting
national economic growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
