<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Re-elected President Promises to Do Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Israel's President Ezer Weizman
Wednesday promised to do his best to serve the country after being
re-elected for a second five-year term by the parliament.
</P>
<P>
In a secret balloting, Weizman won a clear majority of 63 votes
in the 120-seat Knesset (parliament) and defeated the challenger
Shaul Amor nominated by the ruling Likud party.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the announcement of the results by Knesset
Speaker Dan Tichon, Weizman said in a televised speech that he was
happy with the result, but would not "jump for joy," because what
he was caring about was how to serve the country better.
</P>
<P>
President of Israel is mostly a ceremonial figure. He is meant
to detach from politics and acts as a representative of the whole
nation, regardless of his political, social, religious and
cultural affiliation.
</P>
<P>
But Weizman, a dovish who strongly supports to advance the
Middle East peace process, has been involved in political affairs
more deeply and widely than any of his predecessors and in
disputes with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Weizman has been criticizing the hardline policy of the
rightwing Likud-led coalition on the peace talks with Arab
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
He has annoyed Netanyahu so much that he faced a strong
opposition to his effort to seek a second term. The prime minister
went so far as to break with Israel's tradition that an incumbent
president will not be challenged as long as he is intended to seek
a re-election.
</P>
<P>
The two candidates represent different parts of the Israeli
culture. Weizman helped create the Air Force of Israel. As a
general-turned-politician and former defense minister, he played a
key role in negotiating peace with Egypt and called for a revival
of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Amor has for years been mayor of Migdal Haemek, a development
town in northern Israel. He does not have his opponent's links
with the political and military establishments and has regarded
himself as a representative of "second Israel."
</P>
<P>
Shortly after Weizman succeeded in re-election, Netanyahu made
a courtesy call to him, during which they pledged to work together
for the benefits of the country.
</P>
<P>
Observers here have interpreted this as conducive to the
political stability of the country and helpful to move the Middle
East peace process back on track. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0067 </DOCNO>
