<HEADLINE> NATO Backs U.N. Resolution on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) expressed on Wednesday its strong support for
the latest United Nations resolution on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The support was expressed at a meeting of the North Atlantic
Council, the executive body of the western military alliance.
</P>
<P>
The council said it supports U.N. Security Council's insistence
on compliance by Iraq with its obligations under the Memorandum of
Understanding and relevant Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the U.N. Security Council passed Resolution 1154 to
warn Iraq of "several consequences" if it fails to live up to the
U.N.-brokered agreement on weapons inspection.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also stated that Iraq's compliance with its
obligations will allow the U.N. Security Council to work toward
lifting the U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq following its invasion
of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations currently has more than 400 people in Iraq,
including arms inspectors and staff administering the oil-for-food
program. 
