<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expanded Opening-up Enhances Market Competitiveness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China's existing buyer's market is
gaining increased integration with the rest of the world,
according to information released today by the State Statistics
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The dependence level of China's market on the international
market has jumped from ten percent to around 40 percent over the
past five years.
</P>
<P>
The statistics bureau reports that market expansion has been
accompanied by intensified competition, with the lack of necessary
demand needed to fuel economic restructuring becoming increasingly
apparent and prices falling in favor of buyers.
</P>
<P>
The government has removed price controls on over 90 percent of
commodities over the past five years, with less than five percent
of goods remaining under government control at the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese market exhibited increasingly obvious
characteristics of buyer's market between 1993-1997. Statistics
for 1997 revealed excessive supplies for 31.8 percent of 613 types
of products, with balanced supply and demand for 66.6 percent of
total products. Only 1.6 percent of products were subject to
shortages.
</P>
<P>
Consecutive bumper harvests over the past five years have also
helped to increase supplies and prevent rising prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
