<HEADLINE> NPC Deputy Calls for Developing Water-Efficient Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Wang Guangping, a peasant deputy
to the Ninth National People's Congress, presented his
water-saving rice cultivation technique to the Ministry of Water
Resources today.
</P>
<P>
Wang is here to attend the first session of the NPC due to open
here tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Wang began to work as a peasant in his hometown in east China's
Anhui Province after graduation from senior middle school in 1980.
As his hometown is a dry area, Wang tried to grow paddy rice under
plastic sheets and achieved initial success.
</P>
<P>
In the following year, he expanded his experimental plot to 1.3
ha. Though the fields received little rain for two months, Wang
gathered in a good harvest.
</P>
<P>
The 20-plus water conservancy experts present at today's
discussion all expressed appreciation for Wang's technique.
</P>
<P>
There is a shortfall of 30 billion cubic meters of water in
China each year. Water for agricultural use constitutes 80 percent
of the country's total water consumption. Water-efficient farming,
therefore, is a matter of the greatest importance, according to an
expert present at the discussion.
</P>
<P>
Wang said he would raise three proposals at the NPC session
including one on developing water-saving farming. 
</P>
</TEXT>
