<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nordic Farmers to Lose in EU Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Swedish farmers stand to lose
1.5 billion kronor (about 190 million U.S. dollars) in subsidies
if the European Union (EU) works to reform agricultural policy.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, said a press report here Wednesday, Hans Jonsson,
head of the Swedish farmers' association, is lobbying against the
agricultural reform proposal pending EU discussion on March 18.
</P>
<P>
The proposal would slash subsidies for meat by 30 percent, on
grain by 20 percent and dairy products 15 percent, but leave corn
silage -- an important crop in Germany and France -- intact.
</P>
<P>
As Sweden and Finland can not grow corn silage because of the
climate, their farmers said they will be disproportionally
affected by the cuts and should be compensated by the EU.
</P>
<P>
If the EU proposal goes ahead, Finnish farmers could lose an
amount of subsidies equal to their Swedish neighbors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
