<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian Awaits Increased Investment From Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Fujian Province offers sound
infrastructural, policy, economic, cultural and geographical
advantages and is fully prepared for a substantial increase in
investments from its neighboring province across the Taiwan
Straits.
</P>
<P>
Liang Maogan, director of the Provincial Office on Taiwan
Affairs, made the remarks today during an interview with reporters
from the Xinhua News Agency.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome Taiwan investments in all areas and industries so
long as they are introduced in strict accordance with related laws
and policies," according to Liang.
</P>
<P>
Local departments are adopting measures to further improve the
investment environment and efficiency in serving investors from
Taiwan, said Liang. "We must ensure Taiwan investors obtain
deserved economic returns and will extend the greatest possible
effort to protect their legal rights."
</P>
<P>
The vast majority of Taiwan-funded projects are currently
earning profits. Official statistics show that some 120-odd local
companies established with funding from Taiwan have increased their
capital by more than one billion US dollars since 1995.
</P>
<P>
The province has approved 5,032 Taiwan-funded enterprises, with
total contracted capital of 9.6 billion US dollars and actual
investments of 5.6 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Liang pointed to the complimentary economic cooperation between
the two provinces, and noted that Fujian offers abundant natural
and labor resources, while Taiwan offers superiority in terms of
funding and technology. He added that Fujian also offers abundant
supplies of raw materials and a vast market in inland areas.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan investment in Fujian has yielded enormous benefits for
both sides, said Liang. He also stressed that Fujian has benefited
greatly from the current reform, opening up and the modernization
drive initiated by Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
Fujian was once a poverty-stricken area due to political and
military factors, but has since recorded notable economic
progress. Statistics for inland provinces during 1997 show that
the province ranked 12th in gross domestic product, seventh in per
capita income, and fifth in foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Fujian has also recorded monumental achievements in developing
local infrastructure. The province has constructed various
types of roads stretching a total of 47,000 km, 99 berths,
four airports, and a large telecommunications network with
over four million telephones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
