<HEADLINE> Ice Dance Rules to Be Changed: ISU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The standing rules for ice dance
will be changed to solve the problem of "stable results" in the
scoring system, Ottavio Cinquanta, president of the International
Skating Union (ISU) said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ISU has been criticized for many years for excessively
rigid judging with positions seldom changing after the
compulsories.
</P>
<P>
At last month's Nagano Olympics there was no change in the
final order of the first 19 of the 24 couples. The only switch
involved couples placed 20th and 21st, one of whom fell and
dropped a place in the free dance.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the remedy for this problem is to introduce
changes in the rules, thereby giving the skaters and the judges
more specific references." said Cinquanta.
</P>
<P>
Cinquanta said he was confident that introducing new technical
rules imposing, for example, certain specific elements in the free
dance together with other technical amendments would help move the
sport on to another level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
