<HEADLINE> Kuwait Students Call for Release of POWs by Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Scores of Kuwait National
Union of Students and families of the Kuwait Prisoners of Wars
demonstrated in front of British Embassy Wednesday, calling for
early release of Kuwaiti POWs by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
This is the second demonstration of this kind in a week. Women
organizations held similar demonstrations in front of the
U.S. embassy last week calling the U.S. government to work for an
conclusion of the POWs issue.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain were the two major countries
which help Kuwait drive out the Iraqi occupation forces in 1991
and have built up their military power in the Gulf following the
standoff between the U.N. and Iraq over arms inspections in the
past few weeks, preparing for a possible air strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators urged Britain to help force Iraq to release
the Kuwaiti POWs held in Iraqi jails since the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the demonstrators, after carrying out
peaceful demonstrations in which women and children held
pictures of their beloved ones, delivered a letter to be
transferred to the British Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
The letter was received by the British Ambassador Graham
Boyce.
</P>
<P>
The Students Union called on Blair to make "more efforts
and more pressure on the Iraqi regime to release our sons
and brothers."
</P>
<P>
The letter also said "we are calling on the international
society for more efforts to end this human tragedy and to
return the smile to every mother, wife and son in Kuwait."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait insisted that 625 people went missing in the final
days of Iraq's seven-month occupation, more than 550 are
Kuwaitis, besides Saudis, Iranians, Egyptians, Syrians, Indians
and Lebanese. But Iraq denies it still holds any Kuwaitis it
detained at that time.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqis say most of the detained were missing in
fighting between the government forces and rebels in the weeks
after the Gulf War or in other post-war turmoil in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
