<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Build Oil Pipeline Along Ancient Silk Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China will build a long oil
pipeline along the ancient Silk Road, according to a delegate to
China's top legislature.
</P>
<P>
Dai Mingzi, head of Xinjiang Petroleum Administrative Bureau,
who is in Beijing to attend the annual session of the National
People's Congress (NPC) as a deputy to the NPC, said the new
international "oil road" will extend 3,000 kilometers from Karamay
in northwest China's Xinjiang Autonomous Region and end in
Khazakstan.
</P>
<P>
When completed in eight years, the pipeline, which will cost
2.3 billion US dollars to build, is expected to transport 25
million tons of oil to China annually.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline's domestic section starts from Korla, north of the
Tarim Desert. After arriving at Lanzhou, a major petrochemical
industrial center in Gansu Province, the pipeline will go east to
Central China's Henan Province in one direction and to southwest
China's Sichuan Province in another.
</P>
<P>
China's northwest provinces of Shaanxi, Gansu and Qinghai and
autonomous regions of Ningxia and Xinjiang together have one third
of the country's total oil reserves. The region is expected to
produce one fifth of China's total oil output in three years.
</P>
<P>
Khazakstan, which borders China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region, is widely considered to be the world's new energy center
in the next century. The country has plans to build itself into
one of the world's six largest petroleum producing countries,
hence the construction of the international oil pipeline.
</P>
<P>
According to Dai, the 428-km pipeline from Korla to Shanshan
within Xinjiang was completed last May and preparations are in
full swing for the construction of the pipeline from Xinjiang's
Shanshan to Luoyang in Henan and Pengzhou in Sichuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
