<HEADLINE> Blizzard-Hit Area in Tibet Needs Better Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- An official from a blizzard-hit
area in China's Tibet Autonomous Region said he will submit a
proposal on improving infrastructure in his native place to reduce
losses brought about by blizzards.
</P>
<P>
Kanggyin, commissioner of the Nagqu Prefecture of Tibet, said
he will submit such a proposal to the the First Session of the
Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) to which he is a deputy.
The session is scheduled to open tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Since last September, successive blizzards have hit the
Nagqu grassland area, and 260,000 people have suffered from heavy snow
falls, Kanggyin said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past several months, disaster relief has been well
under way with assistance from the State Council, local
governments and people in other areas of the country, as well as
troops stationed in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Relief materials, such as food, clothes and fuel, which were
sent by the government or donated by domestic and overseas
organizations and people, have been sent to blizzard-hit herdsmen,
Kanggyin said.
</P>
<P>
No one has been found dead as a result of the cold or hunger,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Nagqu areas is hit by blizzards almost every year. To
reduce losses, anti-disaster infrastructure needs to be built,
such as highways, housing for herdsmen and shelters for animals,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Also, the local economy needs to be diversified, he said.
</P>
<P>
If anti-disaster infrastructure can be improved with an
investment of tens of millions of yuan, hundreds of million yuan
of losses can be avoided, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Clarifies Stand on Rushdie Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government would not
support carrying out the death sentence on British writer Salman
Rushdie, the local Iran Daily Wednesday quoted a senior Iranian
official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Although the fatwa (verdict by Islamic leader) on Rushdie is
irrevocable, Iran will not support implementing the terms against
the British author and people associated with him, Mohammad
Hossein Fadaiefar, Iran's Foreign Ministry director general for
social-political affairs, has said in an interview with the daily
which was published Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Fadaiefar's statement was regarded as a new signal for the
European Union (EU) which demanded a written assurance from the
Iranian government over Rushdie issue.
</P>
<P>
The EU lifted a 10-month ban on ministerial contacts with Iran
last week, but still expressing concerns over Iran's stance on
various issues, including the Rushdie case.
</P>
<P>
Late Iranian supreme leader Ayatollah Musavi Khomeini issued
the death sentence on Rushdie in February 1989 for his
controversial novel "the Satanic Verses" which was believed to
have insult the Islamic prophet Mohammad.
</P>
<P>
On the 9th anniversary of the issuing of the fatwa, Iranian
Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi reiterated last month
that the fatwa "is irrevocable and will remain in the history."
Iranian Majlis (parliament) Speaker Nateq Nouri called on Muslims
to carry out the death sentence on Rushdie "to teach a lesson to
those who oppose god and the divine prophets."
</P>
<P>
During the past years, the Iranian government announced it
would not dispatch commandos to kill Rushdie, but refused to
offer written assurance to the EU.
</P>
<P>
U.N. High Commissioner for Human Rights Mary Robinson recently
confirmed that the Iranian government had no plan to carry out
Khomeini's fatwa on Rushdie after she held several talks with
senior Iranian officials in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Robinson was quoted by Los Angeles Times as saying that Iranian
Deputy Foreign Minister Mohammad Javad Zarif told her the Iranian
government could not annul the fatwa, but would not carry it out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Legislature Approves Immigration Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Provisional
Legislative Council (PLC) Wednesday approved a bill to abolish the
port of first asylum policy for Vietnamese illegal arrivals in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
According to the Immigration (Amendment) Bill 1998, there will
be no more special treatment for Vietnamese illegal arrivals in
Hong Kong and they will be treated in the same way as those
illegal arrivals who are from any other country.
</P>
<P>
The special provisions in Part IIIA of the Immigration
Ordinance provided for special treatment of Vietnamese people
arriving in Hong Kong without valid travel documents, including
detention, screening, review of screening decision and removal
from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Peter Lai, secretary for security, said at a PLC meeting here
Wednesday afternoon that after amendment, it should be clear that
"Part IIIA of the Immigration Ordinance shall not apply to
Vietnamese illegal arrivals intercepted and detained on or after
January 9, 1998, being the day on which the bill was gazetted."
</P>
<P>
The amendment has been made with regard to changed
circumstances in Vietnam, the nature of recent illegal arrivals
and widespread calls in the community for scrapping the port of
first asylum policy.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are a total of 1,194 Vietnamese refugees,
1,230 Vietnamese illegal immigrants and 690 Vietnamese migrants in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Two other bills, one about road traffic (validation of
collection of fees) and the other concerning the protection of the
harbor, were also adopted by PLC members during the PLC meeting
after second and third readings.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a series of bills covering inland revenue, stamp
duty, dutiable commodities and air passenger departure tax were
introduced at the PLC meeting by Secretary for Treasury Kwong
Ki-chi for first and second readings.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, government officials answered a dozen of
questions raised by PLC members on various policies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Retail Participation in HK Stock Market: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A survey, mostly conducted in
September last year, has found that 16 percent of Hong Kong adults
were stock investors, defined as those who held or had traded
listed stocks during the previous 12 months.
</P>
<P>
This represented a 60 percent growth in retail participation
since 1994, according to the survey findings released Wednesday by
the Stock Exchange of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the stock exchange said one out of four
households had at least one investor and that one-third of all
investors had invested in the market for the first time during the
previous two years.
</P>
<P>
"First-time investors tended to be less well educated than
longer-term investors, more prepared to take risks and had shorter
investment time frames," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said a lack of investor understanding of the securities
market had emerged from the survey and that investor education
would be a major priority of the stock exchange this year.
</P>
<P>
"More than 10,000 people attended investment seminars organized
by the exchange in the second half of last year and additional
resources will be allocated to this activity in its 1998-1999
budget," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The survey indicated that investors were trading more
frequently, making an average of 10 transactions during the past
12 months, compared with four in 1994 when the previous survey was
conducted.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that the typical retail investor was a male
white-collar worker in his late 30s with secondary or higher
education and a monthly income of about 22,500 HK dollars (2,885
U.S. dollars). New investors were younger and less well educated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Unemployment Rate Reaches 2.8 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The unemployment rate in Macao
reached 2.8 percent between November 1997 and January 1998, the
latest official statistics show.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by the Macao Census and
Statistics Department on Wednesday, the jobless rate rose by 0.1
percent from the October-December period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The underemployment rate went up by 0.3 percent to reach 1
percent in the period, 0.5 percent higher than a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Macao has seen an economic slowdown since 1993, with the
economic growth rate for 1997 estimated at less than 1 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
