<HEADLINE> HK Companies Remain Competitive at European Fairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong companies
participating in recent winter fairs in Europe have shown their
continuing competitiveness in overseas markets by winning business
worth at least 1.27 billion HK dollars (163 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
More than 300 companies organized by the Hong Kong Trade
Development Council (TDC) took part in six major international
consumer goods trade fairs in Germany, Italy and France in January
and February this year, said the TDC.
</P>
<P>
They won confirmed orders worth nearly 445 million HK dollars
(57 million U.S. dollars) in addition to business valued at a
further 827 million HK dollars (106 million U.S. dollars) under
negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong representatives at these trade fairs managed to keep
the edge amid strong Asian competition and were happy with the
results despite initial fears that currency devaluation elsewhere
in Asia might make exports more difficult, the well-known trade
promotion body noted.
</P>
<P>
"The amount of orders can be taken as a strong sign of
confidence in Hong Kong," said Lore Buscher, TDC's director for
Central and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Among the international buyers at Premiere '98 in Frankfurt was
Steven Lorenzetti, national marketing manager of an
Australia-based firm. "I don't think the Asian financial crisis
will have any effect on our business with Hong Kong in the short
term... We want added value, something different in colors and
fabrics, so that's why we buy from Hong Kong," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the Nuremberg Toy Fair, Hong Kong exhibitor Jane Lam, who
participated in the fair for the second time, was "surprised to
receive so many inquiries and make such good business."
</P>
<P>
"We had expected this time it would be rather tough in
Europe..., but none of our fears came true," she said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's total exports to Europe amounted to 239 billion HK
dollars (31 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
