<HEADLINE> Consultation on Macao Transition Smooth: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Consultation on a number of issues
concerning Macao's transition has proceeded smoothly, a senior
Chinese official of the Sino-Portuguese Joint Liaison Group (JLG)
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Han Zhaokang, chief of the Chinese side of the JLG, made these
remarks to reporters on Wednesday after a closed-door meeting with
his Portuguese counterpart, Antonio Carlos. The meeting was a
preparation for a plenary session scheduled to be held in Beijing
on March 10.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have started technical consultations on the
nationality issue of some Macao residents and on assets transfer
and the localization of the civil service has achieved new
progress since the last plenary session late last year, Han said.
</P>
<P>
Consultation on the transfer of archives and the setting up of
a Portuguese-language school is continuing and the two sides have
also stepped up efforts in dealing with Macao's renewal of
membership in international bodies and application of
international conventions in Macao, Han said.
</P>
<P>
"Macao has entered its final stage of transition," said Han.
"Time is limited but the task remains arduous. It is our historic
mission to make the utmost efforts on the major issues concerning
Macao's transition, and seek timely and proper resolution through
cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Carlos said the localization of the civil service has made new
progress. The Portuguese side has promised to have all leadership
and heads of government departments basically localized by the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed a wide range of issues concerning
Macao's transition that will be further discussed in the upcoming
plenary session. The JLG convenes three plenary sessions each
year, in Macao, Beijing and Lisbon respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
