<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Customs Cracks Down on Smuggling of Pirated, Pornographic VCDs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Pirated and pornographic VCD
smugglers may find it more difficult to bypass the "great wall"
established by customs officials as China is taking stronger
measures to control the VCD market.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Junxiong, an official with China's General Administration
of Customs, today told Xinhua that the nation's ability to fight
pirated and pornographic VCD smuggling has been significantly
strengthed.
</P>
<P>
Now, he said, nearly 300 inspection posts have been established
at ports; a satellite network can quickly inform all major customs
offices about a smuggling case; and the work of seizing on-sea
smugglers has been greatly improved.
</P>
<P>
Satistics from the administration show that more than 5 million
smuggled VCDs had been seized in 1997, among which more than 80
percent were pirated VCDs.
</P>
<P>
According to local observers, this figure also reflects the
determination of the Chinese government to protect property rights.
</P>
<P>
"In the crackdown on smuggled VCDs, successful cooperation has
been achieved between customs in both Guangdong Province and the
Hong Kong Special Administration Region," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
"Last year, through exchanging information and joint actions,
two illegal VCD production lines and more than 2 million smuggled
VCDs have been seized."
</P>
<P>
At present, the official added, all customs offices in China
have opened hot lines for accusations of smuggling and a
nationwide information network has been formed.
</P>
<P>
He said that, so far, the largest smuggling case of pirated and
pornographic VCDs was discovered on Dec. 12, when the Jiangmen
Customs in Guangdong Province seized 1.47 million smuggled VCDs
from a batch of waste plastic.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, an increase in the number of VCD
players, which was estimated by experts to exceed 50 million this
year, and the high profit margins of VCD smuggling make it
difficult for China's customs officials to tackle the smuggling
problem.
</P>
<P>
However, the official emphasized, "China has confidence to
win the battle in the end." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
