<HEADLINE> Khatami Urges US to Withdraw Forces from Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
Wednesday called on the United States to withdraw its forces from
the Persian Gulf, saying that the U.S. presence there has
threatened security in the region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a gathering of the Islamic Revolutionary Guards
Corps (IRGC) at Ahvaz, the capital of southwestern province of
Khuzestan, Khatami stressed that Iran along with other countries
in the region can preserve security in the absence of aliens.
</P>
<P>
The Persian Gulf is not a place for the showdown of foreign
forces and the U.S. fleet, and the U.S. forces should leave the
region immediately, the Iranian official news agency IRNA quoted
him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Khatami noted that presence of the U.S. forces in the Gulf is
an insult to the regional states because they themselves can
preserve the security of this region.
</P>
<P>
The United States has mounted up its military buildup in the
Gulf following a crisis between Iraq and the United Nations over
arms inspections. It still warned to launch military strike on
Iraq if Baghdad failed to comply with the U.N. Security Council
resolutions and the accord signed with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan late last month.
</P>
<P>
Khatami arrived at Ahvaz Tuesday afternoon on an inspection
of the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
