<HEADLINE> China Unicom Seeking Multi-faceted Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The GSM network, China's second
largest public telecommunications service provider, is expected to
cover the country's major cities by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
This demonstrates that China United Telecommunications
Corp. (China Unicom) continues to treat the expansion of mobile
telecommunications as a priority task in 1998, according to Unicom
General Manager Li Huifen.
</P>
<P>
The GSM network development will focus on the Yangtze River
Delta, the Pearl River Delta and the Bohai Sea Rim, Li said.
</P>
<P>
She said its mobile telecommunications network is set to plug
in 750,000 new subscribers this year and serve six more cities.
</P>
<P>
Long-distance telephone service is the second focus on Unicom's
agenda, she said.
</P>
<P>
Optical cables run by Unicom as far as 10,000 kilometers with a
capacity of 51,500 lines are ready to begin operations.
</P>
<P>
To date, Unicom GSM service is available in 80 cities in China,
with a capacity of 1.23 million lines. Its subscribers exceed
500,000.
</P>
<P>
The optical cables under construction total 9,000 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Unicom also expects to expedite the development of local
telephone service. While absorbing more local subscribers in
Tianjin in northern China, it plans to complete local networks in
Chongqing and Chengdu in southwestern China with a combined
capacity of 50,000 lines.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Unicom also plans to increase its paging
subscribers from the existing 720,000 to 2 million by the end
of the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
