<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Revolutionary Base Go in Line with Market Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- In Yan'an, the sacred place of
China's revolution, many local farmers have laid down their hoes
and run modern joint-stock businesses, according to a deputy to
the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
The First Session of the Ninth NPC is to open tomorrow at the
Great Hall of the People in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"The shift of people's mentality was not plain-sailing anyhow,"
said Liu Xiaowen, mayor of Yan'an City and a deputy to the Ninth
NPC.
</P>
<P>
Yan'an was the final destination of the Red Army's Long March
under the leadership of the Communist Party of China (CPC). Before
the founding of new China in 1949, Yan'an had been the
headquarters of the CPC for 13 years.
</P>
<P>
And in the beginning of the country's reform and opening to the
outside world in late 1970s, many people in Yan'an still kept to
the mentality of planned economy.
</P>
<P>
"The competition mechanism was not easy to introduce and reform
was hard to carry out," the 52-year-old mayor said. However, as
time goes by, local farmers have familiarize themselves with the
market economy, and market-oriented companies have cropped up.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials of the central CPC leadership have showed
great care for the people in the old revolutionary area, Liu
Xiaowen said. Over the past several years, major senior Party
officials have paid visits to Yan'an.
</P>
<P>
Each year, the central government sets aside approximately
100 million yuan (12 million US dollars) for Yan'an.
</P>
<P>
The locals have changed their traditional way of production and
life style. They have better transportation, medical and
educational conditions, and farmers have adequate food.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the GDP of Yan'an, with a population of two million,
reached 6.5 billion yuan, and the net income of farmers was 1,050
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The city has more than 500 enterprises involving petroleum,
chemical, coal and electricity industries. Their total annual
output value each was 3.2 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the city has been active in fostering
cooperation with foreign countries and international institutions,
Liu Xiaowen said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
