<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Presidium of Ninth NPC First Session Has Wide Representation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The 177-member Presidium of the
First Session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), which
was elected this morning at the session's preparatory meeting, has
wide representation of Chinese society.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Presidium include leaders of the Communist Party
of China (CPC) and the state, such as Jiang Zemin, Li Peng, Zhu
Rongji, Li Ruihuan, Hu Jintao, Wei Jianxing and Li Lanqing.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of China's eight non-Communist parties and the
All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce, and patriotic
personages without party affiliation occupy 13 seats in the
Presidium.
</P>
<P>
The Presidium also consists of relevant leaders of central
Party, government and military bodies and people's organizations,
deputies from the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR)
and Macao, deputies from national pillar industries and from
science and technology, social sciences, culture, education,
public health, sports, and religious circles.
</P>
<P>
Overseas Chinese, workers, farmers, officers and men of the
People's Liberation Army (PLA) and armed policemen also have their
own representatives in the Presidium.
</P>
<P>
In defining the identity of the Presidium members, the new term
"deputies from national pillar industries" has replaced the old
terminology of "deputies from the economic circles", and the
former phrase of "labor models" has been divided into "workers"
and "farmers". The new definitions are believed to be more
scientific and reasonable.
</P>
<P>
Among China's 55 ethnic minorities, those with comparatively
large population have contributed 18 members of the Presidium,
about 10 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
The Presidium members also include heads of the delegations to
the NPC session from China's 32 provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities directly under the central government and of the
PLA delegation.
</P>
<P>
Ng Hong-mun, an NPC deputy from Hong Kong who was elected head
of the Hong Kong SAR delegation yesterday, is also in the Presidium.
</P>
<P>
Reports say that the draft list of candidates for the posts of
the Presidium members and secretary-general of this session
indicates the outcome of repeated discussions and consultations by
relevant sides, with approval after discussion by the chairman and
vice-chairmen of the Standing Committee of the Eighth NPC.
</P>
<P>
The duty of the Presidium is to preside over the NPC session.
</P>
</TEXT>
