<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cataracts Top Cause of Blindness in Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese health official said
here today that cataracts are the top cause of blindness in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Cataracts were the most dangerous threat to Chinese people's
eyesight, especially the old, Liu Keling from the Ministry of
Health said at an international symposium for preventing blindness
which started Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Among the country's more than six million blind people,
2.5-to-3 million are cataract sufferers, according to statistics.
</P>
<P>
Health authorities are now shifting their medical focus to
surgical treatment for cataract patients.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 1.75 million cataract patients underwent
surgery from 1988 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Chinese government is seeking international
cooperation and exchanges with foreign countries and worldwide
health organizations, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
In the 1950s, Chinese doctors focused on curbing trachoma, an
eye infection that was then the first cause of blindness, experts
said.
</P>
<P>
The government also set a goal of holding blindness to 0.3
percent of the population by 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
