<HEADLINE> Think Tanks: Major Japanese Firms' Earnings to Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Leading Japanese companies are
expected to see, for the first time in four years, their profits
declining in fiscal 1997, two private Japanese think tanks said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The combined unconsolidated pretax profits of 461 companies
listed on the First Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, said the
Nikko Research Center, will drop 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The decline is likely the result of the companies' expected 8.5
percent drop in profits in October-March, or the second half of
the business year, said the affiliate of the Nikko Securities Co.
</P>
<P>
And behind the downward trend is the laggard Japanese economy
and of the fallout from Asia's economic crisis, it said.
</P>
<P>
Also Wednesday, the Okasan Economic Research Institute, of the
Okasan Securities Co., said the combined pretax profits of leading
firms would be down 0.2 percent this fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
