<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Statistics Reflect Improvement in China's Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China made further progress in
1997 in protecting the environment, according to statistics
released by the State Statistics Bureau at a news conference here
today.
</P>
<P>
Construction was completed on 4,533 pollution treatment
projects in 1997 with a combined investment of 7.9 billion yuan,
the statistics show.
</P>
<P>
In 557 cities, 2,339 smoke/dust control zones were set up
covering an area of 15,791 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
In 1,822 zones, noise pollution was reduced below a specified
level in 456 cities. The zones cover 6,913 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The annual statistics report shows that pollution prevention
and treatment is in full swing in key river valleys and regions.
</P>
<P>
First-phase objectives of the Huaihe River pollution project
have been achieved, and the river's water quality is improving.
</P>
<P>
The project attracted 4.3 billion yuan, and the government
closed 1,111 pulp mills each with an annual production capacity
under 5,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Also as part of the treatment program for the Huaihe River,
3,876 heavily polluting firms were banned, and 1,562
pollution-discharging companies with a daily wastewater discharge
exceeding 100 tons were given a specified time frame to establish
treatment measures.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show there are 932 nature reserves in China, of
which 124 are state-level. These reserves cover 76.71 million
hectares, accounting for 7.7 percent of the total area of the
country.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, 99,000 people were working for
environmental protection agencies in China, of whom 37,000 were
employed by 2,170 environmental monitoring stations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
