<HEADLINE> Survey: Chinese Citizens Prefer Traditional Family Pattern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Most Chinese citizens still choose
to form a family in the traditional way -- a husband, a wife and
children, according to a survey announced by today's Beijing Youth
Daily.
</P>
<P>
Some 5,138 families participated in the survey in 10 major
Chinese cities: Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Chengdu, Nanning,
Wuhan, Xi'an, Jinan, Shenyang and Xiamen.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that 48 percent of the respondents said that
they love the traditional pattern. Such a family pattern is more
popular in Beijing and Shanghai, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
Forty-three percent of the respondents chose the pattern of a
family consisting of husband, wife, children and parents.
</P>
<P>
Only 310 people, or 6 percent of the respondents, chose the
"Double Income No Kids" (DINK) family pattern, according to the
survey.
</P>
<P>
Among those who prefer DINK, 35 percent said raising children
takes much time and affects the quality of their life; 34 percent
do not want children for economic reasons; and 12 percent said
they are too busy with work to have children.
</P>
<P>
The survey also reveals that 27 percent of those who stated a
preference for DINK would have children if their economic
conditions improve in the future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
