<HEADLINE> Gulf States to Hold Joint Military Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) states are preparing to hold joint military exercises as a
routine check on their collective defense capabilities.
</P>
<P>
The exercises, the first one in the year, will take place in
the United Arab Emirates (UAE) in "the next few days," the UAE's
official Wam news agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"A number of troops" from the six GCC states, namely the UAE,
Saudi Arabia, Bahrain, Qatar, Oman and Kuwait will take part in
the scheduled war game code-named "Peninsula Shield-6," according
to Wam.
</P>
<P>
The military exercises are aimed at "supporting the process of
joint work to strengthen friendly ties" among the GCC states,
Wam said.
</P>
<P>
It gave no further details, but an informed source from the UAE
Defense Ministry, who spoke on condition of anonymity, told Xinhua
that the maneuver will focus on training the newly-structured GCC
collective troops named Peninsula Shield and improving the group
members' cooperation in protecting communication safety.
</P>
<P>
The GCC chiefs of staff worked out last October two military
projects known as "projects on tightening military cooperation and
defending communications safety."
</P>
<P>
The two projects included setting up a common radar network for
naval and air surveillance and an early warning aerial system
covering all the GCC states.
</P>
<P>
The projects also included plans for raising the strength of
the Peninsula Shield, established in the early 1990 from 4,000 to
25,000 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a political, economic and defense alliance was set up
in 1981. In the past years, it held military exercises annually as
one of the ways to improve its self-defense capabilities.
</P>
<P>
However, due to their relatively limited human resources, the
GCC states still remain seriously reliant on a large foreign
military presence to protect their security.
</P>
<P>
The United States keeps the largest troops in the oil-rich Gulf
region and it has some 20,000 service members and 30 combat and
support ships in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
