<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Lazio president Dino Zoff fumed over
Belgian referee Michel Piraux's controversial handling of their
UEFA Cup tie with Auxerre here.
</P>
<P>
Lazio won the quarter-final first leg 1-0, but were furious at
first being denied a penalty and then having Vladimir Jugovic sent
off in the 67th minute for a second bookable offence.
</P>
<P>
"It seems to me that the referee really went over the top, "
said Zoff, the goalkeeper of former Italian World Cup winning
squad.
</P>
<P>
Coach Sven Goran Eriksson concentrated on the moment when
Giuseppe Pancaro went down in the penalty area after a tackle by
Bernard Diomede at the end of the first half.
</P>
<P>
"On Pancaro, it was clearly a penalty," said the Swede. "I
really didn't like the way the referee handled a match which was
as important as this one. And no referee in Italy would have done
what he did over Jugovic.
</P>
<P>
Jugovic himself was bitterly disappointed at what he thought
was a mis-carriage of justice.
</P>
<P>
"I only stood in front of the ball because the free-kick should
have been taken two meters further back," said the Yugoslva
midfielder, who now misses the return leg in Burgundy in a
fortnight's time. 
</P>
