<HEADLINE> China Raises 65.5 Billion Yuan through Issue of Domestic Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China witnessed brisk business on
its stock exchanges in 1997, the State Statistics Bureau announced
here today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 188 Chinese companies issued 10.6 billion A shares
on the Shanghai and Shenzhen stock exchanges, raising funds valued
at 65.5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that China's number of listed companies
reached 745 by the end of last year, up from from 530 in 1996. The
listed companies had a combined capitalization of more than 1.75
trillion yuan, about 25 percent of the national gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
Also last year, China introduced 8.1 billion U.S. dollars of
foreign funds by issuing B shares, H shares and bonds on overseas
markets. A total of 241.2 billion yuan worth of state treasury
bonds were issued in 1997 and all treasury bonds due were repaid.
</P>
<P>
The standardized and stable development of the securities
market has played an important role in improving the product mix
and the industrial structure as well as optimizing the
distribution of resources, experts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
