<HEADLINE> BJP Fails to Win Majority to Form Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP)
has emerged as the largest political force in India but failed to
win the majority to form a new government.
</P>
<P>
As the counting of votes in the general elections is near the
end, the BJP and its allies have secured 254 out of the 535
contested seats in the first three phases of the four-phase
elections to the Lok Sabha (the Lower House of the Parliament),
but failed to get the necessary 273 seats to form the next
government.
</P>
<P>
BJP's opponents, the Congress and its allies, won 167 seats
while the United Front got 167 and others 17.
</P>
<P>
The final results may not be declared in two or three days due
to some irregularities in certain constituencies.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Election Commission announced Wednesday
that the commission had withheld the counting of votes in a
constituency in the eastern state of Bihar because of certain
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
The commission ordered fresh polling at two stations on
Thursday and the counting process would resume only after the
repolling.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources here said President Kocheril Raman Narayanan
was unlikely to take a decision on government formation before the
formation of the new Lok Sabha which is expected only after March
10.
</P>
<P>
Intense efforts are now under way among major political forces
in the country to form a new central government.
</P>
<P>
BJP spokeswoman Sushma Swaraj said Wednesday that her party has
already identified supporters among the 39 independent groups to
muster a simple majority of 273 in the 545-member Lok Sabha.
</P>
<P>
BJP's National Executive Committee is scheduled to meet in
Delhi on Friday to finalize its strategy to form the next
government, said BJP General Secretary Venkaiah Naidu.
</P>
<P>
He added that the meeting would also discuss and work out a
common minimum program of BJP and its allies in the event of a
BJP-led government.
</P>
<P>
The newly-elected MPs of the BJP and its allies would also meet
on Saturday to formally elect Atal Bihari Vajpayee as their leader
before staking claim to form the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
