<HEADLINE> Philippine Economy Remains Stable: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Manila, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Despite the Asian currency crisis,
the Philippine economy remains one of the most stable in the
Asia-South Pacific region, Trade and Industry Secretary Cesar
Bautista said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Citing surging investment and brisk exports, Bautista said the
country's economy will grow from 3 to 5 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines registered some 700 billion pesos (17.5 billion
U.S. dollars) in domestic and foreign investments last year while
its exports reached nearly 30 billion dollars, according to
Bautista.
</P>
<P>
Despite the "fine" performance of the country compared with
other Asian countries at this point in time of the economic
turmoil in the region, Bautista asked Filipinos to adopt
belt-tightening measures until the full recovery of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Due to the current currency crisis, the Philippine economy is
expected to slow down considerably in 1998 and 1999.  
</P>
