<HEADLINE> China Reports Financial Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China reported financial stability
and appropriate money supply growth last year, according to
figures released today by the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Chinese financial institutions had more than 8.23 trillion yuan
in outstanding deposits by the end of last year, up 18.6 percent
from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown shows that deposits of Chinese enterprises grew
18.4 percent to more than 2.86 billion yuan by the end of 1997,
while savings of urban and rural residents soared 19.3 percent to
more than 4.6 trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Outstanding loans of the Chinese banking system were valued at
7.49 trillion yuan at the end of last year, up 16.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
China's money supply was appropriate last year, with year-end
cash in circulation up 15.6 percent to 1.01 trillion yuan,
according to the bureau.
</P>
<P>
Financial stability has provided a reliable guarantee for the
sustained, rapid and healthy development of the national economy,
experts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
