<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Look at Weizman's Military, Public Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Ezer Weizman, an air force
general and politician, was re-elected Israeli president by the
Knesset (Parliament) for a five-year term on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Born in Tel Aviv in 1924 and raised in Haifa, Weizman is the
second president in his family, following in the footsteps of his
uncle, Chaim Weizman, the renowned scientist and Zionist leader
who was Israel's first president between 1949 and 1952.
</P>
<P>
Weizman's extensive military career began when he joined
Great Britain's Royal Air Force during World War II, serving
in Egypt and India.
</P>
<P>
After the war, he served in the Air Service, the
predecessor of the Israel Air Forces (IAF), and was one of
the founders of the IAF when it was formed as an integral
part of the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) in 1949.
</P>
<P>
In 1956, Weizman was appointed commander-in-chief of the IAF,
and 10 years later he became head of the IDF operation
branch and deputy chief-of-staff responsible for the IAF.
</P>
<P>
Weizman's political career began in 1969 with his appointment
as minister of transport. A high point of Weizman's public
service came during his tenure as minister of defense between
1977 and 1980, when he was instrumental in the process leading to
the signing of the peace treaty with Egypt.
</P>
<P>
He fostered close personal relations with Egyptian leaders
and played a pivotal role in the Camp David negotiations.
</P>
<P>
In 1984 Weizman founded a political party, Yahad, which ran on
a dovish platform in the elections to the 11th Knesset, gaining
three seats. In the national unity government formed after these
elections, Weizman served as minister without portfolio and a
member of the inner cabinet.
</P>
<P>
In 1985 he was appointed coordinator of Arab affairs, a
position which enabled him to promote his long-time interest
in assisting Israel's Arab sector.
</P>
<P>
In the 1988 elections, he ran Labor's campaign and
subsequently became minister of science and development in a
new national unity government, serving in his position until
March 1990.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, Weizman resigned from the Knesset over what he
regarded as lack of progress in the Arab-Israeli peace
process. And in 1993, he was elected Israel's seventh
president by the Knesset. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
