<HEADLINE> Aerial Ads Being Discouraged in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The people of Guangzhou, the
capital of China's Guangdong Province, were attracted recently to a
luminous lighter-than-air object filling the urban sky.
</P>
<P>
The airship was an airborne advertisement for Finland's Nokia,
the telecommunications giant, and was the first instance of a
Guangzhou company using this form of advertising. And it really
got the attention of a lot of people, some of whom even wondered
whether it was a UFO.
</P>
<P>
This style of advertising style, however, is running into
trouble, according to a Guangzhou Civil Aviation Administration
official, because of the possible effect on civil aviation
operations if the airship's altitude and area of operation are not
been strictly defined.
</P>
<P>
These kinds of airships used for advertising need to be
approved by the aviation department, the official said. And some
people in the advertising profession say that although the device
is quite new and interesting, it can not be used
indiscriminately. 
</P>
