<HEADLINE> China Bars Entry of Hazardous Wastes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China has stopped foreign garbage
from entering the country after more than a year's effort of
inspecting imported waste.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that commodity inspection departments examined
more than 5.6 million tons of imported waste last year, which was
worth 1 billion U.S. dollars. The result showed that most abided
by relevant regulations and contracts.
</P>
<P>
An official with the State Administration for the Inspection of
Import and Export Commodities (SAIIEC) said that 99.59 percent of
the imported waste met quality standards, up 2.09 percent over
1996.
</P>
<P>
Importing recyclable waste such as metal, paper and plastics
has helped ease the shortage of some raw materials, the official
said. However, a number of lawbreakers have transported hazardous
wastes to China as recyclables in recent years.
</P>
<P>
A leading official with the SAIIEC said that China will
continue to step up inspection of imported wastes, and will refuse
to approve those failing to meet the requirements.
</P>
<P>
He added that the SAIIEC will conduct spot checks of imported
wastes at ports of entry, and will leave unqualified waste to
local customs offices and environmental protection departments.
</P>
<P>
China announced a list of hazardous wastes recently in a bid to
further strengthen the management of dangerous wastes. The list
will take effect July 1.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
