<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Passengers,Freight Handled by Uganda Aviation on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 4 (Xinhua) --International and domestic
passengers and freight handled by Uganda Aviation greatly
increased during the period from 1991-1997.
</P>
<P>
International passengers received by Uganda Aviation increased
from 61,160 in 1991 to 165,300 in 1997, while domestic passengers
via Entebbe Airport increased from 2,440 to 14,600, and freight
from 1,300 tonnes to 12,700 tonnes in the same period, according
to statistics issued recently by the Uganda Civil Aviation
Authrity (CAA).
</P>
<P>
The CAA attributed the freight transport increase mainly to the
development of non-traditional exports such as fish and flowers.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's traditional exports are coffee, tea and cotton. But
in the recent years, its non-traditional exports developed rapidly.
Flower exports grew from 31 tonnes in 1994 to 1,860 tonnes
last year, while fish export went up from 2,970 tonnes to 5980
tonnes in the same period.
</P>
<P>
CAA Board Chairman Francis Omaswa said that the CAA planned to
establish a new cargo center, aircraft maintenance hangers, a
general aviation terminal, a fuel storage and distribution
services, in-flight catering center and airline support functions
in next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Olmaswa said that the CAA has injected six billion Uganda
Shillings (some 54 million U.S. Dollars) to rehabilitate
upcountry aerodromes.
</P>
<P>
He said that the problem bothering CAA is the problem of
possible bird accident, he noted. Some 70 percent of the birds
involved in accident is from a nearby livestock veterinary
experimental farm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC Chief Calls Poverty Alleviation National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Poverty alleviation is basically
a national responsibility because problems concerning poverty
differ from country to country, said Naeem U. Hasan,
secretary-general of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC), Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Unlike economic cooperation, you cannot have a treaty, you
cannot have a common program on poverty alleviation because
although the seven SAARC countries are basically poor and the
South Asia region one of the poorest in the world, the questions
and issues on poverty differ from country to country," Hasan said
in an interview with Xinhua at the Kathmandu-based SAARC
Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
For example, he said, the main concern of most SAARC countries
is education. But for Sri Lanka and the Maldives, it is no problem
as the literacy rates there are quite high.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said another major problem concerning
poverty in South Asia is the overgrowth of population and it is
especially true for India and Pakistan which both have a growth
rate of almost 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
"For these reasons, you cannot have one SAARC common policy. It
has to be national programs to be introduced," he said. "What we
do together as SAARC is to basically exchange information and
expertise and we try to replicate the successful programs in other
countries. This is the basic philosophy and basic approach of
SAARC to poverty issues."
</P>
<P>
Hasan said that in accordance with this philosophy and
approach, the SAARC Secretariat launched in 1996 the "SAARC Seven
Sisters: District Development Coordination and Improved Poverty
Project Design."
</P>
<P>
Under the project, district-level fora were established in each
of the member countries to periodically review and monitor the
poverty-alleviation programs there and identify the best
practices.
</P>
<P>
Except Bhutan, all the other SAARC members -- Bangladesh,
India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka -- participated
in the project.
</P>
<P>
SAARC also has a three-tier institutional mechanism which meets
regularly to review and follow up its poverty-alleviation
projects, Hasan said.
</P>
<P>
The mechanism comprises meetings of planning secretaries at the
first tier, of other related secretaries at the second and of
ministers of finance and planning at the third, the career
diplomat from Pakistan said.
</P>
<P>
In poverty alleviation, SAARC also has very close relations
with some international organizations like the U.N. Development
Program (UNDP) and the Economic and Social Commission for Asia and
the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
"We have some common programs, for example the UNDP in
Kathmandu has a special unit for SAARC-UNDP cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
South Asia is one of the poorest regions in the world with more
than 400 million of its 1.2 billion people live in destitution.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in 1985 to promote regional cooperation in
economic and social development, placed poverty alleviation high
on its agenda at its sixth summit in 1991.
</P>
<P>
At the seventh summit in 1993, SAARC voiced its commitment to
eradicating poverty in South Asia preferably by 2002.
</P>
<P>
The group adopted an agenda of action which included a strategy
of social mobilization, and a policy of decentralized agricultural
development, small-scale labor-intensive industrialization and
human development.
</P>
<P>
At the following two summits in 1995 and 1997, the leaders of
the seven countries reaffirmed their commitment to poverty
alleviation and the year of 1995 was designated as the SAARC Year
of Poverty Eradication.
</P>
<P>
Hasan said that in the past years, the literacy rate in South
Asia has been rising and most countries in the region are
conscious of controlling the population.
</P>
<P>
And in their national programs, these countries gave more and
more importance and allocation to the social sector, he added.
</P>
<P>
In efforts to alleviate poverty, attention should be paid to
education, especially that of women, control of population,
stronger rural development programs for food security and income
generation, he said.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general acknowledged that it is a "difficult
exercise" to wipe out poverty from South Asia by 2002. "I think
the deadline we have in mind is basically to give importance to
this subject and try to collectively and individually remove
poverty as early as possible," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women Playing Important Role in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The women's status in the Tibet
Autonomous Region has been raised remarkably, said Tibetan
pediatrician Yexi Yangcog based on her own experience.
</P>
<P>
Being a deputy to the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC)
from Tibet, she is currently in Beijing to attend the First
Session of the Eighth NPC, which is to open tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Before the peaceful liberation of Tibet in the early 1950s, her
parents and grandparents were all serfs toiling and suffering at
the bottom of Tibetan society. Both her parents were illiterate.
</P>
<P>
"It is the Communist Party that brings about fundamental
changes to my destiny," the pediatrician at the Tibet Autonomous
Regional People's Hospital said.
</P>
<P>
In 1965, Yexi was enrolled into the Capital Medical Sciences
University in Beijing, and became the first-generation of college
students from Tibet. Later she turned out to be a well-known
doctor on pediatrics.
</P>
<P>
Beginning 1988, Yexi Yangcog has been serving as a deputy to
the Lhasa City People's Congress and deputy to the Tibet Regional
People's Congress, the supreme power organ of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, she was elected into the Standing Committee of the
Tibet Autonomous Regional People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
"My present political status can never be anticipated by my
ancestors," she said.
</P>
<P>
According to traditional law codes in old Tibet, ordinary
Tibetans were classified into nine grades in three categories.
Women were not allowed to be involved in political and
military affairs, and their life was worthless, Yexi said.
</P>
<P>
Following the democratic reform in 1959, Tibetan women have
been protected by the Chinese Constitution, and they have obtained
equal political rights with men, he said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that more than 20,000 Tibetan women are working
in governmental departments as officials, and they make up 32.3
percent of the total cadre ranks.
</P>
<P>
Women deputies in people's congresses at various levels in
Tibet account for 10.53 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Many female NPC deputies from Tibetan had set forth proposals
for the development of river, airport and highway projects,
Yangcog said. All the projects have been or are being carried out.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Tibetan women are now working, among in other trades
and occupations, as county magistrates, township heads, judges,
procutorators and lawyers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
