<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Meets With Tunisian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
held talks with Tunisian Prime Minister Hamed Karoui on promoting
cooperation on various tracks here Wednesday, the Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"President Mubarak expressed satisfaction with the level of
Egyptian-Tunisian coordination, cooperation and consultation," the
visiting Tunisian minister told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The meeting reviewed the distinguished Cairo-Tunis relations in
various domains and the Egyptian-Tunisian Higher Committee to
convene later Wednesday under the co-chairmanship of the two
countries' prime ministers, Karoui said.
</P>
<P>
The higher joint committee is expected to sign nine agreements
and protocols on activating bilateral cooperation in trade and
economy, health, transportation and other fields.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on establishing a free trade zone between the two
countries will also be signed, according to Egyptian State
Minister for Planning and International Cooperation Zafer Selim
el-Beshri who chaired the committee's preparatory meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will introduce an annual 10 percent tariff
cut over ten years in order to realize a total liberalization of
trade in 2007.
</P>
<P>
Karoui, who arrived here Tuesday night on a three-day visit,
delivered to the Egyptian leader "a message of appreciation" from
Tunisian President Zine Al-Abidine Ben Ali and was entrusted with
a similar return message. The messages dealt with bilateral
cooperation and efforts to establish peace in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
