<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three River Project to Boost Economic Growth in Tibet (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region is
boosting its economy by accelerating the development of its Three
River Project.
</P>
<P>
The project is the short term for the comprehensive development
of the central part of the Yarlung Zangbo, Nyang Qu and Lhasa
river valleys.
</P>
<P>
The central part of the Three-river valley is located in the
southern part of the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, with Nyingchi in the
east, Ngari in the west, state boundary in the south and Nagqu in
the north.
</P>
<P>
The Three-River Project encompasses 18 counties and cities, 231
towns and 1,890 villages with a population of 798,000, accounting
for 36.37 percent of the total population of the Tibet Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
As part of China's Eighth Five-Year Plan and Ninth Five-Year
Plan development program, the project aims to quadruple 1990's
industrial and agricultural output value within the valleys of 840
million yuan to reach 2.47 billion yuan, averaging an annual
growth of 11.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural output value is expected to rise from 653 million
yuan in 1990 to 1.66 billion yuan in 2000, averaging an annual
increase of 9.79 percent.
</P>
<P>
Industrial output value is expected to rise from 187 million
yuan in 1990 to 812 million yuan in 2000, averaging an annual
increase of 15.82 percent.
</P>
<P>
Farmers and herdsmen are expected to increase their income from
602.24 yuan per capita in 1990 to 1,450 yuan per capita in 2000,
averaging an annual growth of 9.18 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
