<HEADLINE> China, France Sign Memorandum on Securities Supervision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China and France today signed a
memorandum of understanding on cooperation in the supervision of
securities and futures.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum marks a new stage in securities and futures
cooperation between China and France, opening a channel for the
two countries to exchange personnel and information on securities
market supervision, both parties agreed.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Zhengqing, chairman of the Securities Committee of the
Chinese State Council and chairman of the China Securities
Regulatory Commission, said that China's eight-year-old securities
market has become an important part of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Michel Prada, Zhou's French counterpart, said that the
memorandum serves as a bridge between the capital market of France
and China and will benefit the globalization effort of companies
in both countries.
</P>
<P>
The latest official statistics show that China has 757 listed
companies, including 42 listed overseas, and more than 34 million
stock investors.
</P>
<P>
The market capitalization of the listed companies reached 1.8
trillion yuan at the end of 1997, while securities turnover
totaled 3.07 trillion yuan last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
