<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three River Project to Boost Economic Growth in Tibet (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Central Government in 1991 decided to invest 1 billion yuan
in the Three-River Project, the largest of its kind undertaken in
Tibet.
</P>
<P>
From 1991 to 2000, more than 220 projects will be undertaken as
part of the Three-River Project, involving farming, livestock
breeding, forestry, water conservancy, energy, communications and
industry.
</P>
<P>
The water conservancy project includes building or expanding 36
irrigation canals with a total length of 811 km, and 12 reservoirs
with a total holding capacity of 460 million cubic meters of
water, and building six pump irrigation stations, four
flood-preventing works, and three drinking water works.
</P>
<P>
The livestock breeding project covers planting 15,553 hectares
of grass, renovating 60,000 hectares of natural pastures, setting
up 433 hectares of grass seeds bases, building five yak, seven
buffalo and four pig breeding centers.
</P>
<P>
In forestry sector, Tibet is to plant 62,000 hectares of
forests, building three tree seedling farms which cover a total
area of 245 hectares, and building up four forest belts in the
Yarlung Zangbo, Nyang Qu and Lhasa river valleys.
</P>
<P>
The energy development project involves building five
county-level power stations with a combined installed capacity of
10,400 kw and five county-level power grids, and encouraging use
of 50,000 solar energy stoves among the locals.
</P>
<P>
The communications project encompasses building the Yarlung
Zangbo River Zetang Bridge and the Yarlung Zangbo River Donggar
Bridge in Xigaze, and building 1,000 km of rural roads.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
