<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Makes Headway with World Trade Organization Access </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) believes
that China's latest proposal on tariffs and quotas in the
negotiations for its entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO)
makes it possible to finish an agreement on market access this
spring, the International Business Daily has reported.
</P>
<P>
The EU Commission deemed that 75 percent of the multilateral
protocol for China's WTO access has been concluded, which
constitutes significant progress in China's WTO efforts, according
to the article.
</P>
<P>
The opening of China's service industry will be one focus of
the negotiation, the daily quoted an EU newspaper as reporting.
</P>
<P>
The report said that in the last four years China has shown
initiative and flexibility in the negotiations on import tariffs,
quotas, agricultural compensation and opening-up of the service
sector.
</P>
<P>
From 1994 to 1997, China has lowered its general level of
import taxes from 34 percent to 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
The commodities subject to quota have reduced to 350 from
1,200, and quota limits will disappear in 2005 when EU lifts its
control on China's exports of garments, shoes, porcelain and toys.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 12,000 businesses have foreign trade rights in
China now compared to 14 in 1979 when China began its economic
reform and opening-up to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
China's compensation on farm produce has been controlled
within 20-to-25 percent, and will reach 15 percent before 2005.
</P>
<P>
As for China's opening of its service sector, the EU
Commission is interested in a proposal China made last November
which touched upon distribution, judiciary, accounting, banking
and insurance.
</P>
<P>
The EU hoped that the negotiations on China's service industry
would speed up in the first half of this year, and began to draft
the rest of the protocol, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The EU Commission was also satisfied with China's
strengthening of the protection of intellectual property rights,
the article said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
