<HEADLINE> China's Industrial Enterprises Report Improved Economic Efficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) --The overall efficiency index for
China's 370,000 industrial enterprises at and above township level
was 91.3 percent in 1997, a rise of 3.1 percentage points over
that of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Information released by the State Statistics Bureau today also
shows that sales ratio of manufactured commodities stood at 96.2
percent last year, an increase of 0.3 percentage points over 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the same report, the assets-to-debt rate of
enterprises was 64.8 percent in the past year, down by 0.3
percentage points over 1996. Capital value of industrial
enterprises at the end of 1997 was 112.8 percent as compared with
that at the beginning of the year, of which, that of state-owned
enterprises was 109.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country's industrial enterprises reported an improvement in
the quality of their products last year, with 84.7 percent of
major products meeting their quality standards, 3.1 percentage
points higher than the year before.
</P>
<P>
Progress was achieved in curbing losses and profits made
industrial enterprises increased. The net industrial profits rose
by 16.8 percent and that of state-owned enterprises went up by
11.9 percent, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
