<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1stadd: Weizman Re-elected Israeli President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 4 (Xinhua) -- In a Knesset (Israeli
Parliament) vote for state President, incumbent Ezer Weizman
defeated the ruling party Likud candidate Shaul Amor and won a
second five-year term.
</P>
<P>
Knesset Speaker Dan Tichon announced that Weizman, who enjoys
strong public support, gained an absolute majority of 63 votes in
the 120-seat-Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Weizman's victory was mainly attributed to the backing of
opposition Labor party that was satisfied with Weizman's strong
support for the peace process with the Palestinians and Syria.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Weizman's dovish views frequently angered
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. In nominating Amor,
the Likud broke with a tradition that a president who wishes
to serve a second term is never opposed.
</P>
<P>
But because the ballot is secret, and members of the
government coalition can sometimes be persuaded to defect or
abstain. Therefore, Weizman also got some votes from the ruling
party members.
</P>
<P>
Israel's president is a largely ceremonial figure. Weizman was
elected Israel's seventh president by the Knesset for a five-year
term in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Weizman, 73, is the second president in his family, following
the footsteps of his uncle, Chaim Weizman, a renowned scientist
and Zionist leader, who was Israel's first president.
</P>
<P>
The presidential inauguration is scheduled for May 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
