<HEADLINE> 1stlead: Weizman Reelected Israeli President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 4 (Xinhua) -- In a Knesset (Israeli
Parliament) vote for state President, incumbent Ezer Weizman
defeated the ruling party Likud candidate Shaul Amor and won a
second five-year term.
</P>
<P>
Knesset Speaker Dan Tichon announced that Weizman, who enjoys
strong public support, gained an absolute majority in the
120-seat-Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Tichon said that 119 legislators took part in the secret
ballot -- 63 votes for Weizman, 49 votes for Likud member Amor and
7 white ballots were cast. He noted that the presidential swearing
ceremony will take place in May.
</P>
<P>
At the presidential residence in Jerusalem, Weizman told
reporters that he was happy about the outcome though he was not
"jumping for joy."
</P>
<P>
Weizman said the role of the President comes with much
responsibility and he intends to continue to fill that role.
</P>
<P>
He said he was pleased that the people of Israel have stood by
him, noting that they did push him to the victory.
</P>
<P>
The incumbent president's victory was also attributed to the
backing of opposition Labor party that was satisfied with
Weizman's strong support for the peace process with the
Palestinians and Syria.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Weizman's dovish views frequently angered
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. In nominating Amor,
the Likud broke with a tradition that a president who wishes to
serve a second term is never opposed.
</P>
<P>
But because the ballot is secret, and members of the
government coalition can sometimes be persuaded to defect or
abstain, Weizman obviously also got some votes from the ruling
party members.
</P>
<P>
Weizman said that it was Netanyahu's democratic right to
support the candidate of his choice. He also stressed that he and
Netanyahu would find a way to work together.
</P>
<P>
Israel's president is a largely ceremonial figure. Weizman was
elected Israel's seventh President by the Knesset for a five-year
term in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Weizman, 73, is the second president in his family, following
the footsteps of his uncle, Chaim Weizman, the renowned scientist
and Zionist leader who was Israel's first President. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
