<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Peace Process to End Within Days, UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Behrooz Sadry, Deputy
Representative of the United Nations to Angola, said here Tuesday
night that the peace process in the country is to end in a few
days.
</P>
<P>
Sadry made the remark at a press conference after a meeting
between the former rebel force UNITA (the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola) and the UN Observation Mission.
</P>
<P>
He said that his talks with UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi was
very positive, creating good prospect for the accomplishment of
the peace process in the country.
</P>
<P>
The February 28 peace deadline, which Angolans have failed to
meet, he said, had thrown the peace process into dilemma, but his
talks with Angolan President and UNITA leader have brought
forward series of new peace proposals.
</P>
<P>
The government and the UNITA are studying ways to implement
the Lusaka Peace Protocol, he said.
</P>
<P>
No new deadline has been set for the peace process, Sadry
said, adding that March 13 would be an important day for Angola's
peace process as the UN Observation Mission is scheduled to hand
over a report to the UN Security Council over the development of
peace process in the country by that day.
</P>
<P>
He announced that the joint peace process committee would hold
a meeting to discuss the development of peace process in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The sabotage activities by the UNITA forces have destroyed the
peace process originally set to end on February 28.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
