<HEADLINE> U.S. Delegation to Watch China's Village Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A delegation from the Carter
Center of the United States, led by Dr. Robert Pastor, arrived in
Beijing today to watch elections of the villagers' committee in
Jilin and Liaoning provinces in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, made up of experts on election issues and
journalists, is the second sent by the Carter Center to watch
China's village-level elections in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
The center sent a delegation to Fujian and Hebei provinces last
March. Delegation members reportedly rendered objective and
positive remarks on the villagers' election there.
</P>
<P>
Pastor said, after watching the election, that "our conclusion
is that this is a serious and positive and significant
development" that China achieved in granting political rights to
its 900 million people living in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
Invited by China's Ministry of Civil Affairs, the eight-member
delegation will also discuss how to increase bilateral exchanges
and cooperation with ministry leaders in their 12-day China tour.
</P>
</TEXT>
