<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll on European Integration to French Identity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Nearly one Frenchman in two thinks
that European integration is posing a threat to the national
identity of France, said a poll published by the daily Le Figaro
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen percent of the people polled say they regard European
integration as a "very grave threat" to national identity, 34
percent regard it as "a rather grave threat," while 47 percent
consider it not a threat to national identity.
</P>
<P>
The poll was conducted by the Ipsos polling institute on February
27 and 28 among 981 people above the age of 18 and representing all
walks of life in France.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-five percent of the Frenchmen prefer local communities to
manage the running of national territory, against 37 percent who
think the national government should be in charge of territorial
management. Only five percent think European Union authorities should
be in charge of policy in territorial management of national states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
