<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Entrepreneurial Idea Motivates American Women to Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 3 (Xinhua) -- American women are launching
new businesses because they are inspired by an entrepreneurial
idea, according to a national survey today.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the National Foundation for Women
Business Owners, also found that women start their own business
because of frustration with their previous work environment.
</P>
<P>
Forty-four percent of the women surveyed said that they start
their own enterprises because they recognize opportunities to
implement entrepreneurial ideas.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-one percent of the women with prior private sector
experience cite the desire for more flexibility as the major
reason for leaving their corporate position, while 29 percent
cite "glass ceiling" issues.
</P>
<P>
While the businesses started by men are most likely related to
their previous ones, most of women either started a business
totally unrelated to their previous jobs or turned a personal
interest into a business pursuit, said the survey.
</P>
<P>
The study also found that women business owners are more likely
to have started a business than to purchase one as compared with
men. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
