<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 40 Bodies Recovered in Flooded Area in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Rescue teams have so far
recovered about 40 bodies from flood water in southwestern
Pakistan, where flood caused by torrential rains wreaked havoc,
officials here said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chief Minister of Balochistan province Sardar Akhtar Mengal has
left the provincial capital of Quetta for Turbat, headquarters of
the Markran Division near the Arabian Sea to oversee relief
efforts, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
About 60 to 70 villages were washed away as the Dasht river
near Turbat overshot its banks resulting in heavy floods on
Tuesday, leaving hundreds of people homeless. Earlier, reports
have put the death toll at around 70.
</P>
<P>
The Public Relations Department of Balochistan said Tuesday in
a press release that the current flood level had broken the record
of 200 years.
</P>
<P>
The Balochistan provincial government has set up a relief cell
in Quetta and announced a relief package of five million rupees
(about 100,000 U.S. dollars) for the flood victims.
</P>
<P>
Rain has now stopped in the area, which would accelerate the
rescue operation, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Markran Division administration, with the assistance of the
army, has launched a rescue operation in the area, using army
boats and helicopters to evacuate people from the flood-hit zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
