<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe Won't Tie Asian Aid to Myanmar's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Britain has assured ASEAN
member countries Europe will not be forced to pressure Myanmar
over Yangon's alleged human rights abuses in return for Europe's
help for Asian economic recovery, the Malaysian national news
agency Bernama reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"There is no leverage or linkage between the two," said British
Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs Derek
Fatchett, who is on a one-day visit here as personal emissary of
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and special representative of
the European Union presidency.
</P>
<P>
"The answer is no," he said when asked by reporters if Europe
would use its assistance to the Asian region to pressure ASEAN
countries to act against Myanmar over its alleged human rights
abuses, Bernama said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference prior to meeting Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad, he said Britain and Europe have already
stated their position on Myanmar's human rights record.
</P>
<P>
According to Bernama, Fatchett said earlier in a statement read
out at the news conference that it was in Europe's interest to
help Asian countries deal with their financial difficulties
because "they are our problems too."
</P>
<P>
Reports from Bangkok Tuesday quoted Amnesty International as
calling on European countries to use their "influence" and make
human rights abuses in Myanmar a central issue at the Asia-Europe
Meeting (ASEM) in London next month, Bernama said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN maintains a policy of non-interference in the internal
affairs of member countries.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Thailand, Singapore and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
