<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Producer Inflation Continues to Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's year-on-year
producer inflation rate dropped to 3.2 percent in January from
four percent in December, the Central Statistical Service said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The figure was the lowest in 27 years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South African central bank's gold and foreign
exchange reserves rose to 30.9 billion Rand (6.3 billion U.S.
Dollars) in February from 27.9 billion Rand (5.7 billion dollars)
in January.
</P>
<P>
Economists believe that the drop of producer inflation and
rise of reserves will prompt the easing of interest rates as
early as next week. It is predicted that the rates will be cut by
at least two percentage points within the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
