<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sees Fast Growth in Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China continued fast growth in
foreign trade in 1997, said a report released today by the State
Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, total volume of export and import in
1997 reached 325.1 billion U.S. dollars, up 12.1 percent over the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, the volume of export was 182.7 billion
U.S. dollars, up 20.9 percent, and that of import was 142.4
billion U.S. dollars, up 2.5 percent, resulting in a trade surplus
of 40.3 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The import and export by foreign-funded enterprises rose by
11.3 percent. Export of general trade showed strong momentum of
growth and its share in total export rose from 41.6 percent in
1996 to 42.7 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The export of processing trade continued to grow fast and the
structure of import and export commodities was further improved.
The share of mechanical and electrical products in export rose
from 31.9 percent to 32.5 percent, continually making up the
largest category of export commodities.
</P>
<P>
In terms of import, significant increase was seen in the import
of technology-intensive merchandise and resource commodities, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
Further progress was made in the development of multi-market
strategy for foreign trade. The volume of trade with Africa and
with Latin America rose by 24.5 percent and 40.6 percent
respectively, 12.4 percentage points and 28.5 percentage points
higher than the average growth of foreign trade. The precedence of
China in the world with respect to foreign trade rose from the
11th to the 10th, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
