<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Boasts World's Second Largest Telephone Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China has had the second biggest
telephone network in the world, according to a report released
here today by the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the business transactions of postal and
telecommunications services in 1997 totaled 177.9 billion yuan, up
33.3 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
While traditional postal services showed a noticeable decline
last year, new services were full of vitality, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The capacity of public switchboards reach 110.97 million
lines. Telephone services in all cities above county level became
program-controlled, and China has thus owned the world's second
largest telephone network.
</P>
<P>
The new mobile telephone users in 1997 were 6.38 million,
bringing China's total number of mobile telephone users up to
13.23 million or representing 98.1 percent more than that at the
end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
There were 8.1 telephone lines per 100 persons in China and
26.1 telephone lines per 100 urban inhabitants. Subscribers to
computer network services reached 160,000, a four-fold increase
over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Rapid growth was registered in digitized data transmission
services and electronic data interchange services. There were
360,000 users of data communications services, said the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
