<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Diversion Between China's Longest Rivers Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Legislators from east China's
Shandong Province today urged the central government to carry out
as early as possible an ambitious project of water diversion
between the two longest rivers to ease water shortage in northern
China.
</P>
<P>
"The implementation of the project to divert water from the
Yangtze to the Yellow River at an earlier date will give an
ultimate solution to the grave water shortage by Shandong and
other northern provinces," said Wang Xia, a Shandong deputy to the
Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislature.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze is the longest river in China, followed by the
Yellow River. Due to the sharp contrast in climatic and
environmental conditions in northern and southern China, the
former has an abundance of water sources, while the latter has
been frequented by flow stoppage since 1972.
</P>
<P>
Though a coastal province, Shandong only ranks 26th in China in
terms of water resources. Experts predict that the province could
be short of five to six billion cubic meters of water by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Shandong relies heavily on the Yellow River, which runs through
the province before it is emptied into the Yellow Sea, in water
supply. Since the early 1990s, the river has contributed on
average 7.3 billion cubic meters of water each year, about 40
percent of Shandong's annual consumption.
</P>
<P>
But last year the Yellow River scored a record 226 days of flow
stoppage in Shandong, affecting 1.3 million hectares of cropland
and causing a loss of 13.5 billion yuan (1.6 billion US dollars)
to the province.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the Shengli Oilfield, China's second largest
petroleum producer at the estuary of the Yellow River, had to cut
oil production simply because of water shortage.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang, who is also deputy director of the water
conservancy bureau under the Shandong provincial government, the
water diversion project, once completed, will annually provide
three to nine billion cubic meters of water supply for Shandong
alone.
</P>
<P>
The project will also benefit Beijing, Tianjin and Hebei
Province to the north of Shandong, he added.
</P>
<P>
He estimated that the first-phase engineering of the project,
to divert water from the lower reaches of the Yangtze in east
China's Jiangsu Province to the Yellow River in Shandong through
an upgraded ancient canal, would cost 7.5 billion yuan (900
million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
"Given huge economic returns it could bring, the project is not
very costly," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said he is planning to submit a bill concerning the project
to the first annual session of the Ninth NPC scheduled to open
here tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
"I'm quite sure that I shall obtain the support of more than 30
fellow lawmakers required for a bill submission," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Keen to See Asian Economies Stabilized, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) is
keen to see stability restored in Asia's economic and financial
markets and expects next month's second Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM)
in London would make a positive difference on the issue, said a
senior British official here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It was very much in Europe's interest to help Malaysia and
other Asian countries face financial problems, said British
Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs Derek
Fatchett in a statement issued by the British High Commission.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett said that Europe was not "just fair-weather friends",
Asia's problems were Europe's problems too.
</P>
<P>
"We are fully engaged in their resolution, not least through
our contribution toward international financial institutions, and
I fully expect involvement of our private sectors," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the EU was keen to see stability and confidence
returned to the Asian markets as the first crucial step to solving
the problem.
</P>
<P>
"With our visit, we want to send a clear message not just to
the ministers we meet but to the financial markets and to the
people of the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We want ASEM II, which is scheduled from April 2 to 4 in
London, to make a positive difference on this issue," said
Fatchett who will be reporting to EU foreign ministers on his
discussions with Malaysian leaders after his return.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett is on a day's visit here as personal emissary of
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and the special representative
of the EU presidency.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to call on Deputy Prime Minister and Finance
Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim later Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett is accompanied by Jim Cloos, an aide of European
Commission President Jacques Santer and a senior British Treasury
official on his Southeast Asian trip.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to visit Indonesia, Singapore and Thailand
after his Malaysia tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
