<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The World Health Organization (WHO) has recognized criticism
from some humanitarian groups that it adopted a discriminatory
policy in Afghanistan toward women in 1997, after the Taliban banned
women from going to hospitals. The criticism was confirmed by a WHO
report based on the result of an investigative mission in
Afghanistan, which said that the WHO adopted ``an attitude of
collaboration'' with Taliban.
</P>
<P>
-- Hardly had the ink dried from the signings on the resolution
of U.N. Security Council adopted Monday evening on Iraq when a
polemic on the exact meaning of the terms used in the resolution
resumed. The United States said that the term ``severest
consequences'' includes military reprisal.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The number of people living on minimum social benefits in
France increased by 70 percent in 15 years to stand at 3.3 million,
as one in six French families are living under poverty line.
Meanwhile, the French government spends 2,300 billion francs (380
billion U.S. dollars) each year on social aid.
</P>
<P>
-- Winston Churchill once said: ``The Balkans have an annoying
tendency to produce more history than it can consume.'' One firebox
comes after another in the region: After Croatia and Bosnia, Kosovo
could sink in its turn into war. In order to prevent a new
conflagration in the Balkans, the British Foreign Secretary will fly
to Belgrade as representative of the European Union to discuss
Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
