<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reports Steady Growth in Transportation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Transportation registered steady
development, characterized by further adjustment of network
structure to meet the market needs and improvement in the quality
of transportation service in 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released today by the State Statistics
Bureau, the added value of the two sectors was 452.5 billion yuan
in 1997, an increase of 10.7 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Progress was made in 1997 in infrastructure facilities for
railway, highway, waterway and civil aviation, resulting in a
strengthened overall transportation capacity.
</P>
<P>
Total volume of cargo transported by various means was 3,823.2
billion ton-km last year, an increase of 4.9 percent as compared
with 1996.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, the cargo transportation by railways was 1,309.8
billion ton-km, up one percent; by highways, 516.8 billion ton-km,
up 3.1 percent; by waterways, 1,935.2 billion ton-km, up 8.3
percent; and by airways, 2.9 billion ton-km, up 16.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The volume of passenger transportation was 963.7 billion
person-km, an increase of 5.3 percent. Of this total, that carried
by railway was 352.2 billion person-km, up by 5.9 percent; by
highways, 518.8 billion person-km, up 5.7 percent; by waterways,
15.3 billion person-km, down by five percent; and by civil
aviation, 77.4 billion person-km, up 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Major coastal ports handled 878.46 million tons of cargo, up
3.1 percent, of which 359.15 million tons were merchandise for
foreign trade, up 12.5 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
