<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriot Leader Refuses to Meet EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash has refused to meet European Union External Affairs
Commissioner Hans van den Broek who will arrive here later
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus Mail Wednesday quoted a spokesman for the European
Commission delegation in Cyprus as saying that a request for a
meeting between van den Broek and Denktash had been turned down
by the Turkish Cypriot side.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Turkish Cypriot leader refused to meet Britain's
special envoy for Cyprus Sir David Hannay, who paid a 24-hour
visit to the island.
</P>
<P>
Van den Broek is due to arrive on the island Wednesday night
for talks with Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Foreign
Minister Iaonnis Kasoulides on EU accession talks with Cyprus due
to begin on March 31.
</P>
<P>
Denktash told Turkey's private NTV television that he had
nothing to discuss with van den Broek.
</P>
<P>
Denktash was quoted as saying that Turkish Cypriots would never
agree to join the EU which excludes Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He said the debate on EU membership had been initiated in
order to "sabotage" the U.N.-led negotiations between the two
sides on the island.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on President Clerides' inaugural speech on Saturday,
in which he invited the Turkish Cypriot leader to build a common
homeland, Denktash said "if you invite me as a citizen of the
Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus and President Denktash, the
doors to negotiations will open."
</P>
<P>
He warned that if Clerides rejected the invitation to talk
between two states and if Cyprus' accession to the EU took place,
then the island would be divided in two.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-controlled
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and took over the northern third in the
wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a breakaway Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus, which was only recognized by
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The EU summit last December reaffirmed a decision to start
accession talks with Cyprus on March 31, a move denounced by
Denktash who took retaliatory measures, including suspension of
bicommunal contacts with the Greek Cypriot side since last
December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
