<HEADLINE> hke030431 - Australian Stocks Close Strongly Buoyed by BHP Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares closed higher
Wednesday, with a surge by BHP shares following the resignation of
managing director John Prescott propelling the market off morning
lows.
</P>
<P>
"BHP was the one that pulled (the market) up strongly," said
Associate Director of Macquarie Equities Lucinda Chan.
</P>
<P>
"BHP was the star performer today, things are beginning to look
a lot better for them," she said.
</P>
<P>
BHP surged 1.17, or 8.16 percent, higher to 15.51 Australian
dollars and at one stage reaching a high of 15.54, after the
company said it had accepted Prescott's resignation.
</P>
<P>
The company was the top traded stock with 14.43 million shares
traded worth 220.7 million Australian dollars (150 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries finished 21.0 points up at 2705.4, although
traders said they were still concerned about Asia's economic
problems. The market had little reaction however to the economic
data released on Wednesday, showing the economy is growing at a
slower pace than expected.
</P>
<P>
Australian Bureau of Statistics figures said Wednesday that the
real GDP(A) rise in the December quarter was 0.5 percent and 3.6
percent for the year of 1997 to December.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 321.06 million shares worth 871.67
million Australian dollars (592.7 million U.S. dollars), with
falls outnumbering rises 550 to 531.
</P>
<P>
Driven by BHP, the all resources index ended 29.2 points, or
2.57 percent up, at 1163.5.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index also closed firmer, up 14.6 points at
4638.2.
</P>
<P>
Shares in banks also closed up with the sub-index 26.8 points
higher at 5499.1.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed 7.0 points lower at 1116.8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
