<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reports Good Harvest in Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China saw good harvest in
agriculture in 1997, with grain output hitting 492.5 million tons,
the second highest in Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
This was the third consecutive year that China had reaped grain
harvest.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the State Statistics Bureau (SSB) attributed the
upbeat performance in crops to increased investment and broader
application of agro-sciences and technology.
</P>
<P>
SSB figures indicate that cotton output registered a slight
increase in 1997 to chalk up 4.3 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, crop structures further improved along with an
increase in the output of high-quality, brand and speciality
agro-products. Sustained growth was registered in the output of
sugar, tobacco, tea and fruit.
</P>
<P>
Influenced by market demand and supply, the output of oil crops
and hemp, however, declined.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, China's farmland irrigation made remarkable headways
as 1.21 million ha of land was converted to cultivated farmland
with effective irrigation systems. And water-saving irrigation
systems expanded by 1.23 million ha of land, saving 10 billion
cubic meters of water in the year.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture has been listed top priority in China's investment
scheme. China attracted more than three billion US dollars of
foreign funds to its agricultural sector last year.
</P>
<P>
China plans to produce 490 million tons of grain and about 4.3
million tons of cotton this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
