<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Investment Structure Sees Positive Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Positive changes had taken place
in China's investment structure as the government made efforts to
boost basic industries and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Statistics Bureau (SSB), investment in
basic industries and infrastructure, such as agriculture, energy,
transportation, and telecommunications, soared in 1997.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown of the investment indicates that input into
agriculture, forestry, animal husbandry, fishery and water
conservancy totalled 47 billion yuan in 1997, up 40 percent from
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, investment in the energy industry shot up by 21.7
percent to 357.5 billion yuan, and that in transportation and
telecommunications sectors by 14.8 percent to 328.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
A SSB spokesman said at a press conference today that growth of
investment in China's western areas accelerated thanks to
government efforts to spur the local development.
</P>
<P>
China's fixed assets investment rose 10.1 percent in 1997 to
2.53 trillion yuan and its efficiency improved.
</P>
<P>
China completed and put into operation 81,181 projects in 1997
through capital construction or technical upgrading, representing
55.8 percent of all projects under construction, up 1.6 percentage
points from 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Slumps on Weak GDP Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar slumped
following the release of disappointing national accounts figures
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar began the day on a softer tone, under
pressure from lower gold and commodity prices, and weaker Asian
currencies.
</P>
<P>
Its spirits were further dampened by the weaker-than-expected
Gross Domestic Product (GDP) data.
</P>
<P>
Colonial State Bank foreign exchange dealer Nick Volanakis said
the weak data and falling Asian currencies weighed heavily on the
Australian dollar, which slipped half a U.S. cent to close at
67.82 U.S. cents, from 68.36 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics said GDP(A) rose 0.5
percent, slightly lower than economists' forecasts which had
centered on a rise of 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
A 6.5 percent fall in spending on non-dwelling construction and
a drop of 3.7 percent in expenditure on equipment led to the
lower-than-expected outcome for GDP(A).
</P>
<P>
Economists said strong domestic demand was countered by
weakness in external trade, which clawed back two thirds of
domestic growth.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to hold the view that barring a currency collapse,
the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) is more likely to ease rates
than raise rates in the foreseeable future and this is the bias we
retain on our monetary policy call," economist Richard Yetsenga
said.
</P>
<P>
However, Yetsenga said the tone of recent RBA writings gave the
impression that the central bank sees a lower Australian dollar as
a more reasonable market/policy response to the type of problems
facing the Australian economy at present than lower interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
"As such we retain the view that the Australian dollar will at
least re-test the recent lows or make new lows over the next three
to six months," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar fell to 85.25
Japanese yen from 85.80 at the close here Tuesday, and to 1.2272
Deutsche marks from 1.2420. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
