<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Banks Lost 140 Million Rand in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Banks in South Africa lost
nearly 140 million Rand (28 million U.S. Dollars) in armed
robberies last year, local daily the Citizen reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The heavy loss is 31.5 million Rand (6.3 million dollars) more
than the amount lost in 1996, the Council of South African Banks
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The statistics released at a media conference Tuesday revealed
that the banking industry had recorded an increase in both the
number of incidents, and the amounts of money involved in
robberies.
</P>
<P>
A total of 465 robberies netting 139.9 million Rand (28
million dollars) took place last year, compared to 408 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Of the 465 incidents last year, 103 were bank-related
cash-in-transit robberies involving 64.8 million Rand (12.9
million dollars)
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that the South African banking industry
has ever released official bank robbery statistics, which,
political analysts said, was designed to draw attention to the
seriousness of the crime being committed with a view to
addressing the trend.
</P>
<P>
According to Bob Tucker, chief executive of the council, South
Africa's banks have used remote central control TV systems, time
delay locks on vaults, rapid response teams, undercounter cashier
safes, metal detectors, double lock doors, sophisticated bulk
cash containers and guards to protect staff, clients and cash.
</P>
<P>
"Despite spending more than 400 million Rand (80 million
dollars) to protect money, it is increasingly found that the
harder it is for the thieves to access cash, the more violent
their methods become," Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
As security strategies became more successful, robbers would
move on to the next weak link in the whole cash chain, including
retail operations, pension payouts and sports events where large
amounts of cash were collected, Tucker said, noting armed bank
robberies had become big business for big syndicates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
