<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka, Tehran to Enhance Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh and Iran have agreed to
strengthen bilateral trade and economic relations, the national
news agency BSS reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh was interested in expanding trade relations with
Iran as the two countries had potentialities and resources to
explore, Commerce and Industries Minister Tofail Ahmed was
reported as telling Iranian Construction Minister Mohammad Reza
Saidi Kia, who was heading a delegation at the third
Bangladesh-Iran Joint Economic Commission (JEC) meeting, on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two countries had reached agreement on cooperation in the
fields of tea, fisheries, livestock, agriculture and rural
development, the communique of the JEC conference, which ended
here Tuesday, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The two sides had also agreed to set up a joint business
council, according to the document.
</P>
<P>
They would finalize soon an accord to avoid double taxation in
trade and another on investment protection, Finance Minister Shah
A.M.S. Kibria told reporters after a separate meeting with the
Iranian minister on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to exchange information about trade, foreign
trade policies, rules and regulations. To help Bangladesh boost
its export, Iran had agreed to give overland transit to Bangladesh
for transportation of good to Central Asian countries, BSS
reported.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh exported to Iran some 53 million U.S. dollars worth
of goods, mainly tea, jute and jute products, and vegetables, and
imported from the latter petroleum products and coffee worth about
8.7 million dollars last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
