<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Chiefs Own 96% of Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Zambian chiefs own 96 percent of
land of the country, Lands Minister Samuel Miyanda has said.
</P>
<P>
The Post Wednesday quoted him as telling parliament Tuesday
that the government owns only the remainder.
</P>
<P>
He said some of the traditional rulers have recommended that
14,000 hectares in their areas be given to investors but the
government has refused and instead settled on 2,500 hectares.
</P>
<P>
He announced that his ministry will start looking at the
chiefs' boundaries to sort out the quarrels over this issue.
</P>
<P>
The last agreed note on boundaries for the chiefs was in 1940s
and nothing else ever since.
</P>
<P>
"A substantial amount of land was given out last year to
Zambians and not foreigners. There is also a special
consideration for women and vulnerable groups. We are very gender
sensitive, for example, out of 103 plots from the Lusaka South
Forestry Reserve, 33 plots have been offered to women," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that a new land circular is coming next
month which will spell out the process to be followed when
allocating land.
</P>
<P>
"My ministry will do everything possible to avail land to
Zambians to enable them to have shelter and grow food for
themselves. This is the only way we can make people rich. If
people remain poor we can not claim to have developed their
country," he said.
</P>
<P>
It is said that there are over 200 traditional leaders across
the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
