<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seepage-Proof Walls of Cofferdams in Three Gorges Project in Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Work on the seepage-proof walls of
the cofferdams up and downstream in the second phase of the Three
Gorges Water Control Project is progressing smoothly.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made by Chen Xiaolin, a woman chief engineer
and deputy head of the Three Gorges Project headquarters, who is
now in Beijing to attend the First Session of the Ninth People's
Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
On the latest developments in the construction of the project,
Chen said the temporary shiplock at the Three Gorges Project began
to be filled with water on February 28, marking a significant
progress since the damming of the Yangtze River in early November
1997. It is expected to be navigable on the first of May this
year.
</P>
<P>
Technicians and workers have tackled a series of technical
problems in building the two seepage-proof walls which cover a
total construction area of 83,500 sq. m with the maxim designed
depth of 74 m. So far, 30,000 sq. m. have been completed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, concrete has been poured into the foundation pit of
the dam project, Chen said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
