<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ranariddh Sentenced to Five-Year Imprisonment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian deposed First Prime
Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh was sentenced to a five-year
imprisonment on Wednesday by the country's Military Court on
charges of illegally purchasing and transporting weapons and
destabilizing the state.
</P>
<P>
The trial went ahead in the absence of all the three accused,
including General Nhiek Bun Chhay, the prince's top military
commander, and Thach Suong, chief of the prince's bodyguard
unit. They were sentenced to four and two years respectively, but
Thach Suong had got a probation.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh, who is currently in Bangkok, has been in exile since
being ousted after heavy fighting between the forces loyal to him
and Second Prime Minister Hun Sen last July.
</P>
<P>
Nine people appeared in court as a witness and some weapons as
a material evidence were displayed. The trial was held at the hall
of the Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's trial, along with a second hearing scheduled for
March 17, is part of a Japanese-brokered peace plan aimed at
allowing the prince to return to Cambodia in time to participate
in July's elections.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh has to obtain a pardon from his farther, King Norodom
Sihanouk, to clear the way for his participation in the upcoming
elections.
</P>
<P>
The charges against the prince arose from last May's seizure of
2.8-ton shipment of weapons and ammunitions on arrival at
Sihanoukville Port, addressed to Prince Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
The prince's cabinet in Bangkok issued a statement on the eve
of the trial, condemning the court as politically controlled and
predicting a conviction for Prince Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
The statement declared that the FUNCINPEC party would not
recognize and would flatly reject all of the trials of Prince
Ranariddh on Wednesday and any other trials in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Exporters Need to Work Harder Amidst </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Australian exporters will have to
work harder than ever to penetrate markets and establish a
competitive advantage in East Asia as well as in other markets,"
said the Trade Outcomes and Objectives Statement 1998 released
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The severe deterioration in trading conditions in East Asia
would have an adverse impact on Australian exports to the region.
Lower export earnings resulting from the Asian downturn would
affect domestic activity, creating lower corporate profitability
and higher input costs, the 265-page report said.
</P>
<P>
"The consequent slowing in output growth will affect
employment, though not until later in 1998-99 given the lags
between output variations and employment," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Tabling the document, Trade Minister Tim Fischer said in
parliament that the government saw the need to maintain momentum
for economic reform and trade liberalization as an imperative.
</P>
<P>
"The government is committed to Asia for the long haul,"
Fischer said, adding "We are talking to Australian businesses and
putting in place practical measures to assist Australian companies
over coming months."
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar's depreciation, related to Asia's
currency woes, would have a modest impact on consumer price
inflation, the document said.
</P>
<P>
Overall import prices were set to rise, as most of Australia's
imports came from countries against whose currencies the
Australian dollar had depreciated. "This will have a modest impact
on consumer price inflation," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Suppliers of raw and intermediate goods, making up the bulk of
exports, are expected to be hit the hardest in Australia, the
report added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
