<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Economic Growth Fails to Reach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Economic activity in Australia
slowed in the last three months of 1997, failing to meet
expectations that the growth would surpass the four percent
barrier, figures released Wednesday showed.
</P>
<P>
National accounts released by the Australian Bureau of
Statistics (ABS) showed that the country's annual economic growth
was 3.6 percent in 1997, well below the 4.1 percent growth
anticipated by financial markets.
</P>
<P>
The ABS survey found the economy as measured by average gross
domestic product grew by 0.5 percent, seasonally adjusted, in the
December quarter.
</P>
<P>
The quarterly rise was the lowest since the March quarter last
year and less than half the 1.1 percent recorded in the September
quarter survey.
</P>
<P>
The factors leading to the slowdown were falls in farm and
manufacturing production, wholesale trade, a decline in
investment, a slump in exports and reduced corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
Australia's annual economic growth rate was slightly below the
federal government's mid-year review forecast for 1997-98 of 3.75
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
