<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Ruling Party Slams Trade Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The ruling party Tuesday
condemned the Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions (ZCTU)-led mass
stayaway by workers and called on "patriotic" workers to report
for work Wednesday, according to the Zimbabwe News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF)
Secretary for Commissariat and Culture Moven Mahachi said ZANU
(PF) and the government were committed to solving economic
difficulties facing the country through dialogue as the stayaway
was "being instigated by self-seekers who employ intimidatory
tactics in order to foster lawlessness in the country."
</P>
<P>
"These uncalled for ultimatums, threats and work boycotts can
only succeed in hurting the workers themselves, our peasantry and
the nation as a whole," said Mahachi in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Mahachi, who is also the defense minister, said it was no
secret that the government was facing economic problems, but
these were being exacerbated by "directionless bigots" bent on
hurting the people they "purportedly represent for a few,
ill-gotten pieces of silver from their marauding masters."
</P>
<P>
He said the workers should not be woodwinked by a few
individuals whose goal was to grab at every opportunity to
undermine the democratically elected government and form their
own party to oppose the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
Mahachi said the ZCTU had developed a culture of
confrontation, anarchy and violence. The stayaway was
detrimental to the national economy hence the need for the labor
movement to engage in meaningful dialogue with the government on
their demands.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the difficulties being faced by most Zimbabweans
to the liberalization of the economy, introduced by the
government as part of the structural adjustment program in 1991.
</P>
<P>
"It is this difficult path Zimbabwe had to inevitably take in
order to keep in step with all other countries around. The only
noble way to iron out differences and disputes is through
peaceful means, and that is through dialogue," he said.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 percent of the country's industry was said to
have suffered from the stayaway organized by the ZCTU to press
the government into scrapping a 2.5 percentage sales tax effected
late last year, remove developmental levy, reduce the prices of
all basic commodities and other demands affecting the workers.
The two-day national strike started Tuesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
