<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Financial Sector Maintains Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- China's financial sector
maintained stable in 1997, according to statistics released here
today by the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, the savings deposits by the urban and rural
residents reached 4,628 billion yuan, up 19.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the banks issued 7,491.4 billion yuan of loans, up
16.7 percent, in which, 5,541.8 billion yuan was issued in the
form of short-term loans and 1,549.6 billion yuan in the form of
mid and long-term loans.
</P>
<P>
The cash money in circulation (M0) was 1,017.8 billion yuan by
the end of 1997, up 15.6 percent, said the statistics bureau.
</P>
<P>
Major problems existed in banking services included a
relatively high portion of bad loans by state banks, problems
related with non-banking financial institutions, and banking
business undertaken directly or in disguise by illegal financial
institutions established by some local governments or
departments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
