<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Child Labor Convention to be Adopted in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A new international convention
for child labor elimination is to be adopted in 1999, it is
disclosed at a press conference held here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The draft convention on the most intolerable forms of child
labor is currently under discussion, said a press release issued
by the Global March Against Child Labor '98.
</P>
<P>
The global march team, which started in Manila, Philippines on
January 17, arrived in Nepal on 26 February and in Kathmandu
Tuesday after touring Hong Kong, Vietnam, Cambodia, Thailand,
Malaysia, Singapore and Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
During its week-long travel throughout Nepal, the 63-member
team including 30 children and 33 adults from 12 countries and
regions attended press meetings, mass rally, culture and talk
programs, exhibitions and other activities.
</P>
<P>
The march has captured the support of thousands of people and
organizations along the way, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
The global march against child labor, the greatest ever
mobilization of its kind, aims to mobilize worldwide efforts to
protect and promote the rights of all children, especially the
right to receive a free, meaningful education and to be free from
economic exploitation and from performing any work that is likely
to be damaging their physical, mental, spiritual, moral or social
development, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
Two other parallel march teams, which originated from Cape
Town, South Africa and Rio De Janerio, Brazil respectively, are
winding their way through Africa, Latin America, North America and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
The march will culminate in June at the opening of the
International Labor Conference in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
The press release said in the world today, about 250 million
children are the victims of child labor exploitation, of which
South Asia accounts for 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
And in Nepal, there are at least one million child workers and
40,000 are bonded laborers.
</P>
<P>
Children from different countries told the press conference
that they want to go to school, play and have a rest instead of to
work.
</P>
<P>
A total of 120 members of Nepal's parliament have pledged their
solidarity and commitment in the global march.
</P>
<P>
The team is scheduled to march toward India Thursday, then
toward Pakistan and some European countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
