<HEADLINE> Brain Drain in S. Africa Doubles in Past 7 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The number of teachers who
left South Africa doubled over the past seven months, The Star
daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
From January 1994 to August 1997, every day one South African
teacher was on a plane out of South Africa to take up a position
in an overseas school.
</P>
<P>
But over the past seven months, about 50 and 60 teachers are
leaving every month, the paper quoted figures of the Central
Statistical Service as showing.
</P>
<P>
Bheki Khumalo, spokesman of Education Minister Sibusiso Bengu,
said nothing could be done to stop people from pursuing their
careers overseas.
</P>
<P>
To concerns that the teachers who were leaving were the most
experienced, he said: "We have a number of teacher development
programs in place."
</P>
<P>
Many of the 1,250 teachers who emigrated between January 1994
and August 1997 are in New Zealand, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
