<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Appoints Kokoshin New Security Council Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Andrei Kokoshin, Russia's chief
military inspector, was appointed Tuesday by President Boris
Yeltsin as new head of the nation's Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky told a briefing in the
Kremlin that the Defense Council where Kokoshin served as
secretary was abolished by the president.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Chief Military Inspectorate was integrated into
the Security Council, Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
Kokoshin was born in Moscow in 1945 and graduated from the
Bauman Higher Technical school as a computer engineer in 1969.
</P>
<P>
He finished graduate studies at the U.S. and Canada Institute
of the USSR Academy of Sciences and became deputy director of
the institute in the former Soviet Union in 1984.
</P>
<P>
In April 1992, Kokoshin was appointed as first deputy defense
minister. He has been state secretary and first deputy defense
minister since January 1996.
</P>
<P>
Former secretary of the Russian Security Council, Ivan Rybkin,
was appointed as deputy prime minister on Monday. 
</P>
