<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Feature: A Little Square Blanket of Uygur NPC Deputy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Sadik Karihaji, a deputy of Uygur
ethnic group to the First Session of the Ninth National People
Congress (NPC), performed five religious services a day in his
room at the Jingxi Hotel in western Beijing since his arrival.
</P>
<P>
Pointing to the green square blanket inlaid with a yellow lace
at his bedside, Sadik said, "The blanket is used specially to
perform services and I have brought it here whenever I come to
attend a NPC session."
</P>
<P>
Sadik, 66, has been serving as an imam at the Aitika Mosque in
Kashgar, northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous region, for
three years.
</P>
<P>
He bought the pure-wool blanket when he was elected a deputy
to the Eighth National People's Congress in 1993 for the first
time. Today, the blanket still looks neat, simple yet elegant,
though it has been used on many times.
</P>
<P>
His roommate, Yusuyin Yusut, secretary of Xinjiang's Yusuin
Township Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC),
witnesses what Sadik does everyday.
</P>
<P>
"China practices a policy of freedom in religious belief.
so everyone is free to believe or not to believe in religion,"
Yusuyin said.
</P>
<P>
"As a member of the Communist Party, I myself don't believe in
religion. And the Koran doesn't compel anyone to join in the ranks
of believers either," he added.
</P>
<P>
Sadik leads more than 2,000 Moslems to eulogize Allah at the
25,000-sq-m mosque in his hometown daily and, on every Friday, as
many as 10,000 believers flock to the mosque for the service.
During Islamic festival, his recitations can reach more than
70,000 attendants through audio amplifiers.
</P>
<P>
He is concurrently president of a Koran school, which has 140
students.
</P>
<P>
"Our lawful rights and interests are protected by the
government," Sadik said. Islam encourages its followers to work
hard and honestly, and become, which complies with the relevant
government policy.
</P>
<P>
In the capacity of a NPC deputy from the religious circle,
Sadik pays attention all the more to poverty-alleviation measures
that are included in the government report. As he does not know
the Han or Chinese Language, he got a copy of the government
report in Uygur language.
</P>
<P>
"As far as I know, quite a number of imams deputies from Gansu
and Henan provinces and Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, where
Moslem people live in compact community, will not suspend their
religious services during the NPC session," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
