<HEADLINE> Kenyan Port Congestion Causes Huge Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 4 (Xinhua) -- More than 16 vessels are waiting
to discharge their cargo at the already congested port of
Mombasa, causing huge losses, according to the Kenya Ports
Authority (KPA).
</P>
<P>
Shipping lines said Tuesday that they were losing some 100
million Kenyan Shillings (about 1.7 million U.S. Dollars) every
week due to the current ship congestion and cargo build-up at the
port which has more than 3,500 uncollected container boxes.
</P>
<P>
Captain B. Healy of African Liners Agencies Ltd. said that
some of the waiting vessels arrived on February 22, the Daily
Nation Wednesday quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Officials from shipping lines blamed the congestion problem at
the port on a massive breakdown of handling equipment while KPA
officials stated that the build-up of cargo and vessels at the
port was due to the rehabilitation work going on at one berth.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to alleviate the congestion, KPA has converted
four berths, which are supposed to handle conventional cargo, to
handling containerized goods, KPA official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
