<HEADLINE> Tianjin Expects To Be International Production Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Northern China's largest port,
Tianjin, expects to increase the use of investment from
multinationals to make itself into their international production
base.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, 199 multinationals had decided to invest
8.3 billion US dollars in 311 projects in the city. As a result, a
number of small and medium-sized enterprises have grown up
providing them with parts valued at 7.5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin is one of China's leading coastal cities in terms of
overseas investment. By the end of 1997, it had 11,522
overseas-funded enterprises, with overseas investment worth nearly
20 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Improved investment and other conditions provide a good way to
attract more investment from multinationals, according to
Vice-mayor Ye Disheng.
</P>
<P>
Of the US's ten biggest companies, six have put investment in
Tianjin, and some, like Otis and Motorola, have used Tianjin as an
Asian production base.
</P>
<P>
The city will increase economic cooperation and exchanges with
the U.S., Britain, France and Germany this year and increase the
use of overseas funds in automobiles, electronics, chemicals,
metallurgy, and textiles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
