<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Leader Attends NPC Session in Non-Voting Capacity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee-hwa, chief executive of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, will attend the First
Session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) scheduled to
open tomorrow, according to an NPC spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"Mr Tung will be present at the congress in a non-voting
capacity," NPC session spokesman Zen Jianhui told a press
conference this morning. "This will help him acquire a better
understanding of the country's conditions and better implement the
'one country, two systems' policy."
</P>
<P>
Responding to a Hong Kong reporter's question about whether or
not there are any differences in obligations and duties between
Hong Kong deputies and their mainland counterparts, Zeng said
that, like their counterparts in the mainland, deputies from Hong
Kong will participate in the work of China's top legislature and
take part in the administration of state affairs.
</P>
<P>
They also have the same rights and obligations as their
mainland counterparts when the NPC is or is not in session, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong deputies can take part in drafting motions on
amending the Basic Law of the HKSAR and be on election committees
whose functions are to elect the HKSAR chief executive and HKSAR
Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman pointed out, according to the policies
of "one country, two systems," "Hong Kong people governing Hong
Kong" and a high degree of autonomy for Hong Kong, NPC deputies,
from the mainland and Hong Kong alike, do not have the right and
obligation to exercise supervision over the work of HKSAR
government, nor can they interfere with HKSAR's affairs within the
scope of its administrative autonomy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
