<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Strengthens Blindness Prevention Program in Rural Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government will
emphasize the prevention of blindness among rural residents in
regions inhabited by ethnic minority groups and border areas.
</P>
<P>
The information was released from an ongoing three-day
international symposium on preventing blindness in China, which
opened here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ministry of Health official Liu Keling said at the
symposium that Chinese urban residents enjoy better medical
conditions for treating eye diseases than those living in rural
areas, where the incidence of eye diseases is higher because of
cultural and hygienic reasons.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that one-third of the country's more than 2,400
counties have no ophthalmologists or are not capable of operating
on patients with eye diseases.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has done a great deal to resolve this
problem. Each year, medical groups are sent to rural areas and
border areas to perform eye operations and publicize the knowledge
about eye diseases, in addition to providing medical instruments
and helping train medical workers.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has actively cooperated with the World
Health Organization (WHO) and other international bodies in
preventing blindness, and has plans to equip 100 county-level
hospitals with ophthalmology departments, more than 10,000
ophthalmological workers and 4,000 eye doctors by the year
2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
