<HEADLINE> Top Seed Philippoussis Advances in Scottsdale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Mark Philippoussis of
Australia advanced to the second round of the Franklin Templeton
Classic men's tennis tournament by beating Argentina's qualifier
Franco Squillari, 6-2, 7-5, in Scottsdale, the United States on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The big-serve Australian did not use his powerful service -- he
just fired 10 aces including a cannon of 220 kilometers per hour
(137 mile per hour) -- but the quality groundstrokes to blow out
his left-hander opponent.
</P>
<P>
Philippoussis, ranked 13th in the world, who beat Michael Chang
in Memphis final last month, broke in the third game in the first
set and the 11th in the second, which was enough for him to see
off his 92nd-ranked contester in one hour.
</P>
<P>
Philippoussis next faces Tommy Haas, who defeated
country-fellow German Michael Joyce 6-2, 6-2 in another
first-round match.
</P>
<P>
But the tournament lost Boris Becker of Germany who had pulled
out of the tournament because of a back injury.
</P>
<P>
The former world number one was scheduled to play Germany's
Nicolas Kiefer, current German number one player who ranked 28th
in the world and seeded fourth in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
Becker, six-time Grand Slam singles champion, lost his doubles
first-round match with partner Thomas Messmer to Americans Dave
Randall and Jack Waiter, 6-2, 6-0 on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year-old, ranked 66th in the world currently, will be
replaced by Scott Draper of Australia, ranked 80th in the world.
</P>
