<HEADLINE> Service Sector Leading Contributor of Shanghai Revenues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, an economic powerhouse
in China, registered 73.39 billion yuan in revenues last year,
55.4 percent of which were from the local service sector.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time the service sector replaced the local
industry as the largest contributor to the city's coffers,
according to the Municipal Bureau of Finance.
</P>
<P>
This is a great change from the years before 1990, when more
than 70 percent of local revenues came from the industrial
sector. The change also reflects local efforts to restructure
economic setups.
</P>
<P>
The service sector now accounts for 45.5 percent of the local
gross domestic product (GDP), partly because of the speedy
development of local finance-related and insurance businesses
during recent years.
</P>
<P>
Financial revenues collected from local finance and insurance
businesses were 17.7 billion yuan last year, 2.1 times the 1996
figure.
</P>
<P>
Local service sectors such as domestic trade, transportation,
postal and telecommunications, tourism and real estate also
maintained a fast-growing momentum.
</P>
<P>
Transportation, postal and telecommunications, and tourism paid
more than two billion yuan in taxes in 1997, up more than 20 percent
from 1996.
</P>
<P>
Because of further improvement of the local economic framework,
the service sector is expected to account for 60 percent of local
revenues by the turn of the century, with industry accounting for
39 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
