<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Race For Government Formation Gears Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 4 (Xinhua) -- With the counting of votes from
India`s general election is inching towards the finale, the race
for formation of a new government has geared up among major
political players in the country,
</P>
<P>
Of 525 out of 535 seats declared Wednesday morning, the
Bharatiya Janata Party(BJP) and its allies secured 248 seats while
the Congress and its allies won 167, the United Front got 92 and
the remaining 18 went to others.
</P>
<P>
As expected, non of the major forces in India's political arena
passed the crucial figure of 273 in the Lok Sabha(the Lower House
of Parliament) to form a government independently.
</P>
<P>
To get the majority for government formation, both the BJP-led
alliance as well as the Congress and the United Front have geared
up their efforts to seek new allies in smaller parties and groups.
</P>
<P>
BJP General Secretary and Spokesman Venkaiah Naidu vowed
Tuesday to form the next government, saying that "what we need is
just about 20 more MPs and there are groups and parties which are
committed to anti-congressism."
</P>
<P>
BJP leaders said it had already identified new allies who would
not want to see the Congress at the center.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Congress and the main constituents of the
outgoing United Front favored a coalition of all secular forces to
keep the BJP, Labeled "communal forces", and its allies out of
power.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of both the Congress and the United Front spoke in
conciliatory terms vowing to form a government jointly.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Indian President Kocheril Raman Narayanan
was busy studying the complicated situation and preparing for an
exercise that would give the country a measure of political
stability.
</P>
<P>
"With a hung House, the ball is now in the Presidents court",
said the Times of India in its front page article.
</P>
<P>
With political stability for the country as his watch word,
President Narayanan is understood to be pondering over various
permutations and combinations whereby he can swear in a government
at the center that will last long enough.
</P>
<P>
The president is already in touch with the Attorney-General
Ashok Desai and other experts on constitutional issues.
</P>
<P>
Narayanan is believed to favor the participation in the
government by all parties so that none has the licence and the
advantage to pull it down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northern Chinese Railway Repays World Bank Loans On Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A railway line in China's Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region introducing a new system of independent
operation and responsibility for profit and loss has been able to
repay the World Bank loans on time.
</P>
<P>
The 945-km Jining-Tongliao railway is China's longest raiway
line operated in the form of Sino-foreign joint venture. It was
built by Inner Mongolia and China's Railway Ministry with 150
million U.S. dollars (1.2 billion yuan) in WB loans. It began
service on December 1, 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to a company executive, the operator had originally
expected to start repayment of the loans in 1995 and pay back the
total amount by 2009, based on the fact that the railway runs
through the backward pastureland area in Inner Mongolia which had an
anticipated severe shortage of freight for about five years.
</P>
<P>
However, The introduction of the new responsibility system has
given free rein to the management advantage and the operator had a
good economic performance. As a result, the company repaid the
loans as planned for three years running. Last November, the
company paid back 121 million yuan of the principal and the
interest to the WB.
</P>
<P>
The company carried 4.8 million tons of goods and achieved a
rough balance of profit and loss in the first year of operation
and reported an increase of 2.5 million tons in freight volume,
and earnings of 530 million yuan in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
