<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese City Using Foreign Loans For Urban Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The capital of Hainan Province,
China's largest special economic zone, is using more foreign
government loans to improve its infrastructure, which is not
meeting its rapid economic growth needs.
</P>
<P>
The Mipu Waterworks project for improving the water supply and
protecting underground water resources is one example. It got
moving again after being delayed because of a shortage of funds
after it got a German government loan for 7.3-million Deutsch
marks. It is now at the installation stage and will increase the
clean water capacity to 240,000 tons per month.
</P>
<P>
A bridge connecting Haidian Islet to the city proper will use a
50-million-US-dollar loan provided by the Japanese
government. Twenty-three domestic and foreign companies are
expected to compete in the public bidding.
</P>
<P>
The Meishe River, which runs through the city and is seriously
polluted, is another example. Pollution treatment has long been
delayed, again due to lack of money, and has aroused serious
complaints, but the first phase of treatment of the 5-km
watercourse is about to begin with the help of 4.9 million US
dollars from the Republic of Korean government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
