<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nazarbayev: Kazakhstan Sees Agreement with Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh president Nursultan
Nazarbayev said Tuesday that Alma Ata and Moscow should agree this
year on economic measures to improve trade.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev said at a meeting on Tuesday with visiting Russian
Minister of Cooperation with CIS Countries Anatoly Adamishin that
a series of documents on improving mutual cooperation were signed
when Russian government leaders visited Kazakhstan in 1997.
</P>
<P>
These documents laid sound foundation for the economic
integration of the two countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries plunged by 14.3 percent in 1996
due to their different taxation policies, but Nazarbayev claimed
the issue should be solved this year.
</P>
<P>
Russia and Kazakhstan were still at odds over the payback of
rent on Baikonur Cosmodrome owed to Kazakhstan by Russia, which
totals 460 million U.S. dollars, and the 27.5 million dollar debt
for the use of Kazakh facilities for military tests.
</P>
<P>
But Adamishin said he believed the problem could be solved to
both sides' satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that an identical stance on the legal status
of Caspian Sea would be helpful in finding a solution to the
problem.
</P>
<P>
The summit of the government heads of the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) scheduled for mid-March will make the
future of CIS clearer, said Adamishin. Currently all member states
wanted the CIS to continue but thought reforms should be made with
economic integration and a regional common market taking
priority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
