<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belarussian President Says CIS Leaders Obstruct Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Belarussian President Alexander
Lukashenko said Tuesday that heads of the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) have become a major obstruction to
accelerating CIS development.
</P>
<P>
The ITAR-Tass news agency reported that Lukashenko made the
remarks in Minsk, the capital of Belarussia, during an
international meeting on problems and prospects in the CIS.
</P>
<P>
He said the loose alliance of former Soviet republics was a
failure. The disintegration of the Soviet Union was the biggest
disaster of geopolitics in the 20th century. It has also caused
catastrophic economic results. The destruction of the former
union's combined efforts result in a loss of more than 10 billion
U.S. dollars each year.
</P>
<P>
But the CIS has failed to play a constructive role in
preventing or softening the bad results, the Belarussian president
said.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko also complained that the CIS nations have different
views on NATO's eastward expansion. None of the members of the
CIS, except Russia and Belarussia, have expressed opposition to
the NATO expansion publicly.
</P>
<P>
The CIS was formed after the former Soviet Union disintegrated
in 1991. The CIS united all former Soviet republics except the
three Baltic nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
