<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rival U.S. Soft-Drink Makers Claim Bigger Share in Arab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Both Coca-Cola Co. and PepsiCo
Inc. claimed Tuesday that they had the biggest chunk of soft-drink
sales in the Arab market.
</P>
<P>
"Coca-Cola Co. has taken market leadership in the Middle East
and North Africa region, an area long dominated by competition,"
Coca-Cola company said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement added that Coca-Cola products now represented 38
percent of total regional sales, while Pepsi has only 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
PepsiCo spokesman Keith Hughes, however, said his company has
46 percent of total regional sales, adding that in the market of
the Middle East -- the Gulf states and the eastern Mediterranean,
including Jordan and Lebanon -- "We have roughly 73 percent
vs. their 22 percent."
</P>
<P>
Arab countries boycotted Coca-Cola products until late 1980s
because of the company supplied its financial support for Israel.
The company returned to the Arab market following the start of
current peaceful negotiations between Israel and Arab leaders in
1991.
</P>
<P>
Coca-Cola said it had invested 400 million U.S. dollars in the
Arab market over the past five years and plans to spend 200
million U.S. dollars more in the region in the next three years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
