<HEADLINE> Compaq Reduces U.S. Prices for Its Notebooks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Compaq Computer Corp.
announced Tuesday that it had cut U.S. prices for its Armada
notebook line.
</P>
<P>
The price for Armada 7750MT was cut to 3,499 U.S. dollars from
3,699 U.S. dollars, by 5.4 percent, while the price for Armada
4131T was reduced to 999 U.S. dollars from 1,699 U.S. dollars, by
up to 41.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
With the purchase of certain Armada models, the world's largest
supplier of personal computers also added incentives, including
free memory upgrades, discounts on its Armada Station desktop
expansion base, and free mobile CD units, the company said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the company released later in the day a 749
U.S. dollar personal computer to boost its market share in Europe
and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The low-priced machine is the Deskpro 1000 which uses a
200-megahertz Pentium processor with MMX multimedia technology --
one of Intel Corp's low-end chips -- and comes with 16 megabytes
of memory, half the memory of most PCs sold in the United States
and West Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
