<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Business Failures Increase 16 Percent, Survey Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. business failures jumped
16 percent last year after two years of little change, according
to a survey conducted by Dun &AMP; Bradstreet Corp.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, business failures totaled 83,384 in 1997, as every
industry group except mining and wholesale companies posted an
increase, the survey said. The number of business failures
climbed 19 percent to 20,089 from 16,879 in California.
</P>
<P>
The number of business failures should rise in the next few
years, as more new companies enter the market, said Joseph Duncan,
chief economic advisor for Dun &AMP; Bradstreet, adding that stiff
competition is expected ahead.
</P>
<P>
He said that even though the number of failures is now
approaching the high levels reached during the recession of the
early 1990s, the economic impact is subdued because company
liabilities, or debt, remain at low levels.
</P>
<P>
Liabilities from the failures soared 27 percent to 37.4 billion
U.S. dollars nationwide while rising 5.1 percent in California to
5.71 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
