<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chuan Backs Britain's Asia-Europe Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will give support to the
Asia-Europe Fund proposed by Britain, Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
said during a meeting with visiting British Foreign Secretary
Derek Fatchett Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The fund will top the agenda of the second summit of
Asia-Europe meeting in London next month, the Nation newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Prime Minister Chuan stressed that such a
fund should include a guarantee facility for private-sector
liquidity flow.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett also held a separate meeting with his Thai counterpart
Surin Pitsuwan, during which Surin also highlighted that the
proposed fund should reflect more dynamism and concreteness to
help reduce the private sector's financial burden by providing
export guarantees and liquidity support.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett said that Britain would contribute 5 million Pounds
(8.3 million U.S. dollars) to the fund. He added that the proposal
has obtained support from Scandinavian countries including Sweden
and Denmark.
</P>
<P>
The British foreign secretary said he will make the proposal at
the EU ministerial meeting in Edinburgh on March 13.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett's trip to Thailand as the emissary of British Prime
Minister Tony Blair and the 15-member European Union (EU) was part
of a fact-finding mission, which will also take him to Malaysia,
Indonesia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
He also came here to launch the "UK in Asia" campaign which
aimed to strengthen political and economic ties between the United
Kingdom and Asia.
</P>
<P>
Turmoil in Asia would be a key issue at the Asia-Europe summit
meeting since Asia's problems were now Europe's problems, he said
at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett also told Prime Minister Chuan that Britain, which is
Thailand's largest trading partner in EU, was considering helping
roll over Thai private-sector debts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
