<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stock Exchange of Thailand's Reform Plan Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A reform plan aiming to make the
Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) a self-regulating body won
approval from the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) Board,
a newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The SEC Tuesday approved amendments to encourage market reform,
under a program funded by a 300-million-U.S. dollar loan from the
Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
A key objective of the reform is to increase the independence
of the SEC and to make SET a self-regulating organization.
</P>
<P>
The number of SEC directors from the civil service will be
limited, the Bangkok Post newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The SEC also approved other changes, including rules
encouraging development of the provident fund sector, fairer
treatment for clients of securities brokerages, establishment of
more credit-rating agencies, improved disclosure of financial
information and higher penalties for insider trading.
</P>
<P>
The SEC announced that local securities firms would be allowed
to open more branch offices to better service investors.
</P>
<P>
There are now 139 brokerage offices, consisting of 41 head
offices, five branch offices and 93 representative offices.
</P>
<P>
The amendments passed by the SEC board will be forwarded to the
cabinet for formal approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
