<HEADLINE> Coca-Cola: Sales Increase 30 Percent in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Coca-Cola Co. announced
Tuesday that it has expanded its infrastructure in China and that
sales volume jumped by 30 percent last year in the world's most
populous country.
</P>
<P>
China has grown to become one of Coke's top 10 volume markets,
and the average Chinese resident drinks six eight-ounce servings
of Coke products annually, said Douglas Invester, who succeeded
the late Roberto Goizueta as chairman and chief executive of the
company.
</P>
<P>
He said his company will have 27 production facilities up and
running in China by mid-1998, and more than 180 new distribution
centers are slated to open there by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Coke's 1997 annual report, released earlier, said the company's
worldwide sales volume last year grew 9 percent, to 14.9 billion
cases, while net income rose 18 percent, to 4.13 billion
U.S. dollars, following 19 percent jumps in each of the last two
years.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of Coca-Cola's sales volume comes from
abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
