<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SFOR Not to Intervene In Kosovo Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, March 3 (Xinhua) --The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) forces in Bosnia-Herzegovina will not
intervene in the latest Kosovo conflict as their mandate is
restricted to Bosnia-Herzegovina and Croatia, said a Stablization
Force (SFOR) spokesman Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian News Agency quoted Luois Garneau as saying that
events in Kosovo were cause for concern in the international
community, but the NATO headquarters, and not SFOR, were
responsible for analyzing the situation.
</P>
<P>
"We do not have plans to station our soldiers in Kosovo. It is
not our job but the NATO's," he said, adding that the current
mandate excludes involvement in Kosovo or Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Tension in Kosovo was raised on March 1 after an escalation of
an armed conflict between Serbian police and local ethnic
Albanians, leading to the deaths of four policemen and 16
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo has a 90 percent ethnic Albanian majority which has been
seeking independence from Yugoslavia since 1981. 
</P>
</TEXT>
