<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Arable Land Protected in South China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 4 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong Province
has taken effective measures to protect its arable land, resulting
in increasing 60,000 hectares of arable land in the last five
years.
</P>
<P>
Each resident in Guangdong possesses an average of 0.03 hectare
of arable land, less than half that of the whole country. With the
development of city construction and industrial exploitation,
arable land tends to decrease.
</P>
<P>
To cope with such a situation, Guangdong Province has set up
special organizations responsible for land resources management
and set aside 37,000 hectares of land previously not for farming
use for agricultural purpose.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996, the provincial government has invested 50 million
yuan annually to encourage land exploitation. Favorable policies
were instituted to encourage people to exploit arable land.
</P>
<P>
Those who exploit arable land can use and benefit from it, and
are free from agriculture taxes for three-to-five years.
</P>
<P>
The province also established agricultural development
centers. Until now, Guangdong had conceived 100 projects to
develop arable land, and is concentrating on exploiting
wasteland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Provides new Loan to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government has
provided Indonesia with a 20 billion yen (158 million U.S.
dollars) quick disbursement loan to support the country's human
resource development, sources at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs
said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The new loan, in the form of a sector program loan, was handed
over Indonesia Tuesday by Japanese Ambassador here, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The loan supplements a 195.2 billion yen (1.5 billion U.S.
dollars) overseas development assistance package announced by
Japan during the Consultative Group for Indonesia's (CGI) sixth
meeting in last June in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Part of the new loan would be used to finance small projects
for education and human resources development training, social
welfare and health care.
</P>
<P>
the loan is payable in 30 years, including a grace period of 10
years, with an interest rate of 2.2 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
Japan is the largest single creditor to Indonesia. For the
1997/98 fiscal year (starting from April 1), Japan pledged 215.2
billion yen in new loans through the CGI creditor consortium to
Indonesia, despite its plan to slash its official development
assistance (ODA) worldwide by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia received 190.1 billion yen in Japanese ODA loans in
1996/97 and 170.1 billion yen in 1995/96. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
