<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese Gulf Area Economically Active Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Coastal parts of China's Beibu Gulf
in Guangdong and Hainan provinces and the Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region, which suffered from a bubble economy in the
1990s, especially in real estate, are beginning to be active
again.
</P>
<P>
Hainan had only 4.3 percent economic growth in 1995, one of the
country's lowest figures, but last year, the economy of the island
province, which is China's largest special economic zone, grew 6.7
percent and it is expected to average 8 percent over the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
The rosy outlook is due partly to a southwestern seaway that is
taking shape in the area, according to Tao Bohua, a research
fellow at the Hainan Beibu Gulf Research Institute, who says that
the economy in the area has bottomed out and is beginning an
upward movement.
</P>
<P>
The official opening of the Nanning-Kunming Railway in 1997
also greatly raised the gulf's economic status, especially among
coastal regions, and port cities are improving infrastructure for
better development. Guangdong's Zhanjiang Harbor now has 18
million tons in annual handling capacity, and Guangxi's Fangcheng
has increased its handling capacity to 8.5 million tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
