<HEADLINE> Girls In Southwestern China Get Assistance In Returning To School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The women's federation of China's
poorest province has helped 11,000 girls who dropped out of school
resume their studies, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The southwestern province has gotten funds for special classes
for the girls, most of whom are from minority groups, in 30
poverty-ridden counties. Last year, there were 136 new 'Spring
Bud' classes, as part of this national program to educate girls.
</P>
<P>
The poverty relief program gets help not just from local people
and the government. One soldier in northwest China's Gansu
Province sent 1,000 yuan by mail to ten Miao minority girls to
help them continue their education, said Li Guihua, of the Guizhou
Women's Federation. Australia also plans to help support 150 poor
girls, she said.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou still has four million poor people living below the
poverty line, and has tried everything to help girls who have
dropped out even though it lacks funds, Li said, and collected
500,000 yuan (about 60,000 US dollars) in 1997, providing funding
for 7,000 more girls than the year before.  
</P>
</TEXT>
