<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Celebrates National Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria celebrated its national day
on Tuesday and the 120th anniversary of independence from the
Ottoman Empire with a declaration of its own sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
President Peter Stoyanov told a gathering of senior officials
and foreign dignitaries in Sofia that the new national ideal is to
"build an independent, proud, sovereign Bulgaria in the family of
European nations."
</P>
<P>
"The historical conditions are favorable, as never before, to
realize this new Bulgarian national ideal," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Today Bulgaria faces new challenges and, unlike 120 years ago,
we can easily free ourselves from the predetermining of our fate
by the great powers," he added.
</P>
<P>
On March 3, 1878, Russia and Turkey signed the San Stefano
peace treaty, putting an end to the Russo-Turkish War and
emancipating Bulgaria after nearly 500 years of rule by the
Ottoman Empire.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria would also try to build economic prosperity and to
protect Bulgarians living abroad, Stoyanov added.
</P>
<P>
The president also paid his respect to the thousands Bulgarians
and Russian, Romanian, Finish, Ukrainian and Belarus soldiers and
officers who gave their lives for Bulgaria's liberty.
</P>
<P>
The national holiday was marked with religious ceremonies being
held in almost all Eastern Orthodox churches.
</P>
<P>
The celebrations started with a flag raising ceremony in front
of the monument to the unknown soldier in Sofia where President
Stoyanov and Parliamentary Chairman Yordan Sokolov laid wreaths.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
