<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soros Considering Investing in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 4 (Xinhua) -- George Soros, the U.S. financier
accused by some Asian countries of triggering the region's
financial crisis, is hunting for bargains in Thailand, a newspaper
report said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Soros is one of several U.S. investors considering pumping 650
million dollars into the Thai Nakornthai Strip Mill.
</P>
<P>
A Soros fund last week also bought a five-percent stake in the
Thai electronics company GSS Array Technology PCL, which makes and
exports consumer electronics components, the Bangkok Post
reported.
</P>
<P>
Soros runs a group of hedge funds that include the
8.4-billion-dollar quantum fund, the world's biggest.
</P>
<P>
Soros' funds scaled down their investments in the region after
the currency crisis began in Thailand last July. Investors in Asia
and elsewhere tend to place great faith in his judgment.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's stock market, for example, rocketed in December
after Soros said he was comteplating new investment there.
</P>
<P>
Soros has not publicly expressed an opinion on the health of
Thailand's financial market. But despite Soros' reported intention
to invest in Thailand and purchase of some of the GSS Array's
stake, Thailand's stock market ended mixed Tuesday and GSS Array's
price fell six baht to 184 baht a share.
</P>
<P>
The price, however, reflected a 27-percent gain since February
20 when Soros's Quantum Emerging Growth Fund reported to the stock
exchange of Thailand that it had bought about one million GSS
Array shares at 145 baht apiece.
</P>
<P>
Nakornthai Strip Mill's stock also declined Tuesday, closing
at 8.20 baht a share, down 0.20 baht.
</P>
<P>
Southeast Asian leaders, notably Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad, accused Soros of sparking Asia's economic crisis
by speculating on regional currencies and stampeding investors
into a sell-off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
