<HEADLINE> New Voting System Guarantees Deputies' Lawful Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua)-- A new electronic voting system to
be put to use at the forthcoming National People's Congress (NPC)
is highly reliable, and above all, confidential, according to a
senior technician serving the congress.
</P>
<P>
"The software of the system is designed to make it impossible
to track down any individual deputy's voting options," said Tao
Mingguo who is in charge of revamping an earlier obsolete
conference management system at the Great Hall of the People, the
venue of the counntry's high-level Party and government meetings,
including annual NPC sessions.
</P>
<P>
"Use of the system will allay concerns of some deputies who
feared that their voting choices could be monitored and traced,"
said Tao. "The confidential nature of the system ensures that
duputies'lawful rights be fully protected."
</P>
<P>
The Ninth NPC is to convene its first session from March 5 to
through 19, during which deputies will elect or confirm new
government leaders, including the president, the premier and
ministers, through secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the voting system, updated conference facilities
include a registration system, a vote-casting system and a
display system.
</P>
<P>
For the display system, two 150-inch color projection screens
have replaced old monochrome display boards at both sides of the
podium of the central meeting hall, which can not only show the
voting results but also pictures, photos and documentaries.
</P>
<P>
"The Great Hall of the People now has a first-class
computerized conference management system," said Tao.
</P>
<P>
A computer system serving the congress has also been updated.
The system with a dozen terminals in the Great Hall of the People
has more than 10 data banks which make accessible to deputies a
large amount of information covering national laws and
regulations, major national and provincial economic statistics and
namelists of central and local government officials, among others.
</P>
<P>
An official with the NPC information center said that technically
people can access the Internet through the computer system. "Hopely the
day will soon come when deputies can browse the Internet through our
system," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
