<HEADLINE> Alatas Denies Rumors on US Military base in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia has denied rumors that
the United States is planning to have a military base in
Indonesia, arguing that allowing a foreign power to set up such a
base would violate a national political principle.
</P>
<P>
"There has not been and there never will be such a request. It
there is, it is clear that Indonesia will reject it," official
Antara news agency Wednesday quoted Foreign Ministry Ali Alatas as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's foreign policy does not allow any foreign military
base within the country. "It's only a rumor ... there is no
foreign military base," the minister said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Defense and Security Minister Edi Sudradjat also
denied the reports that the United States has set up naval bases
in Biak and Natuna islands.
</P>
<P>
"That is a forbidden policy. Indonesia is a sovereign nation,
so it is impossible for foreigners to install military bases," he
said Tuesday on the sidelines of the People's Consultative
Assembly's session here.
</P>
<P>
Some reports said earlier that U.S. President Bill Clinton's
special envoy Walter Mondale, who arrived here on Monday for a
two-day visit, would discuss political issues including setting up
military bases here with the Indonesian government.
</P>
<P>
Mondale, Former vice president in Jimmy Carter's
administration, met with President Soeharto here Tuesday. They
only talked about the economic crisis in Indonesia and bilateral
relations during their 90-minute meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
