<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based Newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The First Session of the Ninth National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) opened
in Beijing yesterday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan, Executive Chairman of the session's presidium,
declared the session open.
</P>
<P>
Ye Xuanping, Vice-Chairman of the Eighth National Committee of
CPPCC, said at the session that the country's top advisory body
has promoted the standardization and institutionalization of
political consultation, democratic supervision and participation
in the deliberation and administration of state affairs and
pushed forward its work actively, steadily and in an orderly way.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- The frontpage carried five photos on the First Session of
the Ninth National Committee of the CPPCC.
</P>
<P>
-- Chronical of events since the First Session of the Eighth
National Committee of the CPPCC was listed as one of the three
frontpage stories.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China welcomes the resolution passed yesterday by the UN
Security Council on ratifying the memorandum of understanding
signed between the UN and Iraq, a Foreign Ministry Spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
This will lay the foundation for resolving the Iraq weapons
inspection problem foundmentally, justly and reasonably in a
peaceful manner, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
-- Trade unions throughout China are doing more than fighting
for workers' rights -- they are helping needy families.
</P>
<P>
The organizations gave 1.5 billion yuan (180.7 million dollars)
to poverty-stricken families during the New Year's Day and Chinese
Spring Festival period.
</P>
<P>
-- China has announced a list of hazardous wastes -- the first
of its kind in the country.
</P>
<P>
The list -- prepared by the National Environmental Protection
Agency, the State Economic and Trade Commission and the Ministry
of Public Security -- takes effect on July 1.  
</P>
</TEXT>
