<HEADLINE> Philippine Government to Float Global Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government would
issue 500 million U.S. dollars worth of global bonds late this
month to boost the country's gross international reserve.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Daily Inquirer Wednesday quoted acting Finance
Secretary Cecilia Soriano as saying that Manila has chosen two
U.S.-based investment banks, Morgan Stanley and JP Morgan, to
float the bonds.
</P>
<P>
Soriano said that while the terms of the flotation have yet to
be finalized, the fresh government borrowings would likely carry a
maturity of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
She added that proceeds of the bond float would be deposited
with the central bank to beef up the country's gross international
reserve which currently stood at 9.3 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
A healthy gross international reserve level assures the market
of sufficient liquidity in times of a financial crunch.
</P>
<P>
Soriano said that the bond issuance would serve as a benchmark
for future investors to follow, expressing confidence that there
would be a strong appetite for Philippine debt papers in the
global market.
</P>
<P>
After the government's bond float, two Philippines companies,
the National Power Corp. and the Development Bank of the
Philippines, would also float bonds for refinancing purposes.
</P>
<P>
The government last entered the foreign capital market for
fresh borrowings when it successfully issued Samurai bonds in
Japan two years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
