<HEADLINE> Italian Prime Minister Visits Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi arrived in Sao Paulo Tuesday for a two-day visit to Brazil
after finishing his trip to Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is Prodi's second leg of his Latin American tour which
also includes Uruguay and Chile.
</P>
<P>
Prodi, accompanied by 50 businessmen, wishes to promote
economic and trade relations between Italy and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Italy is the sixth biggest market for Brazilian exports and the
fourth major foreign investor in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian Foreign Ministry said Brazil exported goods worth
1.7 billion U.S. dollars to Italy last year and imported 3.4
billion dollars worth of goods from the European country.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries increased from one billion
dollars in 1992 to 5.1 billion dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In Uruguay, during a meeting with President Julio Maria
Sanguinetti, Prodi said Italy would promote negotiations on a free
trade zone between the European Union and the Southern Common
Market (Mercosur), a regional economic bloc grouping Argentina,
Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay with Chile and Bolivia as the
associate members.
</P>
<P>
The Italian and Uruguayan governments signed a treaty for
reciprocal protection of investments.
</P>
<P>
Prodi announced that his country would install an industrial
plant in the free zone of Florida, Uruguay, with an investment of
20 million dollars. This would include the establishment of
companies to produce furniture with Uruguayan timber. 
</P>
</TEXT>
