<HEADLINE> Becker Pulls Out of Arizona for Back Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Boris Becker of Germany pulled
out of the 315,000 U.S. dollars Franklin Templeton Tennis Classic
on Tuesday in Scottsdale, the United States, because of a back
injury.
</P>
<P>
The former world number one was scheduled to play Germany's
Nicolas Kiefer, current German number one player who ranked 28th
in the world and seeded fourth in Scottsdale, in Tuesday's
first-round match.
</P>
<P>
Becker, six-time Grand Slam singles champion, lost his doubles
first-round match with partner Thomas Messmer to Americans Dave
Randall and Jack Waiter, 6-2, 6-0 in Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year-old, ranked 66th in the world currently, will be
replaced by Scott Draper of Australia, ranked 80th in the world.
</P>
<P>
Becker, who announced a half-retirement after last year's
U.S. Open, has captured 49 ATP singles titles, including three
Wimbledon trophies, two Australian crowns and one U.S. Open.
</P>
</TEXT>
