<HEADLINE> Sichuan Province Sets Goals for Agricultural Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Sichuan Province
is hoping to increase its agricultural output value by 5 percent
to 138.5 billion yuan this year.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the provincial goals for agricultural
development this year. The goals also include an increase of 250
million kilograms (kg) in its grain output, which is estimated at
35.76 billion kg this year.
</P>
<P>
Local farmers' per capita income is projected at 1,680 yuan for
1998, local sources said.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan, home of the late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping, is one
of China's leading agricultural provinces. It is also the most
populous province in west China with 83 million residents,
accounting for 6.8 percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
Though the province only has 6 percent of the country's
farmland, with a per capita farmland acreage of 0.05 hectares, it
is the most reliable production center for grain and non-staple
foodstuffs for west China, The province also ships surplus grain
to other parts of the country annually after feeding its local
populace.
</P>
<P>
Local governments at various levels have always placed
agriculture ahead of all other economic work and have been
persisting in a policy of maintaining grain production, expanding
into a diverse economy and developing rural industry. Sichuan
reported a record grain harvest of 35.5 billion kg last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
