<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama to Intensify Fight Against Dengue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Panamanian Health Minister
Aida Libia de Rivera today urged her people to destroy the
breeding places of the aedes aegypti mosquito -- the carrier of
the deadly dengue illness.
</P>
<P>
"If Panamanians do not try to eliminate the breeding places, we
will increase the risk of death," Libia de Rivera said.
</P>
<P>
Dengue, transmitted by the aedes aegypti mosquito which breeds
in stagnant water, is a tropical disease with symptoms of severe
pains and high fever.
</P>
<P>
The Health Minister said that a recent survey showed around
25,000 potential mosquito breeding spots have been located.
Destroying them would prevent the disease spreading in Panama.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
