<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest China Province Improving Irrigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's oldest
irrigation system, at Dujiangyan in Sichuan Province, has
completed its annual renovation.
</P>
<P>
The system, which is 55 kilometers from Chengdu, the provincial
capital, is more than 2,400 years old. China did some
reconstruction work on it in 1986, and again in 1991, and it now
covers 667,000 hectares of arable land, from plains to hilly
areas, in the largest irrigated area in the country.
</P>
<P>
The irrigated area feeds 18 percent of Sichuan's people with 14
percent of its arable land, and 22.3 percent of the grain produced
in Sichuan comes from Dujiangyan area. Its industrial and
agricultural output accounted for 60 and 30 percent of Sichuan's
total respectively.
</P>
<P>
The irrigation capacity of Dujiangyan is expected to reach
768,000 hectares in the first ten years of the next
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
