<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Mining Industry to Expand International Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Ministry of Geology
and Mineral Resources has Pledged to expand international
co-operation in the development of China's mineral industry this
year.
</P>
<P>
Such co-operation will focus more on the economic aspects,
rather than merely on technological exchanges, today's China Daily
quoted Minister Song Ruixiang as saying.
</P>
<P>
As part of this year's work schedule, the ministry plans to
continue tapping mineral resources in Africa, South America and
some of China's neighboring countries, Song said.
</P>
<P>
Minerals such as oil, copper, gold and sylvite will be the
targets.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the influx of overseas funds to the resource-rich
but less developed western parts of China will be encouraged.
</P>
<P>
As for international co-operation in technological issues, the
work will target a geological study on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau,
an underground water tapping program in northwest China and an
extensive adoption of updated geological technologies, Song said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attracted 11.44 million yuan (1.37 million US
dollars) last year to explore 20 varieties of minerals such as
gold and diamonds.
</P>
<P>
The country's mineral trade volume in 1997 reached 34.63
million yuan (4.17 million US dollars), up 77 percent from 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
