<HEADLINE> Ronaldo Scores to Give Inter First-leg Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Ronaldo's first-half goal gave Inter
Milan of Italy a 1-0 home victory over defending champions Schalke
04 of Germany in the UEFA Cup quarter-final first leg on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Atletico Madrid of Spain beat Aston Villa of England 1-0, Lazio
of Italy edged Auxerre of France 1-0, and Ajax Amsterdam of the
Netherlands lost to Spartak Moscow of Russia 3-1 in others.
</P>
<P>
In Milan, Ronaldo, the two-time Footballer of the Year, shot
past goalkeeper Jens Lehmann in the 16th minute with a left-footer
in the box after flicking passes with French international Youri
Djorkaeff.
</P>
<P>
The Germans, who beat Inter 4-1 in a penalty shootout in last
year's final, came close to level before halftime when striker
Martin Max's header bounced onto Gianluca Pagliuca's right-hand
post.
</P>
<P>
In Rome, subsititute Pierluigi Casiraghi scored the winner for
Lazio on his first touch after he rose from the bench for
midfielder Giorgio Venturin.
</P>
<P>
Casiraghi stole in when the French club's defenders misjudged
Czech Pavel Nedved's cross and rocketed into the net at the back
post in the 64th minute.
</P>
<P>
But the hosts had to scrap to hold onto their slim lead when
Yugoslav playmaker Vladimir Jugovic was expelled for a second
bookable offence two minutes later.
</P>
<P>
In Amsterdam, Alexander Shirko's double in 26th and 52th
minutes and Valery Kechinov's 84th-minute goal put Spartak the
driving seat in the two-leg playoffs.
</P>
<P>
Ajax had the better of the game but their finishes always fell
short while their opponents showed no mistake in fast
counter-attacks to pile up a 2-0 lead before Shota Arveladze
pulled one back for the hosts in the 57 minutes.
</P>
<P>
In Madrid, Atletico dominated most of the possession and their
efforts were paid off by Italian striker Christian Vieri's penalty
in the 41 minites after Jose Luis Caminero was bundled by Ian
Taylor in the box.
</P>
<P>
Stan Collymore was subsituted after 51 mintes for a leg
injury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
