<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Network Promotes Financial Sectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The second phase of the China
Financial Data Communication Backbone Network has passed
acceptance tests, paving the way for the country's financial
institutions and banks to share information on line, today's
"China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the Beijing-based newspaper, so far, altogether
200 nodes of China's National Financial Data Communication Network
(CNFN) spreading among 166 cities have been installed and
connected.
</P>
<P>
CNFN has become China's biggest Frame Relay network with 400
Frame Relays, over 2,600 user ports and 80 Megabyte total band
width.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the backbone network including 34 nodes was
completed in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
Since completion of the second phase on December 29, 1997, 101
users from eight financial institutions have used CNFN whose
monthly information processing reaches 370 billion bytes. The Bank
of China is a 24-hour customer of CNFN.
</P>
<P>
CNFN is capable of providing many applications including Local
Area Networks (LAN), IBM, SNA system networking, voice transfer on
Frame Relay, video conference transfers and virtual private
networks.
</P>
<P>
US-based Cisco, as the equipment provider of the first phase,
continued to participate in the second phase construction by
providing ATM facilities and network management system Strata View
Plus.
</P>
<P>
Yesterday, Cisco announced in Beijing the second stage of its
strategy to integrate data, voice and video traffic on a single
network infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
With multiservice support already built into its side area
network (WAN) systems, Cisco has added another piece of the total
solution by introducing new multiservice WAN access products and
outlined plans to continue its voice-over-IP product rollout.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that businesses will greatly reduce their costs
as network voice transfer enables them to pay long-distance calls
at a local phone rate. What's more, it provides better acoustic
effects, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Fast-track Setting Up of Loan-Loss Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 4 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the Philippines
will fast-track the banks' compliance to set aside an additional
two percent of their loan portfolio as a reserve against bad
loans.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Star reported on Wednesday that this was
revealed by Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson, who explained
that the setting up of the loan-loss reserve is part of government
effort to strengthen the banking sector in response to a growing
threat of bank failures.
</P>
<P>
Singson said he is set to talk anew with Deogracias Vistan,
president of the Bankers Association of the Philippines, about the
fast-tracking.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the central bank regulated that the banks must set
aside the two-percent loan-loss reserve within two years as a rise
in the bad loans of banks has been noted.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Deputy Governor Alberto Reyes said the
non-performing loans of the country's 56 commercial banks went up
to five percent of their total loan portfolio as of the end of
last year from the 3.91 percent posted last September.
</P>
<P>
Reyes had warned that if banks' bad loans continue to rise by
the first quarter this year, the central bank would be forced to
go ahead with its plan to speed up the compliance of banks to the
two-percent loan-loss reserve.
</P>
<P>
However, local bankers had expressed opposition to the plan,
saying it would only add "aggravation to an already pressured
market".
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that although the plan would strengthen the
banking sector's ability against non-performing loans, it would
reduce the banks' liquidity and lead to higher interest rates that
are plaguing the country's economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
