<HEADLINE> Foreign Experts Assist Beijing's Agricultural Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 4 (Xinhua) -- Some 70 foreign experts from more
than a dozen countries, including Japan, Germany, Canada and
Israel, came to Beijing last year to assist in the city's
agricultural development efforts.
</P>
<P>
The experts, accounting for 40 percent of the total foreign
experts invited to Beijing during the year, participated in
wide-ranging research related to aquatic and dairy products, fruit
trees, vegetables, flowers and poultry.
</P>
<P>
China and the Republic of Korea have established a joint wheat
research project, in addition to data banks related to
meteorology, soil conservation, plant protection and socioeconomic
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Foreign experts working with the Beijing Academy of
Agricultural Sciences introduced 34 new varieties of asparagus,
with 1998 plans calling for the new varieties to be planted on
some 100 hectares. The annual output value for related projects is
expected to hit 15 million yuan (180,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Canadian experts introduced advanced technology for controlling
diseases affecting poultry, with related efforts leading to a
significant reduction in the mortality rate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
