<HEADLINE> Two Million Shanxi Residents Rise above Poverty Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, March 4 (Xinhua) -- A total of 2.04 million poor
people living in rural areas of north China's Shanxi province now
have enough to eat and wear due to an anti-poverty program started
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
By 1993, Shanxi, a major coal producer in the country, had 3.81
million rural people suffering absolute poverty. These poor
people were mainly distributed in 50 counties of Taihang and
Luliang mountainous regions where natural conditions are harsh and
the agricultural foundation and infrastructure are poor.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, the central and provincial governments have
pumped in 2 billion yuan for poverty relief coupled with hundreds
of millions in funds raised by local governments at lower levels
for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
With the funds, residents of the impoverished areas have been
working hard to rebuild infrastructures, plant trees and cash
crops, improve agricultural production conditions and start new
factories.
</P>
<P>
The province has also selected and dispatched more than 24,000
government officials at different levels to poverty-stricken
villages to help the poverty elimination effort, while mobilizing
all forces of the society to join the aid program.
</P>
<P>
So far, all people suffering absolute poverty in 18 of the
province's 50 poor counties have risen above the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
In February of 1994, the Central Chinese Government announced a
major poverty relief plan of concentrating manpower, material and
funds on helping the country's 80 million impoverished people get
enough to eat and wear in the seven years beginning in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Because of these concerted efforts, the country's poor
population has been reduced to 58 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0344 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Lower Drinking Limit for Drivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Tuesday called for legislation to get states to lower their legal
limit for drinking for drivers.
</P>
<P>
At a White House ceremony, Clinton announced his support for an
amendment in Congress, under which states would be required to
lower to 0.08 percent the blood-alcohol level at which a driver is
declared legally drunk.
</P>
<P>
Clinton instructed Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater to
come up with a plan to make 0.08 percent the legal limit on all
federal property.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "To people who disregard the lethal threat they
pose when they drink and drive, lowering the legal limit will send
a strong message that our nation will not tolerate irresponsible
acts that endanger our children and our nation."
</P>
<P>
Most states use a more lenient limit of 0.10 or higher, and the
organization Mothers Against Drunk Driving (MADD) contends a
nationwide change to 0.08 would save hundreds of lives and prevent
thousands of injuries each year.
</P>
<P>
MADD representatives and highway safety advocates attended the
White House ceremony.
</P>
<P>
A recent MADD survey showed nearly seven in 10 Americans
favored a lower blood-alcohol limit. Researchers also said 53
percent of the 1,000 people surveyed said they considered drunken
driving to be the nation's No. 1 highway safety problem.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, more than 17,100 people died in alcohol-related
vehicle crashes nationwide, about 41 percent of all traffic
deaths, officials estimate. Of the total deaths, about 9 percent,
or more than 3,700, involved drivers with blood-alcohol levels
below the legal 0.10 percent limit.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of the amendment said studies showed that up to 600
lives could be saved annually with a national 0.08 percent law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
