<HEADLINE> World Bank Backs Second Education Project in Bhutan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Tuesday
announced the approval of a 13.7 million U.S. dollar equivalent
credit for a second education project to support the government's
drive to enroll all school-age children in Bhutan.
</P>
<P>
This project will focus on children from rural areas, where
access to higher grade levels is highly constrained. The resources
will be used to construct and upgrade schools, improve teacher
training, and strengthen management support for the system.
</P>
<P>
The credit is provided by the International Development
Association (IDA), the World Bank's concessionary lending arm for
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project is estimated at 21.2 million
dollars. In addition to the IDA credit, the Swiss Development
Cooperation will contribute 5.5 million dollars and the remaining
2.0 million dollars will come from the government.
</P>
<P>
Other ongoing World Bank activities in Bhutan include the third
forestry project approved in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
