<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Appeals Emergency Assistance for Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The UNICEF request for 4 million U.S. dollars follows four
weeks of shelling and street combat in the capital city of
Freetown. Calm has been restored in the capital, but skirmishes,
ambushes and looting continue in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
The destruction of basic infrastructure since last May's coup
d'etat has placed the country in a desperate situation.
Humanitarian programs in the relatively safe northern regions were
devastated by last month's fighting. Current assessment of living
standards in the southern and eastern areas of Sierra Leone reveal
grave health and nutritional conditions, according to UNICEF.
</P>
<P>
"Children have been specially affected," the coordinated UN
appeal says. "They have been exposed to acts of violence and
many were sent into battle as combatants, suffering deaths and
injuries." The trauma is even greater for those who have been
orphaned or displaced, the appeal says.
</P>
<P>
The recent fighting in the country is a continuation of the
civil strife that began in 1991, during which children were
commonly abducted and forced to join military units. By 1997,
children between the age of 7 and 14 reportedly constituted 80
percent of the rebel forces which helped to overthrow the
elected government.
</P>
<P>
Of more than 10,000 sierra Leoneans killed in the civil
conflict, half were children, and children comprise the majority
of the 20 percent of the population who were disabled by the
fighting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
