<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0350 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Panel Okays NATO Enlargement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Foreign
Relations Committee Tuesday approved expanding the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) to include Poland, Hungary and the
Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
Senators of the committee cleared the alliance's plan to
expand by a vote of 16-2 and the full Senate is to vote on it
within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
However, some senators expressed their reservations and
concerns about possible consequences of the move, including a
worse relationship with Russia and inefficiency of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
NATO leaders decided last July to accept Poland, Hungary and
the Czech Republic as new members by 1999. But the decision needs
to be ratified by all parliaments of the current 16 NATO members.
</P>
<P>
Denmark and Canada have ratified the treaty so far and a
two-thirds majority of vote is needed for an approval by the
U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that some members were still concerned about
the plan since the Cold War has ended, and it is not necessary for
the alliance to expand. However, they believe that ratification of
it is almost certain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
