<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Committee Approves NATO Enlargement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Foreign
Relations Committee Tuesday approved expanding the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) to include Poland, Hungary and the
Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
Senators of the committee cleared the alliance's plan to expand
by a vote of 16-2 and the full Senate is to vote on it within two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Chairman Jesse Helms of the committee expressed his optimism
about the ratification of the alliance's plan.
</P>
<P>
"It appears that Senate approval of this resolution will occur
on an overwhelmingly positive vote, which will be an obvious vote
of confidence in the democracies of Eastern Europe," Helms said.
</P>
<P>
However, some senators expressed their reservations and
concerns about possible consequences of the move, including a
worse relationship with Russia and inefficiency of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
Although the resolution approved by the committee does not put
limits on future NATO expansion, several senators were expected to
propose amendments for a hiatus during final debate on the issue.
</P>
<P>
One is a proposal by Sen. John Warner to bar any further NATO
additions for three years. NATO has agreed to consider the issue
of inviting additional members to join the alliance in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Paul Wellstone, who voted against the alliance's move, said he
feared an expanded NATO would result in the redivision of Europe
and poison future relations with Russia, which fears a creep of
the alliance toward its borders.
</P>
<P>
NATO leaders decided last July to accept Poland, Hungary and
the Czech Republic as new members by 1999. But the decision needs
to be ratified by all parliaments of 16 current NATO members.
</P>
<P>
Denmark and Canada have ratified the treaty so far and a
two-thirds majority of vote is needed for an approval by the U.S.
Senate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0353 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Arms Sales Total 8.8 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States arms sales
totaled 8.8 billion U.S. dollars in fiscal 1997, the lowest figure
in 10 years, the Arms Trade News reported in its February edition.
</P>
<P>
The figure, obtained by the Arms Trade News from the Pentagon's
Foreign Military Sales Program, also represents a 15 percent
decline from the 1996 sales due mainly to significant decrease of
purchases by some Middle East nations.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's purchases were 25 percent lower than 1996 levels,
dropping over 350 million dollars to 1.06 billion dollars. Arms
acquisitions by Israel and Saudi Arabia were reduced by more than
40 percent from 1996. Israel's purchases totaled 525 million
dollars, down 358 million dollars and that of Saudi Arabia fell
more than 550 million dollars to 742 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Further, Kuwait acquisitions dropped 80 percent compared to
1996 levels with contracts valued at just 48 million dollars in
1997. Jordan also reduced its purchases in 1997 by 92 percent to
18 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other large drops in procurement of U.S. weapons last year came
in Denmark, down 76 percent to 32 million dollars, and Norway,
down 87 percent to 64 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, Australia and some European nations increased
remarkably their arms imports from the United States in 1997.
Australia's acquisitions rose 66 percent to 288 million dollars
and Belgium doubled its contracts to 122 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
While France tripled its purchases to 102 million dollars in
1997, Spain's purchases were up more than six times its 1996
levels to a total of 828 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other traditional big purchasers of U.S. Arms were South Korea,
854 million dollars; Britain, 559 million dollars; Taiwan, 353
million dollars; Japan, 347 million dollars; Turkey, 339 million
dollars; Germany 325 million dollars. The Netherlands, 225 million
dollars and Greece 224 million dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0354 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: U.N. Resolution Provides Authority of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said
Tuesday that Iraq should be under no illusion about the meaning of
a U.N. Security Council resolution, which warns Iraq of "the
severest consequences" if it fails to comply with an agreement on
weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Iraq should be under no illusion. The
meaning of `severest consequences' is clear. It provides authority
of act if Iraq does not turn the commitment it has made into
compliance," Clinton said during an East Room ceremony about
combating drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
He said the Security Council vote Monday night on the
resolution set a clear message to Iraq that it must allow
inspections of suspected weapons sites "without obstruction or
delay, any place, any time, without any conditions, deadlines or
excuses."
</P>
<P>
Clinton warned Iraq that "no promise of peace and no policy of
patience can be without its limits."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, White House spokesman Mike McCurry said the "severest
consequences" contained in the Security Council resolution meant
Iraq would face military strikes if it failed to live up to the
agreement it reached last week with U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan on weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
"The United States clearly has stated, and the president has so
stated, that any reneging on the commitments Iraq has acknowledged
will lead to severest consequences, which very clearly means
military action," McCurry told reporters.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin also said the severest
consequences in the Security Council resolution was "the clearest
possible threat to use force that the Security Council has taken
since this crisis began last year."
</P>
<P>
"The world is now supporting a strong, clear threat that
military force will ensue if Iraq violates this agreement, and
that's why we think this resolution was so important," Rubin told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Bill Richardson, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations,
said the United States views the Security Council resolution as a
"green light" to attack Iraq if Clinton decides Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein wasn't living up to the agreement. His remarks came
as a majority of Security Council members said only the Security
Council had authority to determine if Iraq had broken its word.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William Cohen Tuesday announced in a
statement that the U.S. military will begin vaccinating 36,000
American troops in the Gulf this month against the deadly anthrax
biological agent as a "prudent action."
</P>
<P>
He said he had made the decision at the request of Marine Corps
Gen. Anthony Zinni, commander of U.S. forces in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
"After a careful review, I have concluded that vaccination
against anthrax is a safe, prudent force protection measure," he
said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
Zinni Tuesday told the Senate Armed Services Committee that
U.S. forces in the Gulf remained ready to act if necessary. "They
understand the mission and they are prepared to do what it takes."
</P>
</TEXT>
