<HEADLINE> Turkey Urges Kosovo Parties to Start Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkey on Tuesday called on all
parties in the Kosovo unrest to exercise restraint and settle
their disputes through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry issued a statement saying "Turkey regrets
that the clashes in Kosovo resulted in a loss of life," according
to the semi-official Anatolia news agency.
</P>
<P>
Large-scale clashes between ethnic Albanian civilians and
Serbian riot police were reported since last week in the southern
Yugoslavian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
At least 16 Albanians and four policemen were killed in the
bloody disturbances triggered by an alleged Albanian terrorist
ambush which claimed the life of a Serbian policeman on February
28.
</P>
<P>
Expressing concern over the Kosovo unrest, the statement urged
the parties to the conflict immediately start "a constructive
dialogue and find a peaceful and wise solution within the
framework of Yugoslavia's territorial integrity."
</P>
<P>
The basic rights and freedoms as well as ethnic, religious and
cultural identities of all the peoples living in Kosovo should be
respected and guaranteed, it said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, which had strong historical links with ethnic Albanians
in Kosovo, has been keeping a close military relationship with
Albania in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here noted that Ankara was anxious that the Kosovo
unrest could spread to the whole Balkans which was termed as "a
hotbed of war" in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Russia and the European Union have voiced
their grave concern about the tensions in Kosovo, demanding the
Yugoslav government deal with it in a cautious and proper
manner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
