<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0356 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Government Considers Further Crackdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The British government is
considering further strengthening the measures currently in place
for dealing with child pornography on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
A voluntary body called the Internet Watch Foundation (IWF) was
set up by the government and industry over a year ago to tackle
the growing problem of illegal material, chiefly child
pornography, posted on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
In its first annual report, the IWF said it had received 781
complaints referring to 4,300 items on the Net in the 12 months
since it established a complaints hotline.
</P>
<P>
Department of Trade and Industry minister Barbara Roche Tuesday
welcomed what the IWF has done but announced that the government
is to review the watchdog's role aimed at widening the work it
does.
</P>
<P>
"The Government is not complacent about illegal and harmful
material on the Internet and we intend to uphold the law on-line
as we do off-line." the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Almost 2,000 images of child pornography have been removed from
the Internet as a result of IWF's action, but as the IWF itself
acknowledged, the amount it catches is just a "very small
proportion" of the total available on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
There are an estimated 70,000 pornography sites on the Internet
and more are added each day.
</P>
<P>
To remove more of those illegal materials more quickly, the IWF
plans to patrol the Net itself rather than wait for complaints
from the public on its e-mail hotline.
</P>
<P>
It is also proposing a ratings system for the Internet, similar
to that for classifying films and videos.
</P>
<P>
However, many child protection groups claimed that the IWF can
only help to remove a small amount of child pornography, they said
that a specialized police unit is still needed.
</P>
<P>
Last week, London's Metropolitan Police Force announced that it
is considering prosecuting companies which provide Internet
services but fail to filter out illegal pornography.
</P>
<P>
The police are concerned about specific discussion forums,
known as news groups, which they believed are used by paedophiles
to exchange photographs and videos. The police said that they want
these news groups banned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
