<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0357 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Drug Sales Rise 6 Pct in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Drug sales in the world's 10
biggest markets rose 6 percent to 166 billion U.S. dollars last
year, according to figures published Tuesday by IMS International,
a specialist market research company.
</P>
<P>
The company said that compared with recent years, last year's
rise of drug sales was modest, mainly due to Japanest government
cost-control measures which led to a 1 percent fall in drug sales
in Japan to 41.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Figures showed that drug sales in Canada and the U.S. made the
biggest gains, rising 12 percent to 4.1 billion dollars and 10
percent to 66.5 billion dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
The fastest growing market in Europe was Spain, where sales
increased by 10 percent to 4.9 billion dollars. Then followed the
UK and the Netherlands, with sales up 7 percent to 7.7 billion
dollars and 1.9 billion dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Italy and France came in the third and fourth place, with sales
up 5 and 4 percent to 8.7 billion dollars and 13.7 billion dollars
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Sales in Germany rose only 2 percent to 14.7 billion dollars as
a result of the German government's control in drug costs.
</P>
<P>
By medical area, the fastest growing sector was nervous system
drugs, with sales rising 12 percent to 23.5 billion dollars. The
biggest single market was heart drugs, with sales up 6 percent to
33.8 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
