<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Voices Concern over Violence in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LONDON, March 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) voiced grave
concern Tuesday over the violent clashes in Kosovo, Serbia Republic of
Yugoslavia and urged all sides to refrain from further violence.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Office, whose country is the current EU president,
said in a statement issued early Tuesday, "The EU is deeply concerned
by the violent incidents in Kosovo over the past few days."
</P>
<P>
"The EU unreservedly condemns the violent repression of
non-violent expressions of political views as well as the use of force
and terrorism to achieve political goals," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The EU urges all sides to exercise restraint and refrain from
further violence, calls on the Serbian law enforcement agencies to
respect fully human rights and rule of law in pursuit of their
duties," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The statement also appealed to leaders from the Belgrade government
and the Kosovar Albanian community to resolve their differences
peacefully through a full and constructive dialogue.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that some 20 people have been killed in the
weekend violent clashes in central Kosovo, where 90 percent of its
population are ethnic Albanians.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
