<DOCNO> XIE19980304.0359 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-03 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Strives to Boost Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran is striving to rejuvenate its
tourism industry and raise tourism revenues to 1 billion
U.S. dollars next year from 260 million last year.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Deputy Cultural Minister Mohammad Moezeddin, in an
interview with Xinhua, said the prospect for Iran's tourism is
bright.
</P>
<P>
Iran is not matched in the world in terms of historic sites,
pre-Islamic civilization dating back to some 20,000 years ago,
varied topographies and beautiful natural scenes, said Moezeddin,
who is also the managing director of Iran's Tourism Organization.
</P>
<P>
About 460,000 foreign tourists visited Iran during the Iranian
year from March 21, 1996 to March 20, 1997, and the country earned
about 260 million U.S. dollars, said the Iranian official.
</P>
<P>
Moezeddin believed that the tourism revenue in the current year
would surely exceed 500 million dollars, and Iran has expected to
earn 1 billion dollars next year, since more foreign tourists are
drawn to this country.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian government has worked out a package plan to bolster
tourism through encouraging private sector to invest in tourism,
introducing Iran's tourism resources to the world and expanding
cooperation with international tourist agencies, Moezeddin said.
</P>
<P>
He rejected the claims that strict religious regulations have
obstructed the development of tourism in Iran, saying that many
western tourists have maintain that Iranian women with Hijab
(Islamic dress code) are wonderful sights for tourists.
</P>
<P>
Iran's goals to promote tourism are not only aimed at
increasing its revenues, but more importantly improving contacts,
exchanges and understanding between nations, Moezeddin said.
</P>
<P>
Through tourism nations will learn how to live with each other
peacefully, he pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
